<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Nuclear     09-15 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Nuclear,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Reported Concerned North Korea Developing Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is ``gravely
concerned'' that communist North Korea may be developing nuclear
weapons, the South Korean news agency Yonhap reported from
Washington on Friday.
   It said the State Department is keeping a close watch on possible
efforts in North Korea to develop nuclear weapons. Yonhap quoted
Spencer Richardson, the head of the department's Korea section, as
saying Moscow would be as concerned as Washington if North Korea
produced such weapons.
   Secretary of State James Baker is expected to discuss North
Korea's nuclear capability with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze at a meeting in the United States this month, Yonhap
reported.
   While denying it has nuclear weapons, North Korea has repeatedly
charged that U.S. forces based in South Korea are equipped with
nuclear arms and are preparing for a nuclear war on the divided
Korean peninsula. U.S. officials reject the North Korean claims.
   The United States keeps about 43,000 troops in South Korea under
a defense pact. The Soviet Union is the North's main arms supplier.
   Chances are dim for an improvement soon in the strained relations
between the United States and North Korea despite diplomatic
contacts between the two sides in Beijing, the report quoted
Richardson as saying.
   North Korea demands immediate withdrawal of U.S. troops from
South Korea. Seoul says U.S. forces are vital to prevent a North
Korean attack.
   North Korea invaded South Korea in 1950, setting off the 3-year
Korean War. U.S. forces intervened on the side of South Korea and
fought under the United Nations banner. U.S. troops have remained in
the South ever since.
</TEXT>
