<DOCNO> AP890915-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Settlers     09-15 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Settlers,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Settlers Face Problems from Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT ARYEH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish settlers in the
occupied West Bank say they are trapped between stone-throwing Arabs
and an indecisive government.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began 21 months ago, nails have
been strewn on their roads and their cars are targets of stones and
firebombs. Glass window panes have been replaced with plastic and
travel is often safest in convoy.
   The settlers complain bitterly that the government is torn on how
to put down the uprising and, indeed, on the future of the occupied
land itself. The result, they say, is that the army is not doing
enough to protect them.
   ``Of course I am fearful,'' settler Mark Barat told visitors to
this fenced, hilltop settlement east of Tel Aviv. ``If there is
debate in Israel, it undercuts us.''
   Barat, 40, a computer scientist, is among more than 70,000 Jews
who have moved to the West Bank and Gaza Strip since the territories
were captured by Israel from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle
East war.
   Some are ``ideological'' settlers, convinced that Jews must
reclaim the biblical land of Israel. Others, like Barat, see
themselves as part of a front line against a Palestinian state.
Still others are lured by the promise of free land and subsidized
mortgages.
   Settlers have become targets in the uprising since many
Palestinians see them as one more encroachment on Arab land. Almost
half the 1.7 million Palestinians in the territories are refugees
whose families fled Israel when it was founded in 1948.
   The settlers say the army, which recently began deploying extra
troops along highways and stepped up escorts for settler convoys at
night, still needs to do more.
   ``Instead of soldiers killing mosquito after mosquito, let them
drain the swamp,'' said Kiryat Arba lawyer Eliyakim Haetzni, a
leader of the settlers' umbrella group, Gush Emunim, or Bloc of the
Faithful.
   ``We demand the deportation of 5,000 people _ members of the PLO
establishment, stone-throwers and their families _ to show them that
stone throwing is not a national sport,'' Haetzni said.
   ``Arabs must know that they can live here only if we can live
here.''
   Some Jewish settlers have poisoned Arab vineyards, raided
villages and fired on suspected stone throwers, killing at least 23
Palestinians in the past 21 months.
   Tensions also have increased because of the government's proposal
for elections in the territories leading to an interim peace
solution.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has repeatedly said he will refuse
to give up any occupied land, and his right-wing Likud bloc urges
creation of more Jewish communities in the territories.
   But the left-leaning Labor Party, partner in the coalition
Cabinet with Likud, advocates trading land for peace and calls for
suspending the creation of more settlements if peace talks get under
way.
   The 130 settlements built so far run counter to the U.S.-backed
land-for-peace solution, which the Palestinians demand.
   By far the largest number of settlers live in communities close
to the pre-1967 border. Some of the settlements deeper in the
territories have populations of only several hundred people.
   Meron Benvenisti, an Israeli analyst who has studied development
in the territories for a decade, notes that more than three-quarters
of the settlers live within commuting distance of Jerusalem or Tel
Aviv.
   ``They have come to see themselves as suburbanites of the major
cities,'' he said.
   Benvenisti said the settlements depend heavily on government
subsidies for survival.
   He calculates that the government and the World Zionist
Organization have spent $2.5 billion in the past 20 years building
the new communities, providing basic services like water and roads
and resettling Jewish families.
   Settlers often live rent-free in mobile homes while they build
their houses. There is no cost for the land. Mortgages are
subsidized, and fees for sewer and water connections are
considerably less than in Israeli towns.
   The goverment plans at least seven new settlements by 1992, but
budget constraints have forced the focus of late on trying to
increase the population in existing communities.
   The number of new settlers fell to 4,500 last year from an
average of 8,000 in previous years, apparently because of fears over
the uprising, said Michael Dekel, the prime minister's adviser on
settlement affairs.
   But settlement advocates hope the trend can be reversed. Dekel
predicted that the Jewish population in the territories would reach
125,000 in five years, even if the Arab revolt continues. ``People
have become used to the uprising,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
