<FIRST>r a PM-MissAmerica-G-String     09-15 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss America-G-String,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>G-String Pageant Competing with Miss America</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miss America Pageant is playing
down the swimsuit competition this year, but a competitor hopes to
draw viewers interested in more flesh.
   The Platinum Doll Bikini Contest, with comedian John Byner as
host, is one in a series of naughty contests that have sprung up
over the years to counter the pageant's wholesome image.
   Today's contest features 36 go-go girls from Florida, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania and New York, said contest producer Neil Cirucci.
   Instead of the scholarship offered by the Miss America program,
the go-go girls will be competing for a $10,000 cash prize and the
``platinum G-string award,'' Cirucci said. The second-prize winner
gets $5,000 and third prize is $3,000. Fourth- and fifth-place
runners-up get trips to Mexico.
   The contestants were auditioned by the contest organizers _ not
selected in state ``pageants'' _ and no interview was required, he
said. No evening gowns in this contest _ a selection of costumes
will be stripped off to reveal halters and G-strings.
   ``We have one girl wearing a nun outfit, another who's a cowboy,
one who will be a nurse,'' he said.
   The winner will not be serenaded by ``There She Is'' but instead
will dance down the stage to ``a good rock 'n' roll band,'' Cirucci
said.
   ``We hope to steal some thunder away from the Miss America
Pageant,'' Cirucci said.
   Leonard Horn, director of the venerable Miss America Pageant,
which crowns Miss America on Saturday night, called the G-string
contest ``ludicrous'' and said it will not take away his audience.
   ``It doesn't mean a thing to us,'' he said. `It's somebody just
trying to exploit us, and it will not affect us at all.''
   Judges for the Platinum Doll Bikini Contest include former
Philadelphia Phillies pitcher Larry Christensen; Tony Bongiovi,
uncle of rock star Jon Bon Jovi and owner of a recording studio; and
Gennaro Meoli, a fashion designer for Frank Sinatra, Cirucci said.
   The G-string contest is not the first time a promoter has tried
to strip away some of the Miss America Pageant's luster. In the
1970s, several Miss Nude USA pageants were held the week before Miss
America.
   The G-string contest was to be held at a Boardwalk nightclub.
