<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Court-Boots     09-15 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Court-Boots,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Boots Were Definitely On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one would be caught outside in the upstate
New York winter without boots on, a state appeals court decided in
upholding the conviction of a man who kicked and injured another
person.
   Thomas Bidwell, who was convicted of assault with a dangerous
instrument, claimed there was no proof he was wearing shoes at the
time of the Dec. 29, 1984, fight in Binghamton.
   ``We disagree,'' said presiding Justice A. Franklin Mahoney of
the Appellate Division of the state Supreme Court in Thursday's
unanimous decision. ``The incident occurred at the end of December
and there was testimony that the temperature was cold, thereby
foreclosing the possibility that the attacker had bare feet.''
   The court also noted that Bidwell's brother testified that
Bidwell was wearing cowboy boots. The victim in the attack required
70 stitches, the court said.
</TEXT>
