<FIRST>r a PM-RobinsAppeal     09-15 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robins Appeal,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Asked to Hear Challenge in Dalkon Shield Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of women has appealed to the U.S.
Supreme Court to review A.H. Robins Co.'s reorganization plan and
its $2.5 billion settlement for victims of the Dalkon Shield
birth-control device.
   The appeal was filed Thursday _ the deadline for opponents of the
Richmond-based company's bankruptcy reorganization plan to challenge
the plan to compensate about 195,000 women who claimed injuries from
the intrauterine device marketed by the company in the early 1970s.
   Douglas E. Bragg, a Denver attorney for more than 100 Dalkon
Shield appellants, said the $2.5 billion trust fund to pay claimants
is inadequate. He said full payment of claims could cost as much as
$7 billion.
   But the director of the Dalkon Shield Victims Association said
the appeal may cause some Dalkon claimants to wonder if they will
ever get paid.
   ``I'm worried mostly that women will lose heart,'' said Linda
Hightower. ``There have been so many delays. It's very difficult for
them to understand.''
   More than 94 percent of the claimants voted in favor of the
reorganization plan, confirmed by U.S. District Judge Robert R.
Merhige Jr. But about 900 women had rejected the plan, which was
upheld in June by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Alan B. Morrison, lead attorney for opponents of the
reorganization, said his clients object to the plan's prohibition on
the filing of separate lawsuits against Robins' corporate officers
and other third parties.
   But Ms. Hightower and company officials said the appeal will only
cause further delays.
   ``While I understand their reasoning it's very difficult to
explain when we have a good plan and most of these women have
already waited 18 years,'' Ms. Hightower said by telephone from her
home in Atlanta. ``I'm very upset by it because it means a delay to
all of the women.''
   Roscoe E. Puckett, a Robins spokesman, said the company also
regretted the appeal because it would delay compensation to
claimants. Puckett has said the trust could have been funded by
Sept. 28 if no further appeals had been filed.
   Robins has until Oct. 16 to file a response to the appeal with
the Supreme Court, after which the court will decide whether to
review the case.
   The reorganization plan was worked out over a three-year period
after Robins sought Chapter 11 protection from creditors in August
1985.
   The reorganization plan also included the acquisition of Robins,
through a $700 million exchange of stock, by the American Home
Products Corp. of New York.
   When Robins filed for protection, the company had settled about
two-thirds of approximately 15,000 lawsuits brought by women who
alleged injuries ranging from infections to sterility to miscarriage
from using the IUD.
   Under the reorganization plan, the $2.5 billion fund to pay
Dalkon Shield claims will be administered by trustees independent of
Robins. The plan also includes full payment to Robins' other
creditors.
   Pending a resolution of appeals, only $100 million of the trust
has been available to settle claims. As of this week, $52.8 million
had been paid to settle more than 81,000 claims, said Tom Morris, a
spokesman for the trust.
</TEXT>
