<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     09-15 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Department Defends Plan to Boost Wheat Plantings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodity analysts in the Agriculture
Department believe wheat farmers won't go overboard in signing up
for a new option designed to boost 1990 production.
   The option announced this week by Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter would let a farmer boost plantings by as much as 10 percent
from what otherwise would be allowed by the 1990 program.
   Yeutter said the increase is needed to help rebuild U.S. food
stockpiles, including a special ``food security reserve'' to meet
global food aid requirements.
   But some members of Congress fear production might rise more
sharply than USDA projects and push down market prices. And the
National Association of Wheat Growers has reservations about the
plan.
   William E. Penn, assistant deputy administrator for state and
county operations in the department's Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service, said the program contains ``some down sides''
that could discourage wheat farmers from planting too much wheat.
   The 1990 wheat program without the option calls for farmers to
idle 5 percent of their base acreage to qualify for price support
benefits. This ``acreage reserve'' program feature means farmers can
plant wheat on 95 percent of their base.
   With the option announced by Yeutter, producers can sign up to
plant wheat on more than 95 percent of their land _ up to 105
percent, or 10 percent more than they otherwise would be permitted
under the basic 1990 program.
   But Penn noted for ``every acre that you go over your normal
(base), you take an acre cut in the acres eligible for payment''
under the program's target-price formula.
   Another dampener, he said Thursday in a telephone interview, is
that the additional acres will not be counted as planting history
for the purpose of adjusting wheat bases in the future.
   ``So, if you plant 101 percent, you're not going to get credit
for that 1 percent as wheat for the purpose of calculating the base
for next year,'' Penn said.
   The signup for 1990 commodity programs will be held January 16
through April 13 at county ASCS offices, Penn said. Farmers will be
able to decide then whether to participate in the optional wheat
program.
   Meanwhile, wheat-state congressmen said the USDA's decision could
weaken prices and hurt producers in some regions.
   Rep. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., whose state is the leading wheat
producer, said the move could send farmers ``back down the road of
low prices and overproduction.''
   Rep. Bob Smith, R-Ore., complained ``now is not the time to
gamble with wheat farmers' income.''
   Although the nation's wheat stockpiles have dropped because of
two years of drought, Roberts and Smith said USDA was overreacting
to the lower inventories.
   ``It's risky, very risky,'' said Smith. ``If increased crops do
not result in a significant price drop, then wheat farmers might
benefit. But that's assuming a lot. Basic laws of supply and demand
would dictate that the price could fall.''
   Roberts said the USDA option would come too late for some winter
wheat producers to alter their planting preparations, especially if
they had grown fall-harvested grain sorghum or soybeans after their
wheat crop failed earlier this year because of drought.
   Farmer are planting winter wheat now for harvest next year. It
accounts for about three-fourths of the U.S. wheat total.
   ``Change for the sake of change to this degree is just going to
confuse farmers and irritate them, to say the least. And it's done
just that,'' said Roberts.
   The U.S. wheat carryover at the beginning of the current
marketing year on June 1 was about 694 million bushels, down from
1.261 billion bushels on June 1, 1988, and 1.821 billion bushels on
June 1, 1987.
   According to USDA projections, the carryover may be down to 494
million bushels by next June 1. Despite a larger harvest this year,
demand for wheat continues to outstrip production.
   Department analysts say the 1990 option is expected to boost the
acreage for harvest by 2.1 million acres to an estimated 69.6
million acres. As a result, they say, the 1990 harvest would rise
only 66 million bushels to 2.596 billion bushels.
   The National Association of Wheat Growers was less critical of
the USDA announcement, but association president Reggie Wyckoff said
U.S. export efforts should be stepped up if plantings increase.
   Producers ``want to be assured that they won't be caught holding
a mountain of surplus grain if this experiment fails,'' Wyckoff, a
Genoa, Colo., wheat farmer, said in a statement issued by the
association's Washington office.
</TEXT>
