<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Refugees-Pollution     09-15 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-Pollution,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Bring Pollution to West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASSAU, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of East German refugees have
driven into this country in a cloud of pollution from their tiny,
exhaust-belching cars.
   The East German Trabants have two cylinders and run on a mixture
of gasoline and oil.
   The cars do not meet West Germany's strict emission control laws,
and the environmental Green party says one should be put in a museum
with a sign: ``Forest Killer'' and the rest sent to the scrap heap.
   West German transportation officials have been issuing special
permits to allow the East Germans to drive the rickety
plastic-and-fiberglass cars.
   But the Greens object to a plan by the federal Transport Ministry
to give wholesale exemptions to the new drivers.
   Instead, they say the government should hand out annual federal
railway passes, worth about $4,000 each, in exchange for the
Trabants.
   ``We're going to have to come up with some imaginative solutions
to this problem,'' said Erhard Jauck, a spokesman for the Bavarian
Interior Ministry. East Germans typically wait more than 11 years
for a Trabant and more than 14 years for the larger Wartburg sedans
some refugees drive.
   But after they become established in West Germany, most refugees
probably will get rid of their cars.
   Some will do so for reasons other than pollution, however.
   West Berlin is surrounded by East German territory, and many of
the refugees who want to settle in the city are reluctant to drive
their car _ which still carry East German license plates _ 70 miles
across their homeland to reach West Berlin.
</TEXT>
