<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DropoutRates     09-15 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dropout Rates,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hispanics Most Likely to Drop Out of School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high school dropout rate for Hispanics is
nearing ``a national tragedy,'' says Education Secretary Lauro
Cavazos who points to a new study showing dropout rates for other
students have fallen in the last decade.
   Cavazos said the study released Thursday by the National Center
for Education Statistics disputes the popular perception that
overall dropout rates have been rising.
   But he said statistics on Hispanics are troubling because they
show one-third of all Hispanics aged 16 to 24 were not enrolled in
school and were not high school graduates last year.
   The report, ``Dropout Rates in the United States: 1988,'' showed
4.4 percent of students in grades 10 through 12 dropped out of high
school annually in the years 1985-1988, down from 6.6 percent in
1978. Nearly 13 percent of all 16- to 24-year-olds were not in
school and had not completed school last year, down from 16 percent
in 1968.
   ``While the report shows some progress,'' Cavazos said, ``I find
much in it alarming. The nation cannot rest any easier based upon
our findings.
   ``As of 1988, 4.2 million young adults were without a high school
diploma. While overall rates may be down slightly, ... for our
Hispanic population, the dropout problem is a national tragedy.
One-third of Hispanic young adults were not high school graduates in
1988,'' said Cavazos, the first Hispanic to head the department.
   Overall, the dropout rates were 15 percent for whites, 22 percent
for blacks and 28 percent for Hispanics. The majority of dropouts
are whites, who accounted for 66 percent of all young adults without
diplomas.
   The dropout rates for American Indians and Alaskan natives were
35 percent, while those for Asian students were 8 percent.
   Cavazos said the ``glimmer of hope in the report is that the
disparity between white and black students has narrowed.'' The
report showed dropout rates for whites and blacks are similar when
individual and family backgrounds are taken into account, such as
the rates for blacks and whites living in central cities and those
living in suburbs.
   The center tracked a sample of students who were high school
sophomores in 1980 and found 17 percent had not graduated by 1982.
However, 46 percent of these dropouts had completed school by 1986.
   The study was required by the Hawkins-Stafford Elementary and
Secondary School Improvement Amendments of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
