<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NewDestroyer     09-15 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Destroyer,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipbuilder Says Destroyer is Ready to Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon officials and the manufacturer of the
Navy's new $1.2 billion destroyer are disputing charges the ship is
a ``procurement nightmare'' of cost overruns and schedule delays.
   ``The ship is ready in every respect to be launched,'' William E.
Haggett, chairman and chief executive officer of Bath Iron Works,
said Thursday.
   Haggett spoke after Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the
House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on oversight and
investigations, wrote the Navy complaining the program is 18 months
behind schedule and the DDG-51 destroyer that Bath Iron Works will
launch Saturday is only 38 percent complete.
   ``The ship has suffered huge overruns, with the design costs
increasing by about 120 percent; and construction costs have
increased by more than 60 percent,'' Dingell said in a Sept. 12
letter to Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III.
   Hailed as the world's most advanced surface combat ship, the
guided-missile destroyer is designed with a more expensive all-steel
superstructure instead of one that was part aluminum and more prone
to splintering and fire damage. It will be equipped with
sophisticated Aegis computers and Tomahawk cruise missiles.
   According to Dingell's letter, design costs have increased from
the original contract estimate of $111 million to $247 million and
construction costs have grown from $157 million to $252 million.
   A total of 760 change orders have been made, he said. One
involved the combat system and included 44 modifications to the
original ship design requiring revisions to 30 to 40 percent of the
ship's drawings.
   Dingell based his charges on a draft report from the General
Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, which is
conducting an inquiry into the program. The GAO's final report is
expected later this year.
   ``The acquisition of the DDG-51 has turned into a procurement
nightmare,'' Dingell said in the letter.
   Haggett called Dingell's assessment a ``distortion of the overall
picture on the destroyer program'' and ``factually incorrect.'' Navy
Cmdr. Mark Baker said the service ``considers the program well under
control in both cost and schedule.''
   ``This launching represents the normal progression in the
construction, equipment activation and test plan. The remaining work
on the ship requires the ship to be afloat,'' Baker said in a
statement.
   According to Baker, the production schedule calls for the ship to
be delivered in February 1991. The original delivery date of October
1989 was changed due to a 99-day strike at Bath Iron Works in 1985,
a requirement of additional Navy testing of the combat system and
problems with computer-aided design.
   Haggett said the DDG-51 is ``47 to 51 percent complete, a higher
level than we launched our previous prototype ship.'' He disputed
Dingell's total of 760 change orders, saying the actual number is
less than 300.
   Haggett also questioned Dingell's claim that the company has
petitioned the Navy for an $85 million bailout or threatened to go
bankrupt. ``We repeatedly told the Navy that this company is
financially viable,'' Haggett said in a telephone interview from
Bath, Maine.
   Dingell also said Bath Iron Works, despite four years of work on
the design and construction of the destroyer, still has not supplied
the Navy with a validated design and production drawings.
   ``The design is in excellent condition. We have over 3,000
drawings,'' Haggett said.
   Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla., chairman of the House Armed
Services subcommittee on seapower and strategic and critical
materials, played down the charges raised by Dingell.
   ``I don't see anything very scandalous,'' Bennett said in an
interview. ``It still will be the best ship of its class in the
world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
