<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-TaxBill-Glance     09-15 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill-Glance,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Capital Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some of the major
provisions of the bill approved late Thursday by the House Ways and
Means Committee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CAPITAL GAINS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The bill would reduce the maximum tax rate on profits from the
selling of capital assets, such as real estate and stocks.
   Through the end of 1991, the current 33 percent top rate would be
reduced to 19.6 percent. The rate would then be raised to 28 percent
and the basis of assets ``indexed'' so that profit caused entirely
by inflation would not be taxed.
   The change is expected to bring the Treasury additional revenue
in the next three fiscal years _ $2.9 billion in fiscal 1990, $3.8
billion in fiscal 1991, and $2.7 billion in fiscal 1992 _ as people
take advantage of the lower rate and increase their capital activity.
   After the initial increase, the government's intake would drop
sharply with losses of more than $5 billion projected for fiscal
years 1993 and 1994.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CATASTROPHIC HEALTH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In response to complaints from the elderly, the bill would cut in
half the surtax paid by the wealthiest 40 percent of retirees and
increase the flat monthly catastrophic premium paid by all but the
poorest Medicare beneficiaries.
   The bill would allow retirees to turn down catastrophic coverage
_ but only if they opt to drop out of Medicare Part B, the program
which pays physicians' fees.
   Aside from the catastrophic coverage, the bill would restrain
scheduled increases in payments to providers of Medicare services, a
spending cut of about $2.7 billion.
   It also would increase to $10,440 by 1991 the amount that a
Social Security recipient may earn without having benefits reduced.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHILD CARE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An additional $16 billion in tax credits and state-administered
grants would be provided to lower-income families over the next five
years to help improve child care for working parents.
   The major change would liberalize the earned-income credit, which
benefits lower-income working families with children. The credit
would be worth more to larger families; it could range up to $1,790
a year for those with three or more children. A new credit of up to
$430 a year would help families with children under the age of 6.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CORPORATE TAXES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The bill includes about $6.3 billion in net revenue increase for
fiscal 1990, including the capital gains cut.
   Significant among the others are repeal the completed-contract
method of accounting, by which big defense contractors may defer
taxes; eliminate special tax benefits for banks that lend money to
Employee Stock Ownership Plans, and end an interest break on big
banks' large loans to developing countries.
   The bill would also require companies to more quickly give the
government the payroll taxes they withhold from employees.
   The bill would effectively repeal a 1986 tax law provision, known
as Section 89, aimed at ensuring that employer-financed health plans
do not discriminate in favor of higher-paid employees. Businesses
contended compliance with the law was an onerous burden.
   An amendment approved Thursday would extend the 25 percent
deduction for health insurance premiums paid by self-employed
workers, which was due to expire this year.
   That extension was tied a measure that would restrict refunds of
interest deductions related to leveraged buy-outs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EXCISE TAXES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The bill would cancel a scheduled reduction in the 8 percent tax
on airline tickets and 5 percent tax on air freight.
   The 3 percent federal tax on telephone service, which is
scheduled to expire at the end of next year, would be made permanent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OZONE LAYER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The bill would levy $4.3 billion in new taxes over the next five
years on profits of companies making ozone-depleting chemicals.
   The Bush administration sought the revenue-raising measure, which
targets windfall profits that chemical firms could earn after an
international treaty reduces supplies of chlorofluorocarbons. The
chemical industry denies there will be windfall profits.
   The so-called CFC's destroy the ozone layer in the stratosphere
and increase risk of skin cancer. A similar provision is pending
before the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
