<DOCNO> AP890915-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0309EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BlackCaucus     09-15 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Caucus,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Black Caucus Celebrates its Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black members of Congress _ who in 20 years
have moved from outsiders demanding black power to insiders wielding
it _ are celebrating their successes this week while considering how
best to use a $2 million war chest.
   The money, much of it raised from corporate donors, was not on
the formal agenda for the Congressional Black Caucus' annual
``Legislative Weekend'' that opened Thursday and runs through
Saturday night.
   But it was a matter of behind-the-scenes debate among the 23
blacks who are members of Congress, as they were joined by thousands
of black political elite from around the country for the gala
fund-raiser, social event and policy discussion.
   Rep. Kweisi Mfume, a second-term Democrat representing Baltimore,
Md., who adopted an African name, said the 23 black members of
Congress are considering several proposals for spending the money.
Among them are to establish a think tank doing black-oriented
research, a recruitment center aimed at developing black political
candidates, and even a computerized library on African-American
culture.
   ``We ought to make ourselves more effective'' with the money,
Mfume said.
   A $300-a-plate black-tie dinner Saturday night is expected to
attract 4,000 guests, and more than 20,000 people will participate
in related events, including a black fashion show and numerous
parties.
   The Congressional Black Caucus is hosting the three-day session
at a time when black political leaders have successes to celebrate,
such as the victory in Tuesday's New York Democratic mayoral primary
of black candidate David Dinkins, and the candidacy in Virginia of
Democratic nominee Douglas Wilder, who seeks to become the first
black elected governor.
   Blacks in Congress are enjoying unprecedented power, too. Much of
it is the result of advances through the seniority system that
awards power to the most veteran members _ the same system that once
benefited white Southern conservatives who were re-elected with
little opposition time after time.
   Their numbers have grown since the Congressional Black Caucus was
formed in 1970, when there were 13 members. But more importantly,
caucus members now hold the chairmanships of five House committees
and 18 subcommittees, and young black newcomers are working their
way up some of the most influential congressional committees.
   ``The staying power of their members and the number of
chairmanships that they have make them an effective force,'' said
former Rep. James Jones of Oklahoma, who is white.
   One member, Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., has leapfrogged ahead,
serving last term as Budget Committee chairman and winning the House
Democrats' No. 3 leadership position this year as majority whip.
   The rise in power is limited to the House, however. The Senate
has no black members.
   The number of blacks in Congress has at least temporarily
declined with the death in an African plane crash last month of Rep.
Mickey Leland, D-Texas. Leland was mourned at several of the caucus'
opening events.
   President Bush earlier this year hosted the caucus at the White
House _ its first invitation there in eight years.
   In addition to the chance to discuss issues, members estimate
this year's Legislative Weekend event will raise $1 million for the
Congressional Black Caucus Foundation, a legally separate entity
with interlocking board members.
   With corporations donating sums of $50,000 in some cases, income
in recent years has exceeded spending on fellowships, internships
and scholarships, allowing the foundation to purchase its own
building and to accumulate a reserve of just over $2 million,
according to foundation financial records for the year ending Dec.
31, 1988.
   Another issue under debate by black members involves whether the
caucus should continue accepting large contributions to the
foundation from tobacco companies and liquor manufacturers, which
some members feel are contributing to health problems within the
black community. The caucus lists companies including Philip Morris,
RJR Nabisco, Anheuser-Busch, Courvoisier Cognac VSOP, Stroh Brewery
and Seagram Co. among its major contributors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0033 </DOCNO>
