<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Diabetes-Shoes     09-15 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Diabetes-Shoes,570</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Critics Say Federal Study Denies Many Diabetics ^By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government study in which expensive
orthopedic shoes will be bought for some diabetic Medicare patients
but not others is being criticized for jeopardizing health in the
name of medical economics.
   ``I consider it morally reprehensible'' to not provide the shoes
to some diabetics at high risk of foot amputations, said Stan Matek,
executive director of the New York State Podiatric Medical
Association.
   But project staff members say no one is being denied anything.
Rather, some Medicare recipients are getting something extra and
that the benefits of the study will reach all such patients, they
say.
   Under the study that began last month, Medicare is choosing
27,000 diabetic patients in New York, California and Florida who
have a high risk of hospitalization or amputation because of
circulatory problems in their feet. Half will be reimbursed for up
to $305 for a pair of therapeutic shoes or inserts, but the other
half will not, though they can still buy the footwear.
   The idea is to determine if the government would save money in
the long run by providing shoes to such patients.
   About 20,000 diabetics each year have parts of their legs and
feet removed. Many experts say specially-fitted shoes have been
shown to prevent the problems that lead to amputations.
   Matek said he finds it ``morally unacceptable to deny a
recognizably beneficial intervention to one out of every two people
at high risk for amputation.''
   And he says since Medicare patients in the study who are not
reimbursed can still buy the shoes, there's no point in doing a
cost-effectiveness comparison.
   But Judith Wooldridge, project director at Mathematica, a
Princeton, N.J., health policy study group commissioned by the
Health Care Financing Administration to do the study, dismisses the
ethical concerns as illogical.
   ``They interpret it as someone being denied something. But no one
is going to be denied anything. Some are going to receive something
extra,'' she said.
   The legislation that called for the study says the benefit will
not go into effect if the study shows money would not be saved in
the long run by paying for the shoes.
   Wooldridge and others in all likelihood therapeutic footwear for
diabetics will become a covered Medicare benefit, at least by 1993.
   The bill originally made the shoes a covered benefit but got
caught in the budget squeeze after the stock market crash in October
1987. Backers in Congress compromised to save the bill by calling
for a study to verify claims it would save $25 million a year by
avoiding costly hospitalizations and amputations.
   Sidney Trieger, director of the division of health systems and
special studies in HCFA's office of demonstrations, said, ``when
Congress says do a demonstration, that means there will be certain
people who get the benefit and certain people who don't.''
   About 2,500 podiatrists and other physicians in the three states
have expressed willingness to participate so far.
   Dr. Stephen Meritt, a Jacksonville, Fla., podiatrist who is
president of the Florida Podiatric Medical Association, said he will
participate in the study, though he is concerned patients who need
the shoes will hold off buying them until they find out whether
Medicare will pay for them.
   ``I'm going to recommend that they get the shoe'' regardless of
whether the government will pay, he said. ``I don't want my patients
waiting on the government. That could be hazardous, and that
concerns me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
