<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MinimumWage     09-15 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Wage Hike Opposed by Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats are gearing up for another
battle with President Bush over the minimum wage, offering to accept
his $4.25 hourly floor but refusing Bush's call for a lower pay
scale for all new hires.
   The House Education and Labor Committee's labor standards
subcommittee on Thursday approved on a 7-4, party-line vote a plan
to raise the $3.35-an-hour wage floor by 45 cents this January and
by another 45 cents in January 1991.
   But the panel refused to expand provisions in a bill vetoed by
Bush in June that would allow employers to continue paying a $3.35
minimum only to people beginning their first job and only for the
first 60 days of their employment.
   Bush has said he would veto the bill again if it phases in the
increase to $4.25 in less than three years. He also insists that a
lower ``training wage'' be allowed for six months for any person
newly hired, regardless of their previous work experience.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said in a letter to the panel
Wednesday to that the compromise offer put together by Chairman
Austin Murphy, D-Pa., with support from the AFL-CIO ``continues to
be unacceptable to the president, and would call for a veto.''
   Rep. Thomas E. Petri of Wisconsin, the subcommittee's ranking
Republican, said minimum wage advocates should accept the proposal
Bush offered in March ``and declare a victory.''
   Otherwise, said Rep. Steve Bartlett, R-Texas, there will only be
``continued deadlock.''
   Democrats, however, said the only concession they were willing to
make was reducing to $4.25 the $4.55 minimum in the bill that passed
Congress last spring and Bush vetoed.
   ``I'm not moving back one step further,'' said Rep. Carl Perkins,
D-Ky., noting the minimum wage has been frozen at $3.35 since 1981.
``I've seen too much given away for the sake of people who don't
care.''
   Perkins said Bush ``is not so much interested in the legislation
than he is trying to prove a point, and that saddens me.''
   On a 6-5 vote, with Murphy breaking away from his fellow
Democrats, the panel rejected an amendment by Bartlett to remove
overtime or minimum wage exemptions for some 30 different
classifications of workers.
   Among the exemptions _ which have worked their way into the law
over the past 50 years _ are fishermen, tobacco strippers, amusement
park workers, employees of newspapers with less than 4,000
circulation, radio and TV announcers in cities of less than 100,000,
laundry workers and domestic maids.
   While the idea intrigued many more Democrats, Rep. Augustus
Hawkins, D-Calif., the full committee's chairman, called Bartlett's
proposal a ``killer'' amendment that would erode support for the
bill.
   The Education and Labor Committee is scheduled to take up the
legislation next Tuesday. Just before Congress recessed in August,
the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee reapproved without
change the bill that Bush vetoed in June.
   But Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, has said he
is willing to change it on the Senate floor to accommodate the
House's action or if a compromise can be struck with Bush.
</TEXT>
