<FIRST>r a PM-LoveCanal     09-15 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Love Canal,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Say Resettlement of Love Canal Threatens Symbol</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rally is scheduled to begin at 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the planned resettlement of the
Love Canal neighborhood mostly cite health concerns, but they also
don't want to lose a national symbol of an environmental disaster,
an activist said.
   Eleven years after officials evacuated hundreds of families from
the Niagara Falls neighborhood when chemicals from a dump seeped
into homes, state health officials say people can move back into the
area after years of cleanup.
   Resettlement opponents, however, question whether the
neighborhood is safe. Hundreds of environmentalists and religious
activists plan to attend a rally in Albany tonight in hopes of
persuading Gov. Mario Cuomo to stop the planned resettlement.
   Lois Gibbs, the former Love Canal homemaker who became well-known
in the environmental movement after leading her former neighbors in
a fight for federal assistance, said she also doesn't want to lose
Love Canal's symbolic value.
   ``By making it habitable, it steals away the symbol from the
people,'' Gibbs said in an interview this week. ``Love Canal is a
symbol for problems across the country.''
   ``Anywhere I go in the country ... regardless of what people are
fighting, they refer to the damage created by that particular
facility as Love Canal,'' said Gibbs, who now works for the
Virginia-based Citizens Clearinghouse for Hazardous Waste. She is an
organizer for today's rally.
   Last fall, Dr. David Axelrod, the state health commissioner,
ruled that two-thirds of the Love Canal neighborhood was suitable
for resettlement after years of work to contain or treat the toxic
contamination from the dump site.
   Resettlement of the homes is scheduled for next year.
   Occidental Chemical Corp., owner of the former Hooker Chemical
and Plastic Co. which used Love Canal as a waste dump, acknowledges
that 20,000 tons of chemical wastes were dumped there in the 1940s
and 1950s.
   The dump was covered and the Niagara Falls School District bought
the land and built a school and playground there. Developers built
hundreds of homes nearby during the 1960s. Foul odors and oozing
chemicals were the first signs for residents that something was
wrong.
   The chemical contamination remains in a giant fenced mound at the
center of the neighborhood.
   Occidental declined to comment on today's rally.
   Today, about 70 homes in Love Canal are occupied by people who
chose not to leave when the neighborhood was declared a federal
emergency area in 1978. But the overriding image of the neighborhood
is one of block after block of bulldozed lawns and boarded-up tract
homes.
   The current residents hope that Cuomo won't stop the resettlement.
   ``We pray that this demonstration will not sway you or your
agencies' progress toward the remediation and resettlement of this
area,'' said a letter from a residents' group.
   Axelrod's conclusion was based on studies comparing levels of
toxics with those found in other areas of Niagara Falls.
   ``Based on what we know, people would not be exposed to any
higher risk there than they would be elsewhere in the greater
Niagara Falls community,'' said Peter Slocum, Axelrod's spokesman.
   A potential sticking point, however, is that scientists used a
``comparison standard'' for certain chemical levels in the
neighborhood ``because we don't have a better standard,'' Slocum
said.
   Gibbs and others fear that the levels used for comparison in Love
Canal will set a precedent.
   ``If they let people back in with those levels, then essentially
they are legalizing those levels,'' said Gibbs. ``That's a precedent
that we cannot allow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
