<FIRST>r w PM-US-Cambodia     09-15 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cambodia,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials, Congressmen Dispute Paris Conference Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Misgivings about U.S. policy toward Cambodia
have surfaced in Congress in anticipation of the promised withdrawal
of Vietnamese forces from the Southeast Asian country later this
month.
   Several Congressmen accused the Bush administration Thursday of
taking a weak stand at the recent international conference on
Cambodia against return of the Khmer Rouge, the communists accused
of causing more than a million Cambodian deaths during their 1975-78
``Killing Fields'' rule over Cambodia.
   ``Given the moral consequences of failure _ given the possibility
that the Khmer Rouge may return ... if there was ever an issue in
which consultation between the executive branch and congress is an
absolute necessity, this is the one,'' Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-NY,
told his House Asian-Pacific affairs subcommittee after a public
hearing on the issue.
   Spectators were then cleared from the room to enable a senior
State Department official to clarify in closed session the U.S.
strategy for blocking the Khmer Rouge from returning to power.
   The official, Richard Solomon, assistant secretary of state for
East Asian and Pacific affairs, during the public debate blasted as
``grossly unfair and inaccurate, implications that somehow we are
trying to whitewash what happened during the 1970s'' in Cambodia.
   Solomon said he would have to dig into the records of the failed
Cambodian conference last month in Paris to provide concrete
evidence of the stand the United States took there against past
Khmer Route genocide. He said tactics for future dealings with the
Khmer Rouge could be explained only in closed session.
   The administration favors ``no role for the Khmer Rouge in a
future Cambodian government,'' but continues to support Cambodian
Prince Sihanouk and his desire to remain allied with the Khmer Rouge
in a four-party transition government, Solomon testified.
   In Paris, the United States agreed with Sihanouk, China and
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations that the
Khmer Rouge could be better controlled if they were inside the new
regime, and that excluding them would be ``a sure formula'' for
civil war once the Vietnamese leave.
   Rep. Chester Atkins, D-Mass., accused the administration of
publicly condemning the Khmer Rouge but remaining silent and taking
no action at working sessions.
   He charged that the Paris conference failed ``in large measure
because the Khmer Rouge and its international backers sought to
expunge from all official records any acknowledgment of their acts
of genocide,'' and the United States acquiesced.
   The U.S. position meant that ``we are clinging to the outmoded
policies and paranoia of the Vietnam War, but the war is over and
the world has changed. We are not able by sheer force and strong
will to create a Cambodian government that is absolutely to our
liking,'' Atkins said. ``If stopping the Khmer Rouge ``means taking
a fresh, more reasoned assessment of the successes of the
(Vietnam-installed) Hun Sen government, then so be it.''
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, said the United States ``does not have
the luxury'' of avoiding such moral issues as Khmer Rouge
``genocide.'' He said Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot should be tried by
an international court for war crimes.
   Solomon said the Paris negotiations are in suspension and could
be resumed if progress appears likely after six months of
lower-level talks. He blamed failure to achieve a comprehensive
settlement at Paris on Vietnam and Hun Sen, head of the
Vietnamese-installed government in Cambodia. They refused to
compromise on Sihanouk's four-party formula and sought to retain the
infrastructure of the Hun Sen government, giving it unfair advantage
in promised elections, he said.
   Sihanouk ``is not infallible ... he is capable of monumental
misjudgment,'' Solarz said. He recalled that the prince's alliance
with the Khmer Rouge in 1970 helped transform them from regional
guerrillas into a force that later overthrew a U.S.-backed
government.
</TEXT>
