<FIRST>r w PM-MissileParts 1stLd-Writethru a0465 09-15 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missile Parts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Drops Missile Supplier</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 7th graf to change `Friday' to `today'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department says the firing of a
California defense contractor will delay deployment of new Amraam
air-to-air missiles and force the Navy to take parts from old
missiles until a new supplier begins production.
   The Pentagon said Thursday it dropped Micronics International of
Brea, Calif., because of years of problems with an arming and safety
device on air-to-air missiles.
   The Pentagon withdrew its inspectors from the Micronics plant
near Los Angeles and the government no longer will accept delivery
of the safety and arming device, said Lt. Robert Fallon, a spokesman
for the Navy.
   ``There's no evidence that the safety and arming device has
caused any detrimental missile performance,'' the Navy said in a
statement. ``The Navy has a full inventory of missiles for its
operational forces to compensate for an expected stop in deliveries
of the safety and arming device.''
   The devices will be produced by Raymond Engineering in
Massachusetts, starting in 1991.
   The missile itself is built by the Hughes Aircraft unit of
General Motors Corp.
   The troubled device will cause problems with the Amraam, Sparrow
and Sidewinder missiles, The New York Times reported in today's
editions. The Amraam will not be installed aboard Navy F-15 and Air
Force F-18 fighters until new parts are secured from another source,
but production problems for the Sparrow and Sidewinder are expected
to be relatively minor.
   The arming device, roughly comparable to the safety on a gun, is
built into the missile's fuze to prevent premature firing of the
missile. It also prevents explosions in accidents, such as dropping
a warhead on a carrier deck, but allows the warhead to explode when
it hits a target after being fired.
   Limited production of the Phoenix missile began eight years ago,
but as late as three years ago the Navy disclosed it was not
deploying the weapon because of several problems, including the
arming device. In a ``tear-down'' inspection of the missile in
mid-1986, the Navy found 2,694 defects.
   Last year, the Los Angeles Times reported the Defense Department
was conducting a criminal investigation of Micronics, which was
suspected of using a production process that does not yield the
quality required by specifications for the arming device.
   The radar-guided Phoenix was designed for the F-14 fighter and is
supposed to be able to hit targets 100 miles away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
