<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Philippines-Refugees     09-15 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Philippines-Refugees,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Navy Vessel Rescues 32 Vietnamese in South China Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUBIC BAY NAVAL BASE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy ship rescued
32 Vietnamese refugees from an unseaworthy craft in the South China
Sea and brought them to this U.S.-run base 50 miles northwest of
Manila, the Navy said today.
   The USS Beaufort, a salvage and rescue ship, arrived Thursday
with the Vietnamese after picking them up Monday about 150 miles
south of the Vietnamese coast, said a statement by the U.S. Navy's
7th Fleet.
   Navy officials said the 12 men, five women and 15 children were
in generally good condition and were turned over to Philippine
authorities.
   They were taken aboard the USS Beaufort because their 40-foot
vessel was unseaworthy and lacked navigation equipment and food, the
Navy said. It did not say what was wrong with the boat.
   A court-martial at Subic Bay in February convicted a captain of
dereliction of duty for failing to help Vietnamese in the South
China Sea who said they later resorted to cannibalism before being
rescued by Filipino fishermen.
</TEXT>
