<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0423EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-15 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rehnquist Disputes Book's Claim He Broke His Word</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist says a new
book on Robert H. Bork's failed Supreme Court nomination incorrectly
says Rehnquist broke a promise to keep Justice Lewis F. Powell's
impending retirement a secret.
   Author Ethan Bronner, in his book, ``Battle for Justice,'' says
Powell told Rehnquist on June 25, 1987, that he would announce his
retirement the following day and asked for ``a solemn promise'' to
keep it a secret overnight.
   ``The chief justice expressed his sincere regret, agreed to keep
it to himself, and called (White House Chief of Staff Howard H.)
Baker with the news,'' the book said. It said Baker immediately told
President Reagan.
   ``That statement is in error,'' an angry Rehnquist said Thursday.
``I notified Howard Baker of the retirement shortly before we went
on the bench on the morning of Friday, June 26, 1987.''
   Bronner, however, stuck by his story and said his tape-recorded
interview with Baker supports his account of Rehnquist's action.
   Privately, Rehnquist has told people at the court that he is
offended by an account that portrays him as a man who cannot be
trusted to keep his word.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FDA Poised To Approve Wider Distribution Of AIDS Drug</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food and Drug Administration sources say they
expect a plan for wider distribution of a promising experimental
AIDS drug known as DDI to be approved shortly.
   Bristol-Myers Co., which is licensed to manufacture the drug, has
said it will distribute DDI, or dideoxyinosine, at no cost to AIDS
patients when the next round of clinical trials begins later this
month.
   Thus far, the drug has been available only to about 90 patients
in phase one clinical trials, the initial safety studies.
   The company has asked the FDA to approve distribution of the drug
to patients who do not qualify for the upcoming round of research
trials, which will compare DDI to AZT, the only approved anti-AIDS
drug. Patients who cannot tolerate AZT would be ineligible for these
trials. Scientists say DDI is less toxic and better tolerated by
patients than is AZT.
   FDA officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Thursday
no decision has been made on precisely who would be eligible to
receive the drug, though one source said it would include certain
patients outside clinical trials.
   Researchers say that like AZT, DDI appears to reduce replication
of the human immunodeficiency virus that causes AIDS and controls
the disease by enabling the body to recover some ability to fight
infection.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Number of Elected Hispanics Jumps But Proportion Remains Low</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite ``impressive'' gains at every level,
Hispanics still account for less than 1 percent of all elected
officials, according to a Latino advocacy group.
   The National Association of Latino Elected and Appointed
Officials says 3,783 Hispanic elected officials hold office in 37
states, an increase of 12.6 percent from 1988.
   Texas leads the country, with 1,693 elected Hispanic officials
who account for 44.75 percent of the total, followed by New Mexico,
with 647 Hispanic elected officials who account for 17.1 percent of
the total, NALEO said in a study released Thursday.
   Despite their gains, elected Hispanic officials still account for
less than 1 percent of all elected officials nationwide, although
they make up 8 percent of the population, NALEO said.
   NALEO's 1989 roster found there are 10 Hispanic members of
Congress _ four from Texas, three from California, and one each from
New York, Florida and New Mexico.
   NALEO also said there are 128 state legislators, 1,340 school
board members, 1,178 municipal officials, 246 mayors, and one
governor _ Bob Martinez of Florida.
</TEXT>
