<DOCNO> AP890915-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0502EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Heroes     09-15 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heroes,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Honors 16 Heroes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anthony Figurski jumped out of bed and into
action when he awoke at midnight to find the house next door in
flames.
   ``I saw the fire and I just ran out of the house,'' Figurski
recalled. ``I reacted fast.''
   Wearing boxer shorts and a T-shirt, Figurski jumped a fence and
climbed through Lelia B. Terry's bedroom window. He found the
77-year-old woman crouched against a door and carried her through
thick smoke to safety.
   Figurski, 30, of Sun City, Calif., was one of 16 Americans and
Canadians honored by the Carnegie Hero Fund Commission Thursday for
risking their lives in an attempt to save others.
   The heroes, who receive a $2,500 cash award and a medal, bring to
79 the number honored this year and 7,367 recognized since
industrialist Andrew Carnegie established the commission in 1904.
   Figurski said he didn't think about the danger when he climbed
through Mrs. Terry's window and crawled across her bedroom on Oct.
6, 1988.
   ``I just knew she was in the house and somebody had to help
her,'' he said. ``There was nobody else around.''
   Mrs. Terry recovered following hospitalization. She died recently
of an unrelated illness. Figurski was treated for smoke inhalation.
   Also recognized Thursday were:
   _Deborah J. Shelly, 36, of Chattanooga, Tenn., who fought a
jaguar to save another woman under attack in a cage at the Wagner
Park Zoo on June 21, 1988.
   _Bryan E. Kratochvil, 24, of Lincoln, Neb., who saved a
5-year-old boy from his burning apartment on Oct. 6, 1988.
   _Dominic Possamai, 22, of Montreal, Quebec, who saved a
28-year-old woman from a man who stabbed her while she was
sunbathing in Lennoxville, Quebec, on Aug. 20, 1986.
   _Charles O. Stickles, 36, of Conwall-on-Hudson, N.Y., who was
injured saving a 17-year-old girl and her 43-year-old father from
their burning automobile in New Windsor, N.Y., on Dec. 10, 1988.
   _Junior David Phillips, 48, of Pamplin, Va., who saved a
59-year-old man from electrocution after his plow snagged a wire in
Evergreen, Va., on Dec. 31, 1988.
   _Donald G. Tolbert, 26, of Cedartown, Ga., and Sylvester O.
McHolmes, 34, of Atlanta, who attempted to save a 35-year-old
utility worker who was electrocuted in an underground power vault in
Atlanta on March 11.
   _Gisele Gagnon, 20, of Drummondville, Quebec, who was injured
saving a 7-year-old boy from his burning house in St. Cyrille de
Wendover, Quebec, on Jan. 13.
   _Katherine Finkbeiner, 38, of Greenwood, S.C., who was injured
attempting to save schoolchildren and fellow teachers from a gunman
who entered their elementary school and killed two people and
injured seven others on Sept. 26, 1988.
   _Jackson E. Stallcup, 36, of San Fernando, Calif., who was
injured saving a 54-year-old man from his burning car in Glendale,
Calif., on Oct. 10, 1988.
   _Murl Jay Sines, 23, of St. Maries, Idaho, who was injured saving
a family of four from their burning house on Nov. 19, 1988.
   _William B. Shelander II, 20, of Washington, Ill., who saved a
47-year-old man from an armed kidnaper on Sept. 15, 1988.
   _Eddie A. Turner, 33, of Catawba, N.C., who saved a fellow
skydiver who was knocked unconscious in a collision with another
skydiver over Clewiston, Fla., on Oct. 16, 1988.
   _Despina Buhagiar, 56, of St. Catharines, Ontario, who was
injured saving a 37-year-old neighbor woman being stabbed by an
assailant at her home on March 21, 1987.
   _J. Gordon Stevens, 26, of Peace River, Alberta, who was injured
while helping rescue a 33-year-old man from a burning car in Prince
Rupert, British Columbia, on Feb. 24.
</TEXT>
