<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Azerbaijan     09-15 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Supreme Soviet Convenes Special Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special session of the Azerbiajan Supreme Soviet
today discussed the ethnic conflict engulfing the ethnic Armenian
enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh, Tass reported.
   The extraordinary session also was to examine draft legislation
on the Transcaucasian republic's sovereignty, citizenship and
economic independence, the official news agency said.
   ``The situation in and around Nagorno-Karabakh has never been so
tense and explosive as today,'' Arkady Volskiy, head of a special
committee ordered by the Kremlin to administer the affairs of the
autonomous region, said in a television interview Thursday night.
   Tass said that for the first time, representatives of the
People's Front of Azerbaijan and other organizations were allowed to
attend the special session.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, a mountainous territory with a predominantly
ethnic Armenian population and situated within Azerbaijan, is the
center of a bitter dispute between mainly Christian Armenia and
predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan.
   About 100 people have died in the ethnic strife over the past 18
months and hundreds of thousands have fled their homes.
   The People's Front is demanding that Azerbaijan reassert control
over Nagorno-Karabakh and that direct rule by Moscow be halted.
   Volskiy said Moscow was forced to assume control of the region
because of the bloodshed. ``The state cannot stay aside if blood is
spilled,'' he said.
   On Thursday, the newspaper Pravda reported that a strike by
Azerbaijani railroad workers to press demands for Azerbaijani
control of Nagorno-Karabakh cut vital fuel and other supplies to
neighboring Armenia.
   The situation was particularly threatening in northern Armenia,
where workers are trying to reconstruct cities devastated by the
Dec. 7 earthquake that killed 25,000 people, Pravda said.
   

