<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomesDeaths     09-15 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Homes Deaths,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse's Aide Threatened to Kill Babies, Witness Testifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nursing home aide charged
with suffocating five patients said she was tempted to ``smash
babies'' at a Texas hospital where she later worked, her alleged
co-conspirator testified.
   Catherine Wood, the prosecution's key witness, continued her
testimony Thursday in Kent County Circuit Court in the trial of her
former lover, Gwendolyn Graham. The trial resumes Monday.
   Graham, 25, is charged with five counts of first-degree murder
and one count of conspiracy to murder in the 1987 deaths of female
patients at Alpine Manor Nursing Home in Walker, a suburb of Grand
Rapids.
   Wood, who has admitted helping Graham kill the patients, said she
and Graham sometimes talked by telephone after Graham moved to her
native Tyler, Texas, in July 1987 and began working at Mother
Frances Hospital as a nurse's aide.
   ``She told me she liked walking past the nursery and she wanted
to take one of (the babies) and smash it against the window,'' Wood
testified. ``I had to stop her somehow.''
   Her statements were made out of the presence of the jury after
the defense attorney objected.
   Bobbie Burks, a spokeswoman at Mother Frances, said by telephone
that there were no unusual occurrences or unexplained injuries at
the hospital while Graham was employed there between July 1987 and
October 1988. Graham didn't have access to the nursery and was fired
when the hospital found out she was being investigated in the Alpine
Manor deaths, Burks said.
   Wood, 27, has pleaded guilty to one count of second-degree murder
and one count of conspiracy to murder and agreed to testify against
Graham. Two counts of first-degree murder were dropped.
   Wood testified she felt bad about the murders while they were
occurring but went along with Graham, sometimes acting as a lookout
while Graham smothered the patients with rolled-up washcloths.
   The two split in July 1987, after living together for nearly a
year, and Graham moved to Tyler with another nurse's aide.
   Defense attorney James Piazza said Wood made up the slayings
because she was hurt and angry that Graham had left her for another
woman.
   Dawn Male, a former nurse's aide at Alpine who said she had
sexual relationships with both Wood and Graham, testified Thursday
that Graham admitted suffocating a patient with a pillow while Wood
kept watch.
   When the five patients died between Jan. 18 and April 7, 1987,
their deaths were listed as natural and no autopsies were performed.
Police began investigating after Wood's ex-husband told them she had
confessed to him.
   Kent County Medical Examiner Stephen Cohle testified Thursday he
performed autopsies on two patients whose bodies were exhumed in
November. He said he changed the cause of death on their death
certificates from heart disease to asphyxia due to suffocation,
primarily because of police reports.
   Cohle said he could find no physical evidence of suffocation, nor
could he find a physiological reason for their sudden deaths.
   The alleged victims were Belle Burkhard, 74, Marguerite Chambers,
60, Myrtle Luce, 95, Mae Mason, 79, and Edith Cook, 97.
   If convicted, Graham faces a mandatory life sentence. Wood could
receive parole in 10 years on the lesser charges.
</TEXT>
