<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-IsraeliMissile     09-15 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Israeli Missile,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Israelis Shot Ballistic Missile Into Mediterranean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel fired a ballistic missile with an 800-mile
range that landed in the Mediterranean north of Libya, the official
news agency Tass reported.
   Officials in Jerusalem neither confirmed nor denied the report
Thursday.
   ``We know nothing about this thing,'' an official of the Israeli
Army Command said.
   Tass said Defense Ministry data showed the rocket blasted off
from the Jerusalem area and fell into the sea about 250 miles north
of Benghazi, Libya.
   It gave no further details but said Israel previously launched a
ballistic missile in January 1988.
   In Athens, officials from Greece's National Defense Ministry
refused comment on reports the missile landed in the sea west of
Crete.
   A ballistic missile is a long-range rocket guided by preset
mechanisms in the first part of its flight, but which becomes a
free-falling object as it approaches its target.
   The United States and Soviet Union have designed ballistic
missiles to carry nuclear warheads.
   Israel, which launched its first satellite last Sept. 19, has
consistently refused to comment on whether it is developing nuclear
weapons or missiles.
   In July 1987, Radio Moscow's Hebrew-language service accused
Israel of developing a nuclear-capable missile, reportedly called
the Jericho-II.
   The Geneva-based International Defense Review reported then that
Israel successfully fired a missile into the Mediterranean and that
it flew 520 miles. The missile's projected range was said to be as
much as 920 miles.
   Two years before the Soviet radio report, the British magazine
New Statesman reported that Israel had deployed nuclear-armed
Jericho-II missiles in its southern Negev desert.
</TEXT>
