<FIRST>r a PM-Carter     09-15 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carter,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Ethiopian Talks, Next Stop for Carter: Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter, fresh from
sponsoring talks to end a rebellion in Ethiopia, is off to Nicaragua
to prepare for elections that could lead to a definitive end to that
country's war.
   Carter, whose activities in Panama and Africa this year have
given him a more visible role in world affairs than at any time
since he left the White House in 1981, will use the visit to prepare
for his role as an observer of Nicaragua's Feb. 25 presidential
elections.
   Peace talks that began Sept. 7 between the Ethiopian government
and the Eritrean People's Liberation Front at The Carter Center may
conclude today or adjourn until Tuesday, when Carter returns from
Nicaragua, said center spokeswoman Carrie Harmon.
   Acting as a private citizen, though with the blessing of
Washington, Carter has used his public policy facility and think
tank as a force to boost talks to end various regional conflicts.
   In Nicaragua, as in Panama, Carter will be representing the
Council of Freely Elected Heads of Government, a group of current
and former democratically elected chiefs of state.
   Carter was an observer at the May elections in Panama.
Afterwards, his accusations of fraud against de-facto military
leader Gen. Manuel Noriega received widespread attention.
   Over the past two weeks, Carter has served as host and observer
for preliminary discussions aimed at setting an agenda for talks to
end the 28-year-old war between Ethiopia and the Eritrean rebels in
the Horn of Africa.
   ``I think I can say without contradiction from Washington that
they do indeed support my trip to Nicaragua,'' Carter told reporters
in a briefing during the Ethiopian talks. ``But I will emphasize
again, this is not a duty designated to me by the Bush
administration.''
   Harmon said Carter's visit this weekend will include meetings
with members of Nicaragua's Supreme Electoral Board, government
officials, opposition leaders and representatives of church and
civic groups.
   President Daniel Ortega is expected to run for re-election in
election against Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, the director of the
opposition newspaper La Prensa and candidate of the 14-party
opposition coalition.
   Carter said his continued involvement in world matters is being
conducted by a concerned citizen, not by a man interested in
resurrecting a political career.
   ``You know, I've got a lot of things I could be doing,'' Carter
told reporters last week, using the Ethiopia-Eritrea talks as an
example. ``And I don't have any personal thing to gain from spending
days or weeks or whatever trying to bring peace to the people of
Ethiopia and Eritrea.
   ``But I look upon this as one of the most terrible conflicts in
the world, and the fact that both sides are at least going to have
good-faith negotiations has already been proven to me ... and I
think warrants my investment of time,'' Carter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
