<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     09-15 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Clashes Shatter Optimism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents rushed back to basement bomb
shelters today when Syrian and Christian gunners shelled the city
hours after Arab League mediators concluded talks aimed at ending
the fighting.
   Police said five people were killed and seven wounded in the
exchanges, which occurred residential districts in the city's Moslem
and Christian sectors as well as the wooded mountains southeast of
the capital.
   The latest casualties raised the toll to 900 killed and 2,559
wounded since March 8, when the current round of violence broke out
pitting Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian troops against Syrian
and allied forces.
   The duel started shortly after the foreign ministers of Saudi
Arabia, Morocco and Algeria ended two days of talks in the Saudi Red
Sea port of Jiddah late Thursday without issuing a cease-fire call.
   The three ministers, in a brief statement, said only that they
conducted a ``necessary evaluation'' of the situation in Lebanon and
considered the possibility of new moves.
   The statement said King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, King Hassan II of
Morocco and Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid will release an
official statement Saturday about the outcome of the committee's
efforts.
   The Syrian-Christian duel forced the few citizens remaining in
Beirut to rush to basements and underground shelters to escape the
barrage, shattering hopes that a relative lull in the fighting would
continue.
   The exchanges had sharply diminished Thursday and Wednesday while
the Arab League members met. Local newspapers had predicted a
cease-fire in the confrontation between Aoun's 20,000 soldiers and
the 40,000 Syrian troops.
   ``We were under the impression that this (shelling) was over, at
least for the time being,'' said Rashid Makkouk, a Sunni Moslem
resident of west Beirut's Bourj Abu Haidar district.
   After hearing the talks produced no agreement, Makkouk said at
the entrance to his shell-scarred apartment building, ``I was
wondering whether we should return to the shelter when the explosion
of the first shell echoed. We rushed down.''
   The shelling began in March over a blockade by Aoun of illegal
ports run by Syria's militia allies south of Beirut. Aoun sought to
reimpose government control on the ports.
   Syrian and allied forces retaliated by shelling and besieging the
310-square-mile Christian enclave, Aoun's power base northeast of
Beirut.
</TEXT>
