<SECOND>PM-Names, Sub, a0434,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf of NEW YORK-dated 2nd item in Rdp to CORRECT
that Southern replacement is nominated but not yet confirmed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugh Southern, the acting chairman of the
National Endowment for the Arts, has been named general manager of
the Metropolitan Opera.
   Southern, 57, has headed the National Endowment for the Arts in
Washington, D.C., since February. Prior to that he was responsible
for supervising the endowment's programs for the 12 major arts
disciplines, according to Thursday's announcement.
   In a previous role as executive director of New York's Theater
Development Fund, Southern brought a half-price tickets booth to
Broadway.
   Met General Manager Bruce Crawford resigned in April to head
Omnicom Group Inc., one of the world's largest advertising
corporations. He has continued to sign contracts for the Met while
it searched for a successor.
   As Southern's replacement in the arts endowment, President Bush
has nominated Oregon lawyer John E. Frohnmayer. His confirmation by
the Senate is pending.
