<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0831EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Commonwealth     09-15 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Commonwealth,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistan Rejoins British Commonwealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan will rejoin the British
Commonwealth next month after a 17-year absence and will attend next
month's annual meeting here, Commonwealth Secretary-General Sir
Shridath Ramphal said today.
   Ramphal said in a statement that at Pakistan's request he carried
out consultations over the past few months with member states of the
London-based Commonwealth, which includes Britain and its former
colonies.
   ``The Commonwealth had responded with unanimity to the wish of
the democratically elected government of Pakistan to rejoin the
Commonwealth,'' the statement quoted him as saying, referring to the
election of Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto in December that ended 11
years of military rule.
   It was Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto,
who in 1972 pulled the country out of the Commonwealth when members
Britain, Canada and Australia recognized the breakaway state of
Bangladesh, formerly East Pakistan. Pakistan hinted it wanted to
rejoin the Commonwealth in the early 1980s, Commonwealth sources
say. But the question was shelved because India, which sided with
Bangladesh in its fight for independence, did not express support.
   However, India indicated after Ms. Bhutto's election as prime
minister that it would have no objection.
   Beginning Oct. 1, Pakistan will be the 49th member of the group,
said Ramphal, who is from Guyana.
   ``There could hardly be a more auspicious prelude to the Kuala
Lumpur meeting later in October,'' he added.
   Ms. Bhutto is expected to attend the Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting to be held in the Malaysian capital Oct. 18-24,
the Foreign Ministry statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
