<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia     09-15 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nujoma Registers to Vote; Police Identify Irish Assassination Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Nujoma, president of the South-West
Africa People's Organization, was mobbed by supporters today when he
registered to vote in the territory's pre-independence elections.
   Police, meanwhile, confirmed the identity of an Irishman arrested
in connection with the assassination Tuesday night of Anton
Lubowski, the only ranking white member of the nationalist movement
that fought a 23-year war against South African rule of Namibia.
   Police Inspector Kierie du Rand confirmed newspaper reports that
Dean Acheson, 50, was the man police arrested Wednesday after
Lubowski was gunned down outside the gate of his home. Acheson is to
appear in court Monday, but du Rand said police are still
investigating a motive.
   ``It appeared very professional,'' he said. ``They or he (the
killer or killers) waited in the bush. Lubowski was in the process
of opening the gate and he was shot three times in the back. It
looked like one bullet was fired from the top after he was on the
ground.''
   Today was the final day of registration for the November
elections. More than 677,000 people have registered in the vast
territory of 1.3 million.
   Nujoma, who returned Thursday to Namibia after almost 30 years in
exile, registered to vote at a post office in Katutura, the main
black neighborhood on the edge of Windhoek, the capital.
   Nujoma said his decision to participate in the elections
indicated his organization was generally pleased with the
independence process, which is being implemented by South Africa
under United Nations supervision.
   ``I'm very happy with the efforts being made by the U.N. in
assisting the Namibian people, who have been so many years oppressed
in attempting to achieve their freedom,'' said Nujoma, whose
movement is favored in the polls.
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia since 1915, agreed to grant
the territory independence under a regional peace accord signed in
December that also calls for Cuba to withdraw its 50,000 soldiers
from Marxist-ruled Angola.
   No date has been set for Namibian independence, but it is
expected to be early next year.
   In brief comments to reporters at the polling station, Nujoma
said SWAPO no longer holds any prisoners at camps in Angola,
although about 200 former detainees released in July say the
organization has either killed or has in custody hundreds of
Namibians.
   A United Nations delegation is in Angola investigating the
charges but has not reported on its findings. The U.N. delegation
``will see for themselves,'' Nujoma said. ``I leave it up to them.''
   SWAPO has acknowledged torturing its detainees, saying they were
suspected of spying for the South African-led security forces. Among
those allegedly detained was Nujoma's wife, Kowambo. SWAPO and Mrs.
Nujoma, who registered with her husband today, have declined to
comment.
   The Star newspaper in Johannesburg and the pro-SWAPO Namibian
newspaper in Windhoek reported that Acheson entered South Africa
from Ireland six weeks ago. The Star said he comes from Belfast but
that his passport was obtained in Dublin.
   Lubowski, a prominent human rights lawyer, was the first white to
publicly declare his support for leftist-leaning SWAPO in 1984. He
was often ridiculed in newspaper articles and cartoons in right-wing
newspapers.
</TEXT>
