<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     09-15 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coalition Partners Fail to Agree on Egyptian Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's top leaders clashed today over Egypt's
plan to arrange Israeli-Palestinian talks, and officials in the two
major parties said the disagreement is threatening the coalition
government.
   The leaders of the left-leaning Labor Party and the right-wing
Likud bloc reportedly disagreed on the 10-point Egyptian peace plan
and on President Hosni Mubarak's efforts to sponsor a Palestinian
delegation for talks with Israel.
   Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny presented Mubarak's peace
plan to Israeli leaders today, said a spokesman for Finance Minister
Shimon Peres, the Labor Party leader. Israel had been saying it
cannot comment on a proposal it has not been officially presented
with.
   In the occupied West Bank, troops shot and killed two Palestinian
youths, including a 12-year-old, in clashes with stone-throwers in
the city of Nablus, Arab hospital officials said.
   An army spokesman said soldiers did not fire in the area where
Tarkek Said Tuffah, 12, was killed. He said a patrol commander shot
and killed a second youth when troops were attacked by youths
throwing iron bars and cement blocks.
   Arab reports said Tuffah was shot by an army sniper. The reports
said the second youth, Ata Yunis, 18, was killed in a clash with
troops that occurred d during Tuffah's funeral.
   The two deaths raise to 570 the Palestinian death toll in the
21-month-old uprising against Israeli occupation. Forty Israelis
have also died in the violence, and 114 Arabs have been killed by
fellow Palestinians who accused them of collaborating with Israeli
authorities.
   Today's meeting between leading ministers of Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc and Labor ended in sharp disagreement,
Israel radio said.
   Peres leaves Saturday for the United States, where he is
scheduled to meet President Bush and Secretary of State James A.
Baker III.
   He said in an interview published today in the Jerusalem Post
that the U.S. role in promoting Egypt's proposal will be crucial to
its success.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens of the Likud bloc is expected to
visit the United States next week and plans to meet with Baker.
   Likud opposes a major point in Mubarak's plan, acceptance of the
U.S-backed formula of trading occupied land for peace.
   Along with the peace plan, Mubarak has proposed that Israel meet
with a 12-member Palestinian delegation that includes two Arabs
deported from the occupied territories.
   The proposal is intended to satisfy Israel's demand to meet only
Palestinians from the territories and the PLO's insistence that
Palestinians living abroad be included in any talks.
   But Likud legislator Eliahu Ben-Elissar said Egypt's proposal was
simply a way to disguise a meeting with PLO representatives.
   ``We have closed the door to the PLO, so the Egyptians have
decided to push them in through the window,'' he said on Israel
radio.
   A Labor official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, confirmed
the party's meeting Thursday agreed to talks with a Palestinian
delegation. The official said Labor would consider leaving the
Cabinet if there is no progress in peace talks.
   The current coalition government was formed in lengthy
negotiations that followed November 1988 elections.
</TEXT>
