<HEAD>Catholic Newspaper Calls for Frank's Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic newspaper in Rep. Barney Frank's
congressional district wants him to resign, but the Massachusetts
Democrat said he won't because that would leave accusations about
him unanswered.
   Frank has been embroiled in controversy since acknowledging he
paid a male prostitute for sex and then hired him as a valet.
   The prostitute, Stephen Gobie, said Frank knew he used the
congressman's apartment in a prostitution ring. Frank denied it, and
said he fired Gobie when he found out about it.
   The call for Frank to step down came in an editorial in The
Anchor, the 29,000-circulation newspaper of the Roman Catholic
Diocese of Fall River.
   ``If he were a policeman, a school teacher or fireman, he would
be out of a job,'' the Rev. John F. Moore, editor of The Anchor,
wrote in an editorial dated Sept. 8. ``His rather tacky double
standard should not be condoned or excused.''
   But Frank said Thursday, ``A resignation would short-circuit the
(House) ethics committee, and I think the committee is an
appropriate forum.''
