<FIRST>r a PM-Police-Blacks     09-15 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police-Blacks,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officers Accused Of Leaving Black Youths In White Neighborhood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors are investigating an incident
in which two white police officers picked up two black youths at a
bus stop, slapped them and then left them in a mostly white area,
where they were attacked.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas announced the probe Thursday as a
Police Department official said an internal investigation had
confirmed the allegation.
   ``The case ... is a sustained case,'' David Fogel, head of the
department's Office of Professional Standards, said Thursday. ``In
other words, the allegations are true.''
   The two police officers, a man and a women who haven't been
identified, face disciplinary action as well as possible criminal
action, Fogel said.
   The probe into the incident by the Federal Bureau of
Investigation was launched at the request of Chicago Mayor Richard
M. Daley, Valukas said.
   The City Council on Wednesday voted unanimously to address the
issue of police brutality later this month after hearing reports of
the incident concerning two black teen-agers, in addition to a
weekend fatal shooting of a black man by police.
   Police say that Leonard Banister, 22, was shot on Sunday when he
tried to grab the gun of a black officer who was frisking him. Some
of Banister's friends and relatives say the shooting was unprovoked.
   In the earlier incident, the aunt of one of the youths said two
officers stopped and questioned her nephew and his friend, both 14,
on Aug. 15, as they headed home from a baseball game.
   The officers picked up the boys, slapped them and then dropped
them off in the mostly white neighborhood of Canaryville, where they
were attacked by several whites, she said.
   One of the youths was hospitalized after the attack and the other
fled and escaped serious injury, officials said.
   Five juveniles and two adults were arrested and charged with
aggravated battery and ethnic intimidation in connection with the
attack.
