<FIRST>u i PM-Refugees 2ndLd-Writethru a0518 09-15 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0518,0856</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Official: Reform More Important Than East Bloc Unity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 4th, `About 500...,' to UPDATE with E.
German comments. Pickup 5th pvs, `Magyar Hirlap...' Minor editing thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary decided to let East Germans flee
to the West because Budapest is more committed to Western-style
reforms than to an appearance of East bloc unity, a deputy foreign
minister said.
   Laszlo Kovacs said Hungary will not sacrifice ``measures held to
be important by us in the light of a possible disagreement by one of
our allies.'' His comments were published today by the state-run MTI
news agency and the newspaper Magyar Hirlap.
   East Germany has lashed out at Hungary for opening its border to
thousands of East Germans fleeing to the West. The border has been
open since Sunday, and about 14,000 East Germans have emigrated
since then.
   About 500 more East Germans arrived in West Germany today after
passing through Austria overnight, authorities said.
   East Germany today rejected calls for reforms to halt the flow of
its citizens to the West. But it also acknowledged for the first
time that the exodus of skilled workers will hurt the economy.
   Guenter Mittag, the East German official in charge of the
economy, said in the state newspaper Neues Deutschland that West
German calls for reform in East Germany ``contain only one point:
they want the type of reform that does away with Socialism.''
   ``Thanks a lot for that. It just won't be that way!'' Mittag
wrote.
   Harry Tisch, a Central Committee member who heads the state-run
labor union, said on a visit to Stuttgart that the government would
have to find solutions to the problem of losing many young, skilled
workers.
   Magyar Hirlap also reported today that dozens of Romanians and
Czechoslovaks are caught each night trying to slip across Hungary's
border with Austria. Austrian border police in the state of
Burgenland said an equal number make it across each night.
   The border police said 40 Romanians and five Czechoslovaks
arrived before dawn today.
   The new escape route has prompted East Germans in Poland and
Czechoslovakia to seek refuge in West German embassies in hopes they
also will be able to go West.
   West German Foreign Ministry officials said today that 60 East
Germans are at the embassy in Warsaw and about 190 in Prague.
   A West German border police spokesman, Klaus Papenfuss, said 273
of the new arrivals today registered with camps set up near Passau
and the rest continued by train to other refugee centers set up in
the central part of the country.
   Papenfuss said in a statement that seven more busloads of East
Germans were expected to arrive today.
   The East Germans are automatically granted citizenship in West
Germany and have been given assistance finding housing and jobs.
   Kovacs said Hugary's decision to let the refugees go ``is in
accordance with international norms and regulations on human rights,
thereby proving the consistency of Hungarian politics, the
commitment of the country's leadership in accomplishing the reform
process.''
   Asked if Hungary felt a ``triangle'' of East-bloc allies was
forming against the reformist state, Kovacs replied: ``It is true
that Hungary's relations with these countries have become tense.''
He referred to ties with Czechoslovakia and Romania, as well as East
Germany.
   Hungary and Poland have led the Soviet bloc in carrying out
social and political reforms, but East Germany, Romania and
Czechoslovakia have resisted.
   Hungary has alienated Czechoslovakia by denouncing the 1968
Warsaw Pact invasion of that country and by pulling out of a
controversial Danube dam project. Romania is angry with Hungary over
Budapest's decision to give refuge to 20,000 Romanians of Hungarian
descent who have fled illegally.
   Kovacs said the strains with the three countries ``are unusual
and call for concern,'' but he did not elaborate.
   West Germany's ARD television network said there were rumors
Hungary would close the border soon, but Hungarian government
spokesman Zsolt Bajnok said he knew of no such plans.
   Bajnok quoted Foreign Minister Gyula Horn as saying Thursday that
``no decision has been made'' on stopping the flow of East Germans.
   Ferenc Somogyi, Hungarian secretary of state for foreign affairs,
said in an interview published today, ``We will leave the border
open as long as we judge it necessary.
   ``I assure you that all East Germans in Hungary will have the
opportunity to leave the country,'' the Paris newspaper Le Figaro
quoted him as saying in Budapest. The article did not give the date
of his comments but did refer to events Wednesday.
   East Germany has accused Hungary of breaking a 1969 agreement
prohibiting unauthorized departures to the West of residents of the
Warsaw Pact countries, and it filed a formal protest Tuesday.
   A Soviet Politburo member said Thursday that Moscow is East
Germany's ``loyal friend'' and President Mikhail S. Gorbachev plans
to visit the troubled communist state next month, East Germany's
official news agency reported.
</TEXT>
