<FIRST>r w PM-US-Refugees 2ndLd-Writethru a0539 09-15 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Refugees, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0539,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagleburger Says US Doing All It Can To Admit Soviet Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs graf 4, Many members, with two new grafs to include
Hatch quote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior administration official, seeking to
deflect criticism of its handling of Soviet refugees, said today the
United States was doing all it can to admit as many as possible but
its capabilities are limited.
   ``We are trying to manage the surge in Soviet emigration in the
most humane and orderly way possible,'' said Deputy Secretary of
State Lawrence Eagleburger.
   Testifying before the Senate subcommittee on immigration,
Eagleburger said that while the United States applauds the recent
liberalization of Soviet emigration, ``we must be honest in
appraising our national ability to respond to unprecedented,
unpredictable and previously unmanaged flows of people.''
   Republican Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah was sharply critical of
the administration's position. ``No budget deficit, however large,
should ever induce the United States to abandon or compromise in any
way its fundamental values'' of granting haven to ``oppressed
peoples,'' he said.
   Many members of Congress have criticized the strategy for dealing
with Soviet refugees, saying the United States is limiting their
entry instead of opening its arms to the unprecedented wave of
emigres.
   ``Just when the Soviet faucets start opening, the U.S. government
finds itself totally incapable of dealing with the results it has
been pressing so many years to achieve,'' said Rep. Benjamin Gilman,
R-N.Y. ``We look like laughingstocks to the Soviets and like fools
to the emigres.''
   In an effort to deflect some of the criticism, Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh on Thursday ordered the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to reconsider the applications of 4,000
Soviets whose bid for refugee status were denied by INS examiners in
Rome.
   The INS will consider whether the Soviets, who are mostly Jews,
would be subjected to persecution if they were forced to return to
their homeland, the Justice Department said.
   This standard will be used in evaluating the applications of some
16,000 Soviets in Rome who are also seeking U.S. refugee status,
said a Justice Department official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``I am aware of and sensitive to the great chorus of concern
which has been expressed for these persons,'' Thornburgh said.
   The Bush administration said this week it plans to limit the
number of Soviet refugees admitted to this country to 50,000 in the
coming fiscal year. As many as 150,000 are expected to apply in
fiscal 1990.
   Princeton Lyman, Director of Refugee Programs at the State
Department, told a joint hearing of two House panels that once the
administration handles the backlog of applicants from this fiscal
year _ estimated at more than 50,000 _ there will not be any slots
left for new applicants in fiscal 1990.
   ``The administration should just hang up a sign in Moscow telling
people not to bother applying in 1990,'' said Rep. Howard Berman,
D-Calif. ``Why establish elaborate processing procedures when no one
will be admitted anyway?''
   Jewel Lafontant, the administration's coordinator for refugee
affairs, told panel members that, ``we share your frustration. We
don't have all the answers, but we're working darned hard to find
them.''
   Two pending bills would require the administration to
automatically grant refugee status to all Soviet emigres on the
grounds that they face persecution as a group.
   All Soviets were granted refugee status until summer 1988, when
former attorney general Edwin Meese ordered that each applicant be
required to prove persecution on an individual basis.
   This change resulted in 20 to 50 percent of applicants being
turned down, U.S. officials said Thursday.
   Berman released an internal State Department report that said
widespread anti-Semitism in the lower ranks of Soviet government and
among the general populace has increased greatly under glasnost.
   State-sponsored anti-Semitism, official policy for hundreds of
years, has abated, although many cases are still reported, the
report said.
   The Jewish community expressed its concern with the new
administration strategy at separate White House and State Department
meetings. At the State Department, leaders of five American Jewish
groups gave the administration the names of 400 Jewish families who
have been denied exit permits.
   The issue will be discussed later this month in Wyoming when
Secretary of State James A. Baker III meets with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Also on the Wyoming agenda is a U.S. request to increase its
embassy staff in Moscow to deal with the number of Soviet applicants
seeking entry into the United States.
   The administration's new proposal would provide full federal
sponsorship for 40,000 Soviet refugees while private organizations
would finance the resettlement for the remaining 10,000.
   It also would allow as many as 30,000 Soviets to come here under
a special parole category if they can find the money for their
travel and resettlement.
   To save money, the State Department announced it will close
processing centers for Soviet emigres in Italy and Austria, and
handle all processing in Moscow with a new facility in Washington to
help with the caseload.
</TEXT>
