<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     09-15 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Arrest 279 Suspects in Crackdown on Sinhalese Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces have arrested 279
suspects in the latest crackdown on anti-government Sinhalese
radicals in central and southern Sri Lanka, a government communique
said today.
   At least two radicals were killed during an army operation
Thursday in Matale district's Udwelgala village, 65 miles northeast
of Colombo, the communique said.
   It said 168 suspects were arrested in Colombo district and the
remaining in several operations since Thursday in the Sinhalese
heartland.
   The statement said 26 ``wanted subversives'' surrendered in
central Sri Lanka during that period.
   Subversives is the official term for members of the People's
Liberation Front, an ultranationalist guerrilla group trying to
overthrow the Sinhalese-dominated government.
   The government crackdown was launched after President Ranasinghe
Premadasa inaugurated an interparty peace conference Wednesday to
try to end six years of ethnic strife in Sri Lanka that has cost
16,000 lives.
   Although invited, the front did not attend the meeting. The next
session will be held Monday. The front has also rejected the
government's earlier peace offers.
   The government says at least 5,000 people have been killed in the
2-year-old Sinhalese movement. The remaining died in a Tamil
insurrection that began in 1983 for an independent nation in the
northeast.
   Former President Junius R. Jayewardene tried to end the Tamil
secession with an India-mediated peace accord in 1987, but it led to
a Sinhalese backlash that was spearheaded by the front.
   The front's campaign of assassinations and strikes intensified
this year after Premadasa took office in January.
   The radicals oppose the deployment of Indian peacekeeping
soldiers in the northeast, invited to supervise the accord, and also
say the peace plan gave too many concessions to the Tamil minority.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
claim they are discriminated in jobs and education. Sinhalese make
up 75 percent of the population and control the government and the
military.
</TEXT>
