<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CalifQuake     09-15 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Calif Quake,0124</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mile Quake Hits High Desert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake struck the
Southern California high desert early today, but no injuries or
damage were reported.
   The quake measured at 3.6 on the Richter scale and hit at 6:20
a.m., said Robert Finn, spokesman for the seismology laboratory at
the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
   It was centered 16 miles northwest of here, about 50 miles
northeast of downtown Los Angeles.
   Residents in Apple Valley, Victorville and Riverside reported
feeling the shaker.
   Quakes measuring from 3.5 to 4 on the Richter scale of ground
motion are classified as mild, but often have enough force to break
windows or knock shelved items to the floor.
</TEXT>
