<FIRST>r i PM-LaPasionaria 1stLd-Writetrhu   09-15 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-La Pasionaria, 1st Ld-Writetrhu,a0534,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legendary Communist Leader Seriously Ill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, ``Mrs. Ibarruri...'' with 1 graf to ADD another
transalation for La Pasionaria. Pickup 8th graf, ``After the...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dolores Ibarruri, the Spanish Communist
leader who became a legend during the Civil War, was seriously ill
in a Madrid hospital today, one day after being admitted for
treatment of pneumonia, doctors said.
   Mrs. Ibarruri, 93, checked into Ramon y Cajal hospital on
Thursday after complaining of serious breathing problems.
   Doctors today said her condition had improved slightly overnight
but remained serious because of her advanced age and chronic blood
circulation problems.
   Mrs. Ibarruri, better known by her pen-name ``La Pasionaria,''
was one of the Spanish Communist Party's founders in 1920 and is
currently the party's honorary president.
   During the 1931-39 Second Republic, she was elected to Parliament
and became renowned during the 1936-39 Civil War for her fiery radio
broadcasts exhorting Republican forces to defeat Gen. Francisco
Franco's insurgent army rebels.
   During the 1937 rebel siege of Madrid, her defiant phrase _ ``no
pasaran'' or ``they shall not pass'' _ became the battle cry of
loyalist Republican forces.
   Mrs. Ibarruri entered politics as a labor organizer and strike
leader and wrote newspaper articles signed ``La Pasionaria,'' which
is the Spanish transalation for passion flower but can also mean
``The Passionate One.'' She chose the name because her first article
appeared in 1916 in a Socialist newspaper during Holy Week, or
Semana de la Pasion in Spanish.
   After the war, she spent 38 years in exile in the Soviet Union
and received that country's highest civilian award, the Order of
Lenin.
   She returned to live in the Spanish capital at the age of 82 as
Spain made a peaceful transition to democracy after Franco's death
in 1975.
   In 1977, in Spain's first democratic elections since the war, the
white-haired grandmother won back her deputy's seat in the lower
house of Parliament, though she later gave it up because of
worsening health.
</TEXT>
