<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Violence     09-15 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Violence,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>13 Killed in Hindu-Moslem Riot; 12 Slain in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police opened fire on rioting Hindus and
Moslems in a western Indian town, and at least 13 people were killed
and more than 50 injured, news reports said today.
   In northern Punjab state, meanwhile, police today blamed Sikh
extremists for an attack that killed 12 people in renewed violence
Thursday night, including eight members of one family.
   The clashes in the western town of Kota, 250 miles southwest of
New Delhi, came late Thursday during celebrations to mark the end of
a popular Hindu festival, Press Trust of India said.
   Moslems hurled stones at marchers carrying idols of a Hindu god,
leading to clashes in which ``arms were freely used,'' the reports
said.
   United News of India said police first tried to repulse the
rioters with batons, but the crowds hurled rocks at policemen,
forcing them to open fire.
   The news agencies did not say if the deaths resulted from police
firing or the clashes.
   More than 25 shops were burned and a shop selling arms was
looted, PTI said. It is not known if stolen weapons were used in the
fighting. A curfew was imposed and troops patrolled the streets
today, the reports said.
   In Punjab, six militants armed with automatic assault rifles
raided the farmhouse in the village of Rasoolpur, killing eight
family members, said Surjit Singh, a senior district police official.
   Elsewhere Thursday night, Sikh militants were reported to have
killed four other people.
   The militants, believed to belong to the radical Khalistan
Commando Force, escaped, police said.
   The Khalistan Commando Force is one of about a dozen militant
groups operating in the troubled northwestern state, where more than
1,280 people have been killed this year.
   Since 1982, Sikh militants have been demanding a separate state,
claiming discrimination by the Hindu majority.
   Sikhism was founded as an branch from Hinduism and Islam in the
16th century. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of India's
population. Hindus make up more than 80 percent of India's 880
million people.
</TEXT>
