<FIRST>r w PM-WheatReserve     09-15 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wheat Reserve,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gives USDA OK to Release Emergency Wheat Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has given Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter the authority to released an additional 2 million
metric tons of emergency wheat for use as food aid to distressed
areas of the world.
   The White House announcement Thursday said the wheat could be
used to provide ``emergency food assistance to developing
countries'' that run short of domestic supplies.
   Under the Food Security Wheat Reserve Act of 1980, a stockpile of
4 million tons _ about 147 million bushels _ was created for use to
supply emergency food relief abroad.
   The first time the stockpile was tapped was last October when
President Reagan authorized release of 1.5 million tons when it
became apparent there would not be enough wheat in the marketplace
to fill the needs of developing countries.
   With the authorization to use an additional 2 million tons, the
special reserve is virtually depleted. That was one reason Yeutter
gave earlier this week when he announced a liberalization of the
government's 1990 wheat program _ to help rebuild U.S. stockpiles,
including the special reserve.
</TEXT>
