<FIRST>u i PM-Canada-Arrests 1stLd-Writethru a0483 09-15 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Hearing for Colombians Under Heavy Guard After Weapons Seized</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6 grafs for grafs 6-8 pvs to UPDATE with men charged, identities,
details. Pickup 9th pvs, `Bill d'Amours...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMUNDSTON, New Brunswick (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of rifle-toting police
surrounded a courthouse where two Colombians faced cocaine charges
after authorities in this city north of Maine arrested four heavily
armed Venezuelans.
   Officials said they did not know if the Venezuelans had planned
to interfere with Thursday's judicial proceedings in Fredericton,
the provincial capital 125 miles southeast of Edmunston.
   Sgt. Mark Flemming of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police said he
ordered the heavy security because ``we are assessing the situation
regarding the situation in Colombia,'' where officials have launched
a crackdown on drug traffickers.
   ``An ounce of protection is worth a pound of cure,'' he said.
   The Mounted Police and Edmundston authorities arrested the
Venezuelans Wednesday and seized weapons from two cars and a van
near downtown Edmundston, a pulp- and paper-producing town nearly
300 miles northeast of Augusta on the tip of Maine.
   Police led the men into a provincial court where they were
charged with a variety of weapons offenses.
   ``Innocent, innocent,'' one of the handcuffed men told reporters.
``No speak English,'' another said.
   The men were identified as Tito Sanchez, Euovio Manzano, Osvaldo
Gonzales and Wilmer Ramon Zanabria. Court documents did not state
their ages or hometowns.
   Only two of the men had lawyers. All were remanded in custody
until Tuesday when they will reappear for bail hearings. Further
charges may yet be filed against them.
   Authorities said the weapons found in their vehicles included an
Uzi submachine gun, Soviet and Israeli assault rifles and more than
3,000 rounds of ammunition. Also seized were six automatic pistols,
a .22-caliber pistol, tear gas, a deactivated Japanese grenade,
burglary equipment and an electric zap gun used to knock people out.
   In a related incident, a fifth man with Venezuelan identification
was arrested at a car rental agency Thursday. Police said they
seized two handguns at the scene.
   Bill d'Amours of the Canandian Immigration Department said the
Venezuelans' passports were sent to the Mounted Police forensic lab
in Ottawa to check if the documents are valid.
   He said it was not known how the men entered Canada.
   Two of their vehicles had New York licenses, including one stolen
plate, police said. The vehicle carrying most of the weapons had
been rented in Fredericton.
   The four were carrrying maps marking a destination in New
Brunswick that police would not identify.
   The Colombian suspects, Jose Ali Galindo-Escobar and Fernando
Augusto Mendoza-Jarmillio, both 36, Thursday were ordered held for
trial next month.
   The two were charged with importing drugs in April after police
made Canada's largest cocaine seizure when they found about 1,100
pounds of the drug inside the nose of an airplane at a makeshift
airstrip outside Fredericton.
   The Mounted Police say Colombian drug cartels have been routing
more drugs through the Canadian Maritime provinces because the
United States has tightened up its borders in an effort to block
drug traffickers.
   ``As somebody put it to me today, it feels like the long arm of
incivility in Colombia is reaching into New Brunswick,'' said
provincial Premier Frank McKenna. ``I think everyone in New
Brunswick feels a great sense of unease.''
</TEXT>
