<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Long-hairedBowler     09-15 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Long-haired Bowler,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tournament Ordered To Pay Damages For Banning Long-Haired Bowler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man banned from a bowling tournament
because his hair was too long has been awarded $3,000 in damages by
the St. Paul Human Rights Commission.
   The commission voted unanimously Wednesday night to uphold Joe
Big Bear's discrimination complaint against the Amateur Bowler's
Tour, a national organization that conducts local bowling
tournaments.
   Big Bear, 35, of St. Paul, wanted to bowl in a tournament at St.
Paul's Midway Bowl in November.
   The Human Rights Commission ordered the organization to pay him
$1,000 in compensatory damages and $2,000 in punitive damages. The
organization also was ordered to pay $1,300 in attorney's fees and
costs of the investigation. In addition, it must change its rules
and remove the discriminatory language.
   Scott Miller, local director of the Amateur Bowler's Tour, had no
comment Thursday. His attorney, Don Horton, had argued at the July
hearing that the organization should be free to set its own rules on
grooming.
   The organization has 30 days to appeal.
