<FIRST>r i AM-DeadlyDrill     09-15 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deadly Drill,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Man Dies, 23 Admitted to Hospital During Fire Drill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of workers outside an
office building thought it was part of the fire drill when people
began gasping for breath, but the smoke turned out to be real and
killed one man, newspapers reported Friday.
   The incident occurred Thursday in Ipoh, 120 miles north of Kuala
Lumpur.
   After five years, the Fire Department thought it was time to have
a fire drill at the city's eight-story state secretariat building
and informed the staff of its plans. To make it realistic, smoke was
released into some rooms.
   The 1,000 government workers began fleeing as part of the drill,
but 89 were overcome by smoke, and one of them, a 44-year-old man
identified as Mohamad Isa Mohamad Tahir, died as he clung to a ledge
on the second floor.
   The New Straits Times Daily, The Star and other newspapers
reported that the other 88 people were rescued and that 23 of them
were hospitalized.
   Mohamed Salleh Khatib Ali said he was in the bathroom on the
second floor when he heard two explosions.
   ``I rushed out and was choked by smoke. I climbed out of a window
and stood on the ledge. Then I heard shouts from below that someone
was about to fall.
   ``I looked up and saw Isa a short distance away on the same
ledge. I ran over and grabbed him. I could see that he had turned
pale and was gasping for air. After about five minutes, I couldn't
feel his heartbeat,'' he told the newspapers.
   Kamli A. Rani, the Fire Department officer in charge of the
drill, said two generators were used to emit smoke and that the
smoke was not poisonous. He said the staff was told there would be a
drill Thursday but was not told what time it would be.
   Police said they would investigate the incident.
</TEXT>
