<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-15 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lankan Violence Continues, 20 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of 18 men were found near
the central city of Kandy on Friday, and residents said the victims
appeared to be Sinhalese radicals killed by pro-government groups.
   The government denied knowing the identities of the victims or
their killers but said two radicals were killed and 279 people
arrested in the continuing crackdown on militant members of the
Sinhalese majority.
   At least 18 partially burned bodies were found in three places
near Kandy, said residents speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In telephone interviews, they said they believed the victims were
Sinhalese radicals killed by pro-government vigilante groups.
Military officials in Colombo confirmed the bodies were found but
did not say who the dead were or who killed them.
   Opposition politicians and human rights organizations allege the
government has set up death squads to counter the campaign of
assassinations by the People's Liberation Front, an ultranationalist
guerrilla group trying to overthrow the government.
   The government denies the charge.
   Security forces arrested 279 suspects since Thursday in the
latest crackdown on the Sinhalese front in the south and center of
the island nation, a government statement said. The regions are
dominated by Sinhalese and are areas where the radical groups draw
most support.
   At least two radicals were killed during an army operation
Thursday in Matale district's Udwelgala village, 65 miles northeast
of Colombo, the communique said.
   It said at least 28 government buildings were burned by the
radicals during the last four days.
   It said 26 ``wanted subversives,'' the government term for
radicals, surrendered in central Sri Lanka during that period.
   The crackdown was launched after a conference of political
parties Wednesday aimed at ending Sri Lanka's ethnic strife.
   Although invited, the Sinhalese front did not attend the meeting.
The front has also rejected the government's earlier peace offers.
   The government says at least 5,000 people have been killed in the
2-year-old Sinhalese radical movement.
   Thousands of others have died in a war by the Tamil minority for
an independent Tamil nation.
   Former President Junius R. Jayewardene tried to end the Tamil war
with an accord in 1987, but it sparked the backlash by Sinhalese who
claimed it granted too many concessions to the Tamils.
   The radicals also oppose the deployment of Indian peacekeeping
soldiers in the northeast, invited to supervise the accord.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
claim they are discriminated against in jobs and education.
Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population and control the
government and the military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
