<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats 1stLd-Writethru a0480 09-15 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockwell Wants Liability Issue Resolved, Says Weapons Plant Could
Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, ``That would ...' with no progress
reported. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Rockwell addressed...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB UNRUH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp. may begin to shut down
the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant as early as today unless
federal agencies decide how it should handle the operation's wastes,
the company said.
   Rockwell, which operates the plant for the Department of Energy,
said Thursday it needs to know what its liability is for the
radioactive and hazardous wastes that are being stockpiled at the
plant where plutonium triggers for nuclear bombs are produced.
   ``I know we've expressed that concern to DOE, and have asked that
they reach some kind of resolution, by (today) if possible,'' said
Rockwell spokesman Dennis Hurtt.
   He said the company has various contingency plans if no
resolution is reached, including the beginning of a shutdown
procedure.
   ``That would always be an option, I suppose,'' he said. ``It's
something we'll have to wait and see.''
   Rockwell and Energy Department officials said there were no
further developments this morning. Officials with the Energy
Department and Environmental Protection Agency were working on the
matter in Washington.
   ``We're waiting at this point for an answer,'' said DOE spokesman
Tom Walton, acting public information officer at Rocky Flats.
   Rockwell addressed its concerns to the DOE, which owns the
facility, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the Colorado
Health Department and the U.S. Justice Department.
   The company said it is concerned improper handling of wastes can
lead to criminal charges against Rockwell employees and managers. A
mix of radioactive and hazardous wastes has built up for which there
is no federally approved disposal site available.
   ``We've got to have someone make some decisions,'' Hurtt said.
``The regulations have been changing and keep changing _ in recent
years very rapidly.''
   This is not the first time the liability issue has come up, or
that a possible closure has been threatened. But the earlier threat
in July came from within the Energy Department, which feared its
officials could face criminal charges over environmental violations
at the site 16 miles northeast of Denver.
   The acting DOE area manager at the time, Edward S. Goldberg,
threatened to close down the plant unless some immunity was granted
for those violations. As a result, the EPA and DOE agreed to come up
with a resolution to the situation by today _ the same deadline set
by Rockwell.
   An FBI affidavit unsealed in June alleged that workers at the
nuclear weapons plant dumped toxic chemicals into creeks that lead
to water supplies for four Denver suburbs and illegally burned
hazardous wastes at the site.
   Those allegations are being reviewed before a special grand jury.
   Rockwell has said its own investigation produced no evidence of
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
