<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     09-15 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Rejects Seoul's New Unification Formula</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea has rejected a
South Korean proposal to create a single Korean commonwealth as an
interim measure to unify the rival Korean states, officials said
Friday.
   The Rodong Shinmun, the newspaper of North Korea's ruling
Workers' Party, rejected the new South Korean plan as perpetuating
the division of the peninsula, said officials at South Korea's
National Unification Board.
   ``This (proposal) is only aimed at legalizing the existence of
two states on the peninsula and making them live separately
forever,'' the officials quoted the newspaper as saying.
   South Koran President Roh Tae-woo on Monday announced the
proposal, which calls for a single commonwealth as an interim
measure in merging the nations.
   To create a commonwealth, both Koreas should adopt a single
constitution, under which a free election should be held to form a
unified Korean state, Roh said.
   While rejecting Roh's proposal, the North Korean newspaper
repeated the North's long-standing formula to unify the peninsula
under a confederation that would keep the two sides' conflicting
political and economic systems intact, the officials said.
   The paper also demanded that the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in
South Korea under a mutual defense treaty be withdrawn before
creation of a single Korean state, officials said.
</TEXT>
