<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-AIDSCosts     09-15 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Costs,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early AIDS Detection, Treatment Could Cost Billions: Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early detection and treatment of those infected
with the AIDS virus may help avert one of the most serious epidemics
of our time, but the cost of doing so may push the U.S. health
system into chaos, medical researchers said today.
   The cost of finding and treating those who carry the virus but
are not yet ill could reach $5 billion or more a year,with urban
areas the hardest hit, researchers reported in today's Journal of
the American Medical Association.
   ``While the economic challenge of early intervention is
substantial for hard-hit regions, it can be managed if the federal
government takes on greater financial responsibility,'' said the
researchers from New York's Montefiore Medical Center and the
universities of North Carolina and California.
   Recent advances in the treatment of those infected with the virus
but who do not yet have full-fledged cases of AIDS make a compelling
case for expanding early treatment, said the researchers, led by
Montefiore's Peter Arno.
   Because of new antiviral therapies that slow the disease and
drugs that can prevent a common form of pneumonia associated with
the disease, early detection may slow the fatal disease's progress,
the researchers said.
   They suggested that policymakers devise a strategy that expands
the capabilities of hospital-affiliated out-patient clinics to
accommodate better patient monitoring and increased counseling.
   The authors estimate that the annual cost for a patient with no
symptoms would be about $854 until drug intervention is needed. Once
drugs and increased medical care are needed, a midrange estimate
would be about $9,600 annually, they said.
   If treatment were available to half of those infected with the
HIV virus today, the cost would be more than $4.8 billion, assuming
more than 1 million people currently carry the virus but are not yet
diagnosed with AIDS.
   The article also suggested overpricing by drug companies accounts
for a large portion of early treatment costs. Drug therapy will
account for approximately 80 percent of the cost of early
intervention, they said.
   One company's ability to market a drug without price restraints
has led to a quadrupling of its parent company's stock, it said.
   ``Although drug companies have a legitimate need to recoup their
(research) investments ... the public expects reasonable prices for
life-saving drugs,'' they wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Talks 1stLd-Writethru   09-15 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0488,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels, Government Agree on Plan for Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE ^By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvadoran government and leftist rebels
reached an agreement today calling for monthly talks mediated by the
Roman Catholic Church to end their nation's 10-year-old civil war,
officials said.
   A text of the agreement calls for talks every month, probably in
Costa Rica, to work out details of a cease-fire, of legalizing the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front guerrillas as a political
party, and of integrating the fighters back into civilian life.
   Roman Catholic Church leaders will act as mediators during the
talks, which will also be monitored by international observers,
unless both sides agree that a specific meeting should be private,
sources close to the negotiations said.
   Both of these points were concessions made by President Alfredo
Cristiani's U.S.-supported rightist government.
   ``We worked until one o'clock this morning. Everything went very
well. The text will be released today,'' said Jose Abelardo Torre, a
businessman and one of the five members of the Salvadoran government
delegation.
   Torre said both sides were holding a brief meeting this morning
to exchange more views and finalize details before issuing the joint
statement.
   Government delegates had been strongly opposed to the rebel
demand that church leaders and international observers be present at
the talks, arguing the dispute was a Salvadoran affair.
   The government also wanted the talks to be held every two months,
instead of monthly, as the rebels demanded.
   Ana Guadalupe Martinez, a guerrilla leader and member of the
leftist delegation, confirmed that both sides agreed the talks will
be held monthly.
   Asked if it meant the rebel demands had prevailed, she replied:
``I believe so, because they were the correct ones.''
   Torre and Martinez gave separate interviews to The Associated
Press.
   The Roman Catholic auxiliary bishop of El Salvador, Gregorio Rosa
Chavez, described the mood at the discussions as ``stupendous.''
   Speaking at a news conference Thursday night, he said the main
issues of the 10-point document were the cease-fire and bringing the
rebels into Salvadoran politicial life.
   Rosa Chavez said the first meeting probably would be held next
month.
   ``It's clear that the two sides have reached a clear agreement
that they should be attempting to reach not just a cease-fire but an
end to hostilities,'' Rosa Chavez said.
   ``I'm very content. I believe this is a very important day for
all Salvadorans,'' he said. ``You can't solve 10 years of war in 10
days, but putting ourselves on the path to peace is an important
achievement.''
   The current round of talks began Wednesday and were the first in
two years between the guerrilla group and the government. The talks
also were the first for the government of President Cristiani, who
took office June 1.
   Fighting continued Thursday in El Salvador, despite a unilateral
truce declared by the guerrillas.
   Army spokesmen in San Salvador said four rebels were killed and
that two guerrillas and one soldier were wounded. He also said a
helicopter was damaged and two buses were torched.
   Clandestine rebel radio in El Salvador said the army had provoked
clashes by moving into guerrilla-held territory in the north and
east.
   The civil war has claimed 70,000 lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
