<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     09-15 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Dismisses Marcos Petition to Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Friday rejected a
petition by Ferdinand Marcos to return home and agreed with
President Corazon Aquino that the former president's return would
threaten the nation.
   The judges voted 8-7 against Marcos' return, supporting the
government position that it would ``wipe away the gains achieved
during the past few years and lead to total economic collapse.''
   ``We cannot argue with that determination,'' the court wrote in a
30-page opinion.
   Marcos had appealed Mrs. Aquino's decision not allow him, his
wife Imelda and other family members to return to the Philippines.
Marcos has lived in exile in Hawaii since 1986 following a popular
uprising that brought Mrs. Aquino to power.
   Mrs. Aquino accuses Marcos of stealing billions of dollars during
his 20-year rule.
   In October, the United States indicted the Marcoses on criminal
racketeering charges for allegedly stealing more than $100 million
from the Philippine treasury and using it to buy art and real estate
in New York.
   Marcos, 72, has been hospitalized since January because of
deteriorating health.
