<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0585,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Flares Again as Lebanese Await Outcome of Peace Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 3 grafs to update casualty figures. Pickup 4th, `The
foreign...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rocket and artillery duels flared across
Beirut on Friday after a two-day lull, killing seven people and
raising doubts that Arab League efforts to end the bloodshed would
succeed.
   Beirut's shrunken population returned to underground shelters
overnight as the Syrian-Christian battles picked up. After a brief
morning break, the exchanges flared again in the afternoon, sending
scores of artillery rounds and rockets crashing into Christian east
Beirut and the Moslem sector in the west.
   Police said seven people were killed and 21 wounded, bringing the
overall toll to 902 killed and 2,613 wounded since the fighting
began March 8.
   The foreign ministers of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria ended
a two-day meeting in Saudi Arabia on Thursday and said they would
present to Arab leaders plans for ending the violence. Details of
the plans were expected to be released in a communique Saturday.
   The meetings were the first held by the mediation committee since
July 31, when the panel appointed accused Syria of blocking peace
efforts by refusing to withdraw its soldiers from Lebanon. The
committee was appointed by the Arab League in May to find a solution
to the crisis.
   Syria has 40,000 troops in Lebanon. They were deployed in 1976
under an Arab League mandate to quell the country's civil war but
have joined with Moslem militias to fight the mainly Christian
troops of Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' to drive out the
Syrians. The latest confrontation began in March after Aoun
blockaded militia-run ports. The Syrians responded by shelling the
310-square-mile Christian heartland north of Beirut.
   Syrian gunners, alternating between 130mm mortars and
multi-barraled rocket launchers, hammered east Beirut and the
surrounding Christian hinterland Friday.
   Aoun's gunners blasted west Beirut and hills to the southeast
with U.S.-made 155mm howitzers and mortars of various caliber.
   Radio stations interrupted programming to list the districts
targeted by the random barrages and urged residents to take
precautions.
   Only 10 percent of Beirut's 1.5 million people remain in the
city. The others have fled to safer areas of Lebanon or left the
country altogether.
   Residents appeared skeptical the Arab committee would succeed in
ending their agony.
   ``I don't think the committee will be able to solve our
problem,'' said Ahmed Hasbini, a bank employee, in Moslem west
Beirut.
   ``But I cannot stop hoping that someone, somehow will come up
with a solution, at least a truce that would put an end to the
present round of criminal madness.''
   Rashid Makkouk, a Sunni Moslem salesman, said of the new
shelling: ``We were under the impression that this is over, at least
for the time being.''
   ``We thought of taking a break from living in the underground
shelter. We started our evening in the apartment.
   ``We were watching television which interrupted programming to
report that the Arab committee has concluded its meeting, but no
cease-fire accord was reached.
   ``I was thinking whether we should return to the shelter when the
explosion of the first shell echoed. We rushed down,'' he said.
   ``Now they say a cease-fire will be announced Saturday. I can't
believe it anymore. I think we'll spend the winter as well in the
shelter.''
</TEXT>
