<FIRST>r i AM-DrugConference     09-15 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Conference,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law Enforcement Chiefs Consider Joint Anti-Drug Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officials ended a strategy
session for combatting drugs Friday with a pledge to work together
to defeat major traffickers and criminal syndicates like Colombia's
Medellin cartel.
   The delegates also sent a letter to Colombian President Virgilio
Barco pledging support for his ``courageous fight'' against the
syndicates.
   ``These criminal groups not only challenge the rule of law and
jeopardize the judicial structures of Colombian society, but they
challenge the nations of Latin America and the Caribbean regions and
the whole international community as well,'' the message said.
   ``In this context, we recognize that your struggle is our
struggle. The success of Colombia ... is of vital importance to us
all,'' the law enforcement officials said.
   Delegates from more than 100 countries attended the
U.N.-sponsored meeting.
   Interpol chief Raymond E. Kendall said drug offenses are taking
up 40 percent of the time and resources of the 147-nation police
network.
   Kendall pointed to a new telecommunications systems linking 28
Caribbean states in an information network as the kind of joint
project that can enhance surveillance and interception of drug
dealers. The network goes into operation next month.
   Delegates to the five-day conference called for harsher sentences
for convicted drug traffickers, including the death penalty, and
some argued for more severe treatment of drug users as well.
   Charles Saphos, chief of the narcotics and dangerous drugs
section of the U.S. Justice Department, called for measures to
``pierce all forms of bank secrecy'' so that governments can seize
illegal drug profits hidden in foreign banks.
   Colombia was to be represented at the meeting by a delegation led
by Miguel A. Gomez Padilla, director-general of the national police
force, but conference sources said the Colombian officials failed to
show up.
   They said the Colombians could have been detained because of
continued drug-related violence in their country.
</TEXT>
