<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Delivers Furious Tirade Upon Arrival At Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with defendant's outburst, and to delete
outdated material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Zsa Zsa Gabor came to court
today in a Rolls-Royce and a furious mood, calling the policeman who
arrested her during a traffic stop and everyone else involved in the
case a ``liar.''
   ``I like men of achievement, not a man with a gun. ... I should
have scratched his eyes out,'' Miss Gabor _ who is under court order
not to talk about the case _ told reporters outside the courtroom
where she is on trial on charges of slapping Officer Paul Kramer.
   ``I think that cop is not too bright. I think he must be very
spoiled because he's very sexy. He's gorgeous. He's sexy, but I
don't like that man,'' said the former beauty queen.
   Miss Gabor is charged with misdemeanor battery on a police
officer, disobeying an officer's orders, driving with an expired
license, and having an open container of alcohol in her car and an
expired car registration. A conviction carries a maximum two years
in jail and $4,000 fine.
   Kramer pulled her over on June 14 for having expired registration
licenses on her $215,000 Rolls-Royce Corniche convertible. As he
checked for violations, Miss Gabor allegedly drove off, was stopped
again and slapped Kramer's face.
   The outburst came before a second day of testimony. Questioned by
Deputy District Attorney Elden Fox and defense attorney William
Graysen, Kramer had testified Thursday that Miss Gabor cursed, spit
on him and slapped him.
   Miss Gabor's diatribe began at the curb outside the courthouse,
where she alighted from the Rolls in a trouser outfit of black
pants, black-and-white polka dot top with a red silk corsage on the
left shoulder.
   ``This man is the biggest liar and the Police Department is the
biggest liar in the world,'' Miss Gabor charged, ignoring pleas from
her attorney reminding her about the gag order in the case.
   ``The officer's a liar and the district attorney's a liar. Every
word of it is a lie. I was there,'' she said.
   ``He's a vulgar policeman and he's a liar,'' the actress said.
   Graysen said prior to Miss Gabor's arrival that she was ``a
strong woman'' and ``she's holding up well.''
   Thursday's testimony featured a recreation of the traffic stop
that ended in a minor altercation and Miss Gabor's arrest.
   ``Officer, you promise not to strike my client?'' the defense
attorney asked in jest at one point.
   Recounting the incident, Kramer said Miss Gabor screamed at him,
``Do you know who I am?''
   ``She closed the door and she spun around and slapped me on the
side of the face. I was very surprised,'' Kramer testified.
   Kramer, under cross-examination, was asked to stand alongside
Miss Gabor, as he wore his helmet and sunglasses.
   ``I'm afraid of him,'' said the 5-foot-3 actress as she stood
next to the 6-foot-4 officer within inches of the jury box on
Thursday. Smiling, she demonstrated a strike to Kramer's left cheek,
showing it was a considerable reach.
   ``I didn't realize he was so tall. He is very gorgeous,'' Miss
Gabor said during a break in testimony.
   Jurors also heard a recorded police radio transmission of Miss
Gabor's traffic stop and Kramer's inquiry for a computer check on a
date of birth for the actress. The answer came back as June 6, 1923.
   An enlarged copy of Miss Gabor's drivers license was displayed to
jurors and it showed the birthdate had been altered. Asked why he
didn't issue a misdemeanor citation for an altered license, Kramer
said, ``It was an amateur job of alteration.''
   Fox said witnesses will prove the officer's actions were
professional throughout the 15-minute episode.
   When she arrived in court Thursday, Miss Gabor deflected
questions about her age, which ranges from 62 to 70, depending on
the source.
   ``The only good thing that comes out of this is my face cream
sells like hot cakes,'' the former Miss Hungary and cosmetics
entrepreneur concluded.
   Graysen said in his statement that Kramer overreacted and Miss
Gabor acted in self-defense.
   Witnesses will show there is a pattern of excessive force by
Kramer and a coverup of that behavior by the Police Department, he
said.
   ``He's a bad cop,'' Graysen said.
</TEXT>
