<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     09-15 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Sentencing of Tanker Captain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday refused to
sentence the captain and owner of an oil tanker that spilled nearly
300,000 gallons of heating oil off Newport until he knows more about
their records and willingness to pay damages.
   U.S. District Judge Ernest C. Torres demanded specifics about the
extent to which Ballard Shipping Co. and its insurers were prepared
to pay for cleaning up the spill from the tanker World Prodigy,
which ran aground June 23.
   The Coast Guard estimates the cleanup at $3 million.
   Torres scheduled a new hearing in two weeks.
   Ballard, a Liberian company operating from Greece, and Capt.
Iakovos Georgudis pleaded guilty Aug. 16 to one count apiece of
violating the federal Clean Water Act. The agreement called for
fines of $10,000 against Georgudis and $500,000 that Ballard would
pay to the state for environmental research and acquisition of
coastal property.
   The delay in sentencing also canceled plans for Georgudis, 43, of
Athens, Greece, to plead guilty and be fined the maximum of $20,000
on state charges of polluting coastal waters and failing to have a
harbor pilot aboard, said Thomas Connell, a spokesman for Attorney
General James E. O'Neil.
   Torres said he had not received information he had requested
about the previous environmental record of Georgudis, Ballard and
its owners.
   Bradford Gorham, Ballard's attorney, said the shipper's insurers
promised to cover $3.2 million in federal environmental damage, $1
million in state cleanup costs and $3.5 million in unspecified other
costs, such as those incurred by businesses hurt by the spill.
   ``The judge now wants to know more about the people behind
Ballard,'' Gorham said. ``I'm not sure until I talk to my clients
what that information can be.''
   John A. MacFadyen, the captain's lawyer, said it was up to
Ballard to provide the information and he declined to comment
further.
   According to testimony at a Coast Guard hearing, Georgudis and a
helmsman were on the tanker's bridge when it ran aground at Brenton
Reef, about a mile south of Newport, and ripped two large gashes in
its hull.
   The heating oil that spilled into Rhode Island Sound forced
beaches to close and killed young fish and lobsters. Most beaches
reopened within a week as the oil evaporated or was cleaned up.
   Georgudis told Gov. Edward D. DiPrete he erred by not waiting for
a harbor pilot before proceeding into the treacherous waters near
the mouth of Narragansett Bay.
</TEXT>
