<SECOND>AM-Swindall-Bar,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swindall, Bar Reach Agreement for Suspension Pending Perjury Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Bar of Georgia has agreed not to push
for disbarment of former Rep. Pat Swindall, and he has accepted
temporary suspension of his law license during appeal of federal
perjury convictions.
   C. David Butler, an attorney who is serving as special master in
the bar association's disbarment case against Swindall, said Friday
that lawyers for the two sides agreed to the deal Thursday.
   Butler said he will submit the agreement to the state Supreme
Court, which must approve it, as soon as the paperwork is complete.
   ``After the (Swindall's) appeal has run its course, I will
conduct a hearing to see what should be done,'' Butler said.
   Swindall, a Republican, was convicted by a U.S. District Court
jury in June of nine counts of lying to a federal grand jury in a
money-laundering case. Swindall had been called to testify to the
grand jury about his negotiations for a home loan from an undercover
agent posing as a money launderer.
   Swindall, maintaining his innocence, has appealed the conviction
to the 11th U.S. Circuit.
   Butler said it was his understanding that Swindall is not
practicing law.
   Swindall, then a virtual political unknown, defeated Rep. Elliot
Levitas in 1984 to represent suburban Atlanta's 4th District. He was
re-elected in 1986 but lost his seat to Democrat Ben Jones last year
amid his legal troubles.
