<FIRST>r a AM-ShockRadio     09-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shock Radio,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Chairman Urges Voluntary Code Against `Shock Radio'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission chairman
urged the nation's broadcasters Friday to tune out ``shock radio,''
programs that use sexually and racially oriented humor to attract
audiences.
   ``We are not simply recorders, transmitters and antennas,''
Alfred Sikes told those attending the National Association of
Broadcasters radio convention. ``We are what we broadcast.''
   Sikes, a former owner of several radio stations, said the
association should revive its programming code, dropped in the early
1980s as the result of a federal anti-trust lawsuit against
provisions regarding commercials.
   Such standards should be drawn up by the industry, without
government pressure, said Sikes, who took over the FCC chair in
August.
   The FCC on Aug. 24 said it was taking enforcement action against
three stations _ WLUP-AM in Chicago, KSJO-FM in San Jose, Calif.,
and WFBQ-FM in Indianapolis _ ``which may have broadcast indecent
programs in violation of the law.''
   The stations were given 30 days to respond to FCC inquiries,
which the agency said were based on a review of public complaints.
According to FCC transcripts, the material involved sexually
oriented humor broadcast during daytime hours.
   ``I know that people say the commissioners were simply responding
to congressional pressures,'' Sikes said. ``But, in that regard, let
me say this: You really ought to first read the program material
which we cited, and also note that it was being broadcast at a time
when children almost certainly were listening.''
   NAB President Edward Fritts said the organization could not
consider a new code unless Congress approves pending legislation
granting the broadcast industry an anti-trust exemption for
programming content codes.

</TEXT>
