<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Drugs 3rdLd-Writethru a0592 09-15 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0592,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Flexible on Funding War on Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, editing throughout to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he's ready to deal
with Democrats on how to pay for the war on drugs, declaring ``we're
flexible in terms of the funding method.''
   However, the president repeated his objections to any proposal
that includes either a tax increase or deep military spending cuts.
   ``We can't afford to sacrifice our military preparedness,'' Bush
said in a question-and-answer session with a group of out-of-town
reporters he invited to a White House lunch.
   The administration has previously voiced opposition to a proposal
by Senate Democratic Leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia that it
claims would make unacceptably sharp cuts in defense spending.
   Bush indicated he still prefers his own formula for raising the
$717 million in additional spending above the $7.1 billion he had
previously proposed for anti-drug spending in the fiscal year that
begins on Oct. 1.
   However, as negotiations were set to begin with congressional
Democrats on a compromise, Bush said: ``We're flexible in terms of
the funding method, but I strongly believe that we must retain the
integrated elements of this drug strategy which took more than six
months to develop.''
   Bush also repeated his opposition to new taxes to pay for the war
on crime and drugs, although he acknowledged that states and some
local governments might need to raise taxes to help pay for new
prisons.
   ``That's up to them. I'm not going to criticize a governor or a
municipality that has to do something on the revenue side,'' Bush
said.
   Earlier today, civil rights leader Jesse Jackson called Bush's
drug plan inadequate.
   ``I submit that we cannot expect Mr. Bush and (drug policy chief
William) Bennett to come up with a plan to deal with drugs in our
community,'' Jackson told a House panel. ``The drug war does not
begin at the White House. It begins at our house.''
   Bennett conceded the administration will not likely get the
budget offsets in the categories Bush suggested to fund the drug war.
   ``That doesn't seem to be the game in town right now,'' Bennett
told the reporters at the White House.
   He said it was likely what ``we're going to talk about is some
kind of across-the-board reductions. Rather than taking money out of
this box and putting it in this box, you may see some small fraction
of a percentage reduction'' throughout the budget.
   Jackson and Bennett shook hands warmly before addressing the
House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, but in his
remarks Jackson was critical of both Bush and Bennett.
   ``In April, Mr. Bennett announced that he would take
comprehensive emergency action to attack the drug crisis in the
nation's capital,'' Jackson said in comments marked by repeated
applause from spectators as well as a few shouts of approval. ``Five
months later, we still have the emergency but no action.''
   ``President Bush announced a drug plan for Bogota, Colombia.
Where is his plan for the District of Columbia and cities across the
nation?'' said Jackson, who has been mentioned as possible mayoral
candidate in the capital.
   He said more money than the $7.9 billion envisioned by Bush was
needed to do the job as well as input from community leaders who
have first-hand experience with fighting the drug problem.
   Meantime, Senate negotiations on financing the war on drugs got
under way, with Democrats demanding a boost in funding and
Republicans saying more money was less important than quick action
on the plan.
   In the House, many lawmakers appeared cool to a proposal from
Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., to gain an additional $2.2 billion for
the $7.9 billion drug war through a half-percent cut in federal
programs across the board.
   Elsewhere Thursday, Bennett got into a sharply worded exchange
with Democrats on the House Government Operations Committee while
lobbying for the administration plan.
   The task force includes nine Democrats and nine Republicans, and
Dole said Bennett and Bush administration budget director Richard
Darman would be in on the talks.
   ``This thing could take a couple of weeks,'' Dole said. He said
Republicans might freeze Senate action on a dozen money bills only
two weeks from the start of fiscal 1990 unless the negotiations
produced results.
   Majority Democrats control the Senate, but the GOP could use the
rules to block the money bills.
   Byrd's proposed across-the-board cut remains attached to a money
bill for transportation programs that is awaiting final action in
the Senate. Republicans oppose the measure, which would delete $1.8
billion from the Defense Department's budget.
