<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-15 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Katie Bethel scooped up Larry the caiman
in her arms, gave him a kiss and took him home, thus ending his
three-month stint behind bars.
   ``C'mon, Larry, let's blow this hole. Let's go home,'' Bethel
said Thursday as she paid $121 to gain freedom for her grinning
3{-foot reptile from the Tri-City Animal Shelter.
   The reportedly warm-hearted caiman was nose-cuffed and taken to
the shelter July 12 after he was found strolling along Tulane Street.
   When Bethel initially tried to retrieve him, she learned he could
be sprung only if she got exotic animal permits from the state and
Union City.
   She did that this week, and Larry is a free man, or cai-man.
   But left behind at least one new friend.
   ``He's great,'' said shelter supervisor Nancy Talamantez. ``He's
superfriendly, almost too friendly. He's a spoiled brat.''
   Although caimans have a reputation for being meaner than their
relatives, the alligators and crocodiles, Talamantez said Larry is
the exception.
   Bethel promised Larry a homecoming feast of pork chops, ground
beef, apple sauce and ``whatever anybody else is eating.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HORSE CREEK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candace and David Kirkman lived in North
Carolina and dreamed of a home in the West. They've got that now and
more.
   The Kirkmans bought Horse Creek, the whole town.
   Horse Creek, which the Kirkmans learned of in an advertisement,
consists of a general store and bar, post office, a house, horse
barn and a repair garage on 17 acres of land.
   ``I love it,'' said Mrs. Kirkman. ``I love it.''
   The two, who are from Randleman, N.C., bought the town from Tony
Schepp, who operated all the businesses in the area, referred to as
``Schepp's Corner'' for almost 40 years with his wife, Marian.
   Schepp was bartender and mechanic and helped in the store; his
wife was postmistress, store keeper and homemaker.
   Schepp's Corner served as a gathering spot for people in the area
until the nearby Great Western Limestone Mine closed in 1978,
curtailing business severely.
   And since the death of Mrs. Schepp several years ago, the
settlement has been little more than a post office, with the general
store, bar and repair shop closed.
   But the Kirkmans have plans for their move in October.
   Candace Kirkman has discussed keeping a coffee pot going through
the day in the post office and serving rolls and cookies to people
who pick up their mail, as well as serving meals several times a
week.
   ``We want to make it a little general store, too,'' she said.
</TEXT>
