<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1537EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Cities     09-15 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Cities,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>League of Cities President Asks for Big Hike in Drug-Fighting Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National League of Cities President Terry
Goddard said Friday the federal drug-fighting budget for 1990 should
be increased by $5 billion to $6 billion over the administration's
proposed $7.9 billion, and that taxes should be raised to pay for it.
   New resources are needed, said the mayor of Phoenix, Ariz., and
``I haven't figured out another way to get new resources.''
   Commenting on President Bush's oft-stated opposition to new taxes
_ ``Read my lips: no new taxes'' _ Goddard said, ``Some of us are
illiterate.''
   The Democratic mayor said the strategy will call on state and
local governments to spend $10 billion to $12 billion for drug
testing and prisons next year alone. ``We believe that an equivalent
resource from the federal government has got to be committed,'' he
said.
   ``We've just gone through a bailout of the savings and loans,
where really no questions were asked and the money simply
appeared,'' he said.
   ``We are at the same level of urgency, or significantly greater
level of urgency, because people are dying,'' he said. ``I'm not
sure anybody died in the savings and loans. In fact, I'm pretty sure
they didn't.''
   Goddard, who was meeting with Bush Friday afternoon, said paying
for the strategy by taking funds away from immigration, juvenile
justice and housing programs is a ``shell game.''
   He likened such a rearrangement of resources to ``asking Dwight
Eisenhower to finance the Normandy invasion by selling his landing
craft. Those programs are important to establishing a climate in our
cities which will keep drugs at bay.''
   Goddard called for a ``significant amount'' to be allocated
directly to cities so they wouldn't run into a ``logjam'' of state
bureaucracies, but he declined to say how much money the cities
should get.
   He said he is asking municipal leaders to lobby Capitol Hill,
where some members of Congress already are balking at a proposal by
Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., to increase the $7.9 billion by $2.2
billion.
</TEXT>
