<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1548EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Spies     09-15 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Spies,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Worried About Spies Among Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Counterintelligence officials said
Friday they are worried Communist East Germany may have slipped
spies among refugees coming from Hungary, and they promised to help
any spies who turn themselves in.
   West Germany has been a playground for spies since the advent of
the Cold War, with agents from several East bloc countries snooping
around for NATO military secrets and sensitive high-tech know-how.
   Some of the hundreds of spies caught in the past were East
Germans who came over to West Germany either as escapees or as legal
emigres.
   Peter Frisch, vice president of West Germany's main
counterintelligence agency, the Constitutional Protection Office,
said there may have been agents or would-be agents among the recent
flood of East German refugees to the West.
   ``This is a possibility we must reckon with. It's something we
must be alert to,'' said Frisch.
   He appealed to any East German refugees who have ``obligated
themselves'' to East German intelligence to telephone the
Constitutional Protection Office in Cologne. ``We can help them,''
he said.
   Frisch said that even if a refugee had committed himself to spy
for East Germany, he would not be prosecuted if he had not yet begun
his work.
   Intelligence officials say dramatically reduced East-West
tensions have not reduced East bloc espionage. Sixty suspected spies
were nabbed in West Germany last year, compared with 34 the year
before.
   A 69-year-old man was arrested last month for allegedly acting as
an East German informer more than 30 years.
   Some of the world's most famous spy scandals have erupted in West
Germany, such as the 1974 exposure of Guenter Guillaume, a close
adviser to then-Chancellor Willy Brandt, as an East German agent.
The disclosure shocked the nation and resulted in Brandt's
resignation.
   There also have been instances of so-called ``Romeo spies''
coming to West Germany from the East and building a seemingly
innocent life with a respectable job, but at some point romancing
government secretaries, exchanging love and companionship for
secrets.
   West German intelligence officials say they have no indications
there are spies among the estimated 14,000 East Germans who arrived
in the past week but that the possibility cannot be excluded.
   Hans-Gert Lange, spokesman for the Constitutional Protection
Office, said that sometimes East Germans who ask to leave for the
West are first coerced into making deals with East German
intelligence.
   ``Permission to leave would be dependent on making an agreement.
If they climb to important positions (in the West) where they might
be useful, the agreement could be activated,'' he said.
</TEXT>
