<FIRST>r a AM-People-Calloway     09-15 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Calloway,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cab Calloway Back on Stage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cab Calloway is performing again after a serious
illness, lighting up the stage of Manhattan's Beacon Theater. But he
longs for another stage, where he made his name more than 50 years
ago _ Harlem's Cotton Club.
   ``I miss it,'' the 82-year-old entertainer said recently.
``Singers, dancers, comedians, we had them all. Oh God, were they
good!''
   Not that the performers who share the bill with Calloway are
chopped liver. His daughter Chris will perform (``She's a block off
the old chip''), along with two dancers, the Williams Brothers.
   ``They have the knack, the desire to entertain. They do it for
the public. That's my style. My public is the important thing to me.
They could have fit into the Cotton Club,'' Calloway says.
   The man who made ``Minnie the Moocher'' famous fell ill at the
end of last year while touring in Japan. While recuperating, he
toured jazz festivals in Europe.
   ``You know, `Sesame Street'' still does a piece of mine on TV,''
he says. ``When I hear it, it makes me feel like I'm living all over
again. I live for music.''
</TEXT>
