<FIRST>r w AM-IndustrialProduction     09-15 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Industrial Production,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industrial Production Rose 0.3 Percent In August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial production recorded its biggest gain
in four months in August, the government said Friday in a report
that drew mixed reaction to the 0.3 percent gain.
   The Federal Reserve Board said the August production rate
followed revised increases of 0.1 percent in July and 0.2 percent in
June after remaining flat in May.
   The Fed originally had reported production rose 0.2 percent in
July, but fell 0.1 percent in both May and June. Production was up
0.7 percent in April.
   ``That's not only stronger than expected, but the revisions were
substantial. The economy never really slowed down,'' said Michael K.
Evans of Evans Economics Inc., a Washington consulting firm.
   However, William K. MacReynolds, forecasting director of the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, said the gain was only 2.8 percent over August
of last year after rising 5.7 percent in 1988.
   ``Growth in the manufacturing sector has been sluggish throughout
1989, falling farther behind the growth in the services sector,'' he
said.
   The Fed credited almost all the August growth to a rebound in
production at auto factories and a pickup in coal mining following a
strike.
   ``Excluding motor vehicles, output of both consumer goods and
business equipment was sluggish during the summer,'' it said.
   At the same time, the central bank reported that the operating
rate of the nation's factories, mines and utilities remained
unchanged at 83.8 percent of capacity in August. The operating rate
measures not only output, but also changes in productivity levels.
   Factory use had declined 0.1 percentage point in June, the
central bank said. The rate had hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent
in December 1988 and last January. Last month's operating rate also
was unchanged from August 1988.
   ``Unchanged capacity utilization in August signals the likelihood
that inflationary pressures have declined substantially in the last
several months,'' MacReynolds said.
   The closer U.S. industry gets to full operating capacity, the
greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading
to shortages and price increases. Analysts generally consider an
operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of
inflationary pressures.
   The Federal Reserve has been walking a fine line of keeping
interest rates high enough to cool inflationary pressures without
slowing growth so much that the economy slides into a recession.
   Industrial production at manufacturing plants making both durable
and non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent last month after remaining
flat in July and increasing 0.3 percent in June. Output was up 2.3
percent at mines and oil wells but fell 1 percent at utilities.
   The Fed said its industrial production index in August stood at
142.4 percent of its 1977 base, up from 142 percent in July.
   At the same time, the operating rate rose 0.1 percentage point to
84 percent at manufacturing plants. The rate had peaked at 84.7
percent in January.
   The rate at factories producing durable goods _ big-ticket items
expected to last more than three years _ rose 0.2 percentage point
to 82.6 percent. The rate at factories producing non-durable goods
fell from 86.4 percent in July to 86.1 percent in August.
  
</TEXT>
