<FIRST>r i AM-MotherTeresa     09-15 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother Teresa,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Faces New Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa may have
developed an infection that poses a new danger to her health
following a heart attack last week, her cardiologist said Friday.
   Another doctor who spoke on condition of anonymity said too many
visitors and doctors may be hampering Mother Teresa's chances for
recovery.
   Dr. Vincenzo Bilotta, a heart specialist from Rome and a longtime
friend of Mother Teresa, said the 79-year-old Roman Catholic nun is
fighting a persistent fever and chest pains.
   ``With the high temperature, her condition is still serious,''
said Bilotta, who treated Mother Teresa for a similar ailment in
1985.
   ``Her heart is very weak. The infection is now posing a new
danger to her,'' he added, without saying where the infection may
have developed.
   Dr. George Lombardi, an infectious disease specialist from
Cornell University in New York, said doctors are trying to find the
cause of the infection.
   Lombardi and Bilotta flew to Calcutta earlier in the week to help
treat Mother Teresa, who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979
for her devotion to the destitute and dying.
   A statement from Woodlands Nursing Home, where she was admitted
last week, said ``Mother is still running a temperature. She has had
a mild episode of chest pain which rapidly responded to treatment.''
   Mother Teresa developed chest pains and high fever Thursday just
as doctors thought she was recovering well from a heart attack
suffered Sept. 8.
   A senior physician said Friday she may have suffered a setback
because too many doctors want to treat her and too many people want
to visit her.
   ``What can the hospital management do if the prime minister, the
chief minister, the health minister and other dignitaries keep
coming to visit?'' he said on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier this week, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi visited Mother
Teresa in the intensive care unit along with his security staff and
a television crew to film the 10-minute chat.
   Mother Teresa was born in Yugoslavia and gave up a comfortable
life as a convent teacher to live and work in Calcutta's squalid
slums. She founded the Missionaries of Charity in October 1950 in an
abandoned hostel.
</TEXT>
