<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Savimbi     09-15 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Savimbi,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Leader May Meet With Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi will visit
the United States next month to meet with U.S. officials, possibly
including President Bush, official and private sources said Friday.
   Savimbi, who heads the Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) has been invited by the Senate Task Force on Angola and will
arrive here Oct. 2, said a source close to his organization.
   ``A meeting with Bush is under consideration, but it's quite
possible,'' said an administration official who asked not to be
named.
   The official said Savimbi would brief the administration about
the precarious peace talks between his organization and the Marxist
government of Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
   He is also expected to discuss the terms of the truce accord and
to ask for U.S. support in achieving closer U.N. monitoring of the
pullout of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   UNITA and the government agreed on a truce to end their 14-year
war at a meeting in Gbadolite, Zaire last June, but the cease-fire
collapsed soon after and hundreds have died in the ensuing clashes.
   The agreement has also been endangered by questions about
Savimbi's fate. Angola contends Savimbi agreed to go into temporary
exile and integrate his troops into the Angolan military. But
Savimbi denied this and accused the Angolans of lying about the
closed-door meeting in Gbadolite, Zaire.
   The State Department has been seeking to bring the sides back to
the negotiating table and a meeting has been scheduled for Monday in
Kinshasa. Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen was in Zaire
this week to help arrange the meeting.
   The United States has promised Savimbi that it will maintain its
military and financial support of UNITA until a final peace
agreement is reached which allows free elections.
   The Soviet Union, which backs the government in Luanda, has also
pledged its support until peace is achieved.
   The Angolan peace talks are a result of the U.S. and
Soviet-sponsored agreement signed last December for the pullout of
some 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola. The pullout has been conducted
according to plan and is expected to be completed on schedule in
1991.
   Savimbi, who once studied in the United States, last visited here
in 1988 and met with former President Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
