<DOCNO> AP890915-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1855EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FishInspections     09-15 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Inspections,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Envisions Large-Scale Effort to Make Fish Safe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel began considering a bill Friday
that would require health inspection of fish and shellfish, the
first effort to establish a comprehensive program to regulate the
fishing industry.
   ``Currently, many consumers are wary about the safety of fish,''
said Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., who introduced the bill. ``They
have heard many stories about contamination from toxic industrial
and agricultural chemicals, medical waste products and red tides.''
   The ``Fish and Fish Products Safety Act of 1989'' would require
setting safety standards for contaminants for fish and establishing
a rigorous and comprehensive inspection system.
   Officials say it is more difficult to regulate fishing than the
meat or poultry industry because there are 300 edible species of
fish in vast waters.
   Contaminants for fish and shellfish include the botulism toxin,
salmonella bacteria and the hepatitis-A virus, as well as PCBs and
other industrial contaminants.
   Dr. Frank Young, head of the Food and Drug Administration,
testified before Waxman's House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
health and the environment that fish consumption increased to 15.4
pounds person in 1987 largely because the food is low in fat.
   Young said the FDA inspects only a quarter of the fish-processing
plants each year. He said data from the federal Centers for Disease
Control ``indicate that seafood does not cause illness in alarming
amounts or diversity.''
   However, Ellen Haas of Public Voice, a non-profit group that
deals with food safety issues, disagreed.
   She offered a CDC study that indicated that the risk of a food
poisoning outbreak from eating seafood is 25 times greater from
seafood than from beef, and 16 times greater than for either chicken
or pork.
   Dr. Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the food safety and
inspection service at the Agriculture Department, said that
``building on the existing meat and poultry inspection program
structure would provide a faster start up and extensive cost-savings
for a fish and seafood inspection program.''
   Legislation has been introduced in the past to give the
Agriculture Department authority over seafood inspections, just as
it is in charge of meat and poultry inspections. The Waxman bill
would make the FDA the lead agency.
   Waxman said in his opening statement Friday that ``the most
contentious issue has become one of turf _ where authority over the
new fish inspection program should be vested.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     09-15 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptian Plan Presented to Israel's Divided Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's four top leaders quarreled heatedly
Friday over an Egyptian plan for Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
that threatens to divide the Jewish state's coalition government.
   A Labor Party official who requested anonymity said the
left-leaning party sees ``no need to stay in the government'' if
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc does not agree
to the talks.
   The two parties are divided over the Egyptian plan's insistence
on a U.S.-backed formula of trading occupied territory for peace.
   In the occupied territories Friday, Arab reports said Israeli
soldiers shot and killed two Palestinian youths, including a
12-year-old. The army said soldiers did not open fire in the area
where the child was killed.
   A spokesman for Finance Minister Shimon Peres, the Labor Party
leader, said Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny on Friday
formally presented Israeli leaders with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's proposal.
   Peres, Shamir, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of the Labor Party
and Foreign Minister Moshe Arens of Likud discussed the plan.
   Israel radio reported they disagreed sharply about the proposals,
which the Labor Party supports.
   A major controversy is Mubarak's offer to sponsor peace talks
between Israel and a 12-member Palestinian delegation, including two
Arabs deported from the occupied territories. This is intended to
satisfy both Israel's demand to talk only to Palestinians from the
territories and the PLO's insistence that Palestinians living abroad
be included.
   ``Deportees are not exactly outside Palestinians ... I would not
be quick to reject this possibility,'' Peres said in an interview
with the English-language Jerusalem Post.
   Israeli newspapers identified possible negotiators as deportees
Mohammed Milhem, a former West Bank mayor, and Akram Haniyeh,
formerly a newspaper editor in east Jerusalem, both senior PLO
officials.
   The Likud bloc is balking about negotiating with the PLO, which
Israel brands a terrorist organization.
   ``We have closed the door to the PLO, so the Egyptians have
decided to push the PLO through the window,'' Likud legislator
Eliyahu Ben Elissar told Israel radio.
   Transport Minister Moshe Katzav, also of Likud, told the daily
Yediot Ahronot that anyone who accepts the plan ``wants to break up
the national unity government.''
   Shamir wants to resolve the deadlock before visits to the United
States next week by Arens and Peres.
   Peres, who leaves Saturday and is scheduled to meet President
Bush, said in an interview published in Friday's Jerusalem Post that
the U.S. role in promoting Egypt's proposal is crucial.
   Palestinian sources in Tunisia said Friday the PLO central
council will consider the Egyptian plan in mid-October.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, Palestinian reporters said Tarek
Said Tuffah, 12, was killed by an army sniper during a
stone-throwing riot. An army spokesman said troops did not fire in
the area.
   The spokesman said a patrol commander shot and killed a second
Palestinian when troops were attacked by youths throwing iron bars
and cement blocks. Arab reporters said Ata Yunis, 18, was killed in
a clash with troops during Tuffah's funeral.
   Six other Palestinians were reported shot and wounded by the army.
   In the Gaza Strip, masked Arab assailants hacked and seriously
wounded a 35-year-old woman accused of collaborating with Israel,
Arab reports said.
   Friday's deaths raised the toll to 570 Palestinians killed in the
21-month-old uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip. Forty Israelis have died, and 114 suspected
collaborators have been killed by fellow Palestinians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
