<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Romanov     09-15 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Romanov,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Gorbachev Contender's Letter Appears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily Pravda published a letter
Friday from a Politburo member once thought to be a challenger to
Mikhail S. Gorbachev in which he denied celebrating his daughter's
wedding in a former czarist palace with the czar's tableware.
   The letter from Grigory V. Romanov, former Leningrad Communist
Party chief, was his first publication in the official press since
he was retired from the Politburo on July 1, 1985, less than four
months after Gorbachev became party chief.
   Rumors of corruption followed the 66-year-old Romanov to Moscow
when he became a member of the Communist Party's ruling body in
1976, but he was considered Gorbachev's leading challenger when the
current Soviet leader assumed power.
   According to one widespread rumor, Romanov held his daughter's
wedding in one of the former czarist capital's palaces while he was
Leningrad party chief and took the czar's tableware from the
Hermitage museum for the wedding dinner.
   Some priceless tableware was smashed during a wild wedding party,
says one variant of the rumor.
   Romanov said in a three-paragraph letter published on Pravda's
third page that a parliamentary commission had investigated the
allegations.
   The wedding dinner actually was for only 12 people and was held
in a small country house, Romanov said.
   ``There was no czarist tableware from the Hermitage,'' he wrote.
   ``On this account, Pravda has all documents, including the
conclusion of a commission of the Supreme Soviet of the Russian
republic, which specially investigated these questions,'' the letter
said.
</TEXT>
