<SECOND>AM-Golden Lion,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Movie From Taiwan Wins Venice Film Festival Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Venice Film Festival on Friday awarded
its Golden Lion Award for best film to ``A City of Sadness'' by
Taiwanese director Hou Xiaoxian.
   The film covers the saga of a father and his four children to
portray the history of Taiwan after World War II, from the Japanese
surrender to the arrival of the defeated Nationalist Chinese from
the mainland.
   ``Like most Chinese films, the film is a huge family melodrama,''
the 42-year-old director said in a recent newspaper interview.
   The film was considered one of the favorites for the festival's
top prize.
   For the second straight year, the international jury divided the
prizes for best performances between two actors and two actresses.
   Italians Marcello Mastroianni and Massimo Troisi, who appeared in
Ettore Scola's ``What Time Is It?'' shared the award for best actor.
   Dame Peggy Ashcroft and Geraldine James of Britain shared the
best actress prize for their roles in Peter Hall's ``She's Been
Away.''
   Twenty-three films from 21 countries entered the competition for
prizes. It was the festival's 46th year.
