<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TeenJustice     09-15 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Justice,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-agers Impose Justice on Peers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DADE CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury of teen-agers let two boys walk on
charges of stealing a bicycle but convicted two others of automobile
theft in a courtroom experiment to let young scofflaws be judged by
their peers.
   Circuit Judge Maynard Swanson Jr. had the final say Thursday and
partially disagreed with the verdicts of the six-member jury from
Zephyrhills High School. It was the first of semimonthly sessions
endorsed by judges, educators and Pasco County officials.
   The jury, volunteers from a class on the law, deliberated about
20 minutes before finding a 14-year-old boy and a 16-year-old boy
innocent of stealing the bicycle, but Swanson overruled the panel.
He explained to the jurors there was enough proof to support a
guilty verdict. The judge withheld a finding of guilt, placed the
pair on probation and ordered them to pay restitution.
   The jury contended that the prosecutor, a real one, never tied
the boys to the theft and that others were involved but avoided
getting hauled into court.
   ``If they got off with it the others should have, too,'' said
juror Sarah Chancery, a senior.
   In the other case, the jury found two boys guilty of auto theft
but innocent of a burglary charge. This time, the judge agreed.
   ``I thought you were very astute,'' Swanson told the jury.
   The boys, whose ages were not available, will be punished later
this month by the judge.
   Teacher Cynthia Brendle said the experiment is a lively way for
students to learn about the law and also should serve as a deterrent
to youngsters who face criminal charges.
</TEXT>
