<FIRST>r w AM-US-Korea-Nuclear     09-15 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea-Nuclear,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Concerned North Korea Developing Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department registered on Friday its
continuing concern that North Korea may be developing nuclear
weapons, but said it was unaware of any development that would
heighten the concern.
   Earlier, the South Korean news agency Yonhap quoted a department
official as saying the U.S. government was ``gravely concerned'' and
was keeping a close watch on possible efforts to develop nuclear
weapons.
   The news agency quoted Spencer Richardson, the head of the
department's Korea section, as saying the Soviet Union would be as
concerned if North Korea produced such weapons.
   While denying it has nuclear weapons, North Korea has repeatedly
charged that U.S. forces based in South Korea were equipped with
nuclear arms and were preparing for a nuclear war on the divided
Korean peninsula. U.S. officials have rejected the North Korean
claims.
   The United States garrisons about 43,000 troops in South Korea
under a defense pact. The Soviet Union is the communist North's main
arms supplier.
   Asked about the Yonhap report, Richard Boucher, the State
Department spokesman, said: ``I don't have anything new to express
our concern.''
   He added: ``I think we've talked very often in our past about the
need for North Korea to put its nuclear programs under international
safeguards. They reached some sort of agreement way back in 1985
with the International Atomic Energy Agency that they would do that.
But so far, the actual safeguards provisions have not been completed
and we really think they should do that at a very early date.''
   Asked if there was some new reason for special concern, the U.S.
official replied he did not have any new information about the
program ``or something that would lead me to think that our concerns
are heightened. But we do have a longstanding concern.''
</TEXT>
