<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Spokesman     09-15 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Spokesman,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Journalist Named as Polish Government Spokesman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Solidarity journalist was named Friday as
spokesman for Poland's new government, which is the first to be led
by non-Communists in the East bloc.
   Malgorzata Niezabitowska writes for Tygodnik Solidarnosc, the
same weekly where Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki still holds the
post of editor in chief. He named her to her new post.
   The last permanent government spokesman was Jerzy Urban, who
conducted Western-style news conferences unique in the East bloc.
   His defense of the former Communist government's policies,
including efforts to suppress Solidarity, led to cold exchanges with
journalists and made him a well-known figure in Poland and abroad.
   Ms. Niezabitowska, who studied law and journalism at Warsaw
University, worked for the labor movement's weekly when Mazowiecki
founded it during the union's first legal phase in 1980-81. She
rejoined it after the movement was re-legalized this spring.
   During the 1980s, she also wrote for several Roman Catholic and
foreign publications.
   Her writing on Poland's once vibrant Jewish community has been
published in the United States, where she was a Neiman Fellow at
Harvard University in 1986-1987.
   There is only one woman in the prime minister's cabinet, Culture
Minister Izabela Cywinska.
   The 24-member body is controlled by Solidarity, which has 12
seats. The Communists hold four seats, and two smaller parties the
rest.
   It is the first East bloc government led by non-Communists since
the Communists consolidated control over Eastern Europe after World
War II.
</TEXT>
