<FIRST>r a AM-ToddlerFound     09-15 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toddler Found,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toddler Missing Overnight Found Clinging to Root in Creek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDER CITY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toddler missing from his home
overnight was found more than 17 hours later Friday clinging to a
root in a creek.
   Jesse Vitu, who will be 2 on Monday, doesn't know many words, but
when rescuer Jeff Jones found him, the boy reached out and said one
word: ``Home.''
   He was taken to a hospital where salve was put on scratches. He
was given liquids and sent home in good shape.
   Jesse wandered down a logging road behid his home about 4 p.m.
Thursday, and Jones spotted him about 9:30 a.m. Friday standing
knee-deep in Sugar Creek about a mile from home.
   Jones said that Jesse apparently had fallen into the creek, and
the current washed him downstream until he grabbed the root sticking
out from a bank.
   ``When I seen him I ran for him like I would my own,'' Jones
said. ``He was standing on the bottom. There was swift water around
him and all I could see was his head.
   ``The only time he started crying was when he got in the truck
coming back.''
   Bobby Brown, another rescue squad member in the truck, said that
when Jesse ``saw home he was a happy fellow.''
   Jesse's mother, Diane Vitu, said he ``disappeared in not even a
minute.''
   She said that when her other children arrived home from school
they went into the yard to play and that Jesse went along. She said
she followed within a minute and the toddler was gone.
   Sixty to 75 people, including members of law enforcement agencies
and two rescue squads, residents of the trailer park where the
family lives and employees of Russell Corp., where Jesse's parents
work, took part in the search.
   ``I couldn't believe all the people,'' said his father, John
Vitu. ``They just wouldn't quit.''
   When Jesse disappeared he was wearing a T-shirt, shorts, training
pants and a bib. When found, the training pants and shorts had been
pulled off him by the current.
</TEXT>
