<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan     09-15 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Lawmakers Debate into the Night in Special Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Azerbaijan's parliament met in emergency
session early Saturday to discuss the ethnic conflict engulfing the
Armenian enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh, official reports said.
   The Tass news agency said the southern republic's Supreme Soviet
would also examine a draft law proclaiming Azerbaijan's sovereignty
and citizenship and transition to the principles of economic
independence and self-management.
   The measures under study in the mostly Moslem republic are in
line with demands increasingly voiced by many Soviet ethnic groups
for greater control over their own affairs.
   The meeting convened Friday, but the lawmakers had debated for
more than 14 hours as the session extended into early Saturday.
   Communist Party officials will meet Tuesday in Moscow to consider
proposed changes in the country's nationalities policy and try to
find a way to calm ethnic quarrels that have often erupted in
violence.
   In another sign of the greater democratization under President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, it was the first time representatives of the
People's Front of Azerbaijan and other informal organizations were
allowed to attend the republic's parliament, Tass said.
   It was meeting in the Azerbaijani capital of Baku on the Caspian
Sea coast.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, a mountainous territory within Azerbaijan with
a predominantly Armenian population, is the center of a dispute
between Armenia and Azerbaijan. About 100 people have died in ethnic
strife the past 18 months, and hundreds of thousands have fled their
homes.
   The People's Front is demanding Azerbaijan's parliament reassert
control over Nagorno-Karabakh and that the direct rule over the
region by Moscow instituted in February be halted.
   ``The situation in and around Nagorno-Karabakh has never been so
tense and explosive as today,'' Arkady Volsky, head of the special
committee created by the Kremlin to administer the district, said in
televised remarks Thursday night.
   Volsky said Moscow was forced to assume control of the region
because of the bloodshed. ``The state cannot stand aside if blood is
spilled,'' he said.
   The duty editor who answered the telephone at Azerinform, the
republic's official news agency, said the session was continuing
early Saturday. ``They're still debating and haven't taken any
votes,'' said the editor, who declined to give his name.
   On Thursday, the newspaper Pravda reported that a strike by
Azerbaijani railroad workers to press demands for Azerbaijani
control of Nagorno-Karabakh has resulted in the cutting of fuel and
other supplies into neighboring Armenia.
   The strike was called off Monday, but it resulted in severe
shortages of fuel and other supplies. Armenia gets 87 percent of its
freight from Azerbaijan.
   The Communist Party newspaper said the situation was particularly
threatening in northern Armenia, where workers are trying to
reconstruct cities devastated by the earthquake Dec. 7 that killed
25,000 people.
</TEXT>
