<HEAD>Farm Bureau Chief Favors Capital Gains Tax Cut</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Capital Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee's vote to reinstate
preferential capital gains tax rates will help ``mom-and-pop type''
farmers, not just rich people, a national farm leader said Friday.
   Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm Bureau Federation,
said there are family farmers all over the country who have owned
land for many years and now want to sell out and retire.
   But because of inflation, land values have increased so much that
many cannot afford to retire after paying high capital gains taxes
on the sales.
   ``We're talking about mom-and-pop type of agriculture here,''
Kleckner said in a statement. ``We're not talking about wealthy
farmers.''
   Kleckner added that ``it's kind of a populist idea that capital
gains are only for wealthy people. It's going to be extremely
helpful for all of agriculture, and most of agriculture is not in
the extremely wealthy class.''
   The House Ways and Means Committee voted 19-17 on Thursday to cut
the tax.
