<FIRST>r w AM-SeminoleDispute     09-15 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seminole Dispute,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inouye Calls For Indians To Settle $50 Million Dispute Themselves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Select Committee on
Indian Affairs said Friday he wants the Seminole Indians of Oklahoma
and Florida to settle a $50 million dispute themselves instead of
asking Congress to handle it.
   ``In most cases, decisions made in Washington for Indians are the
worst solutions,'' said Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii. ``Decisions
should be made in Indian country.''
   His comments came during a hearing on legislation that would
divide money awarded the tribe in 1976 for Florida lands taken when
most of the tribe was relocated by the government to Oklahoma in the
1823 ``Trail of Tears.''
   The award _ $16 million _ has been held by the Treasury
Department for 23 years because the members of the tribe, many of
whom still live in Florida, have not agreed on how it should be
divided.
   It has accumulated substantial interest, and it is estimated to
reach $50 million by the end of this year.
   Legislation sponsored by Oklahoma Sens. David Boren, a Democrat,
and Don Nickles, Republican, would give 75 percent of the money to
the Oklahoma Seminoles and 25 percent to the Florida Seminoles, the
Miccosukee Tribe of Florida and the unaffiliated Seminole Indians of
Florida.
   Nickles said the split is fair because it's based on population
figures that counted 2,146 Seminoles in Oklahoma and 700 in Florida.
   He also said the Oklahoma tribe is poorer than the Florida one.
   ``Not only did hundreds of Seminoles die during the forced march
from Florida to Indian Territory, but lands initially given to the
tribe as a reservation were later taken from them as Oklahoma became
a state,'' said Nickles.
   ``Today the Seminole Nation (in Oklahoma) has a total of only 380
acres of tribally owned land,'' he said.
   On the other hand, he said, the Florida tribe ``is flourishing
economically with a reservation land base of approximately 80,000
acres.''
   James Billie, tribal council chairman for the Seminoles in
Florida who want a 50-50 split, told the committee he thought the
two sides could come to some agreement if they had 30 more days.
   ``While we in Florida have a sharp disagreement with our Oklahoma
brethren over the division of the claims commission's award, we have
not lost sight of the fact that we are all one people,'' Billie said.
   ``As a result of recent informal preliminary discussions we have
had with some of our Oklahoma brethren, we believe that it still may
be possible in a relatively short time ... to have agreement reached
by the two groups.''
   ``I would prefer negotiations,'' said Inouye. He said sovereign
nations, as Indian tribes are viewed, should be able to negotiate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
