<DOCNO> AP890915-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrunkenDrivers     09-15 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drunken Drivers,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Signs Bill Lowering Legal Drinking Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Deukmejian predicted lives
will be saved by legislation he signed Friday to lower California's
blood-alcohol standard for drunken drivers.
   ``We are seeing a reduction in the number of traffic fatalities
caused by drunken drivers,'' he told reporters and law enforcement
officers gathered in his office for the bill signing.
   ``On the other hand, we still have a far greater number of such
fatalities than we should have in California. This will make it
possible for law enforcement to obtain greater numbers of
convictions,'' the Republican governor said.
   Deukmejian said 2,239 people died last year as a result of
drunken drivers on California highways.
   The law, effective Jan. 1, lowers the blood-alcohol level at
which a person is presumed too drunk to drive from 0.10 percent to
0.08 percent. Current law allows for prosecution when a driver's
blood-alcohol level is below 0.10 percent if there is other evidence
the driver was too intoxicated to drive safely. Convictions are
rare, however.
   The new law still allows for prosecutions at levels below 0.08
percent if other evidence warrants it. The American Medical
Association supports a 0.05 percent level.
   A variety of factors, including weight, affect the amount of
alcohol a person can consume before getting drunk. The average
person can consume about three glasses of beer or comparable amounts
of other alcoholic beverages in an hour before reaching the 0.08
percent level.
   Drunken drivers should beware of the lowered standard, Deukmejian
said.
   ``This is a very strong signal and message to individuals who do
drink and do drive that it is more likely that they will wind up
being convicted of drunken driving ...,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
