<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast 300   09-15 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast, 300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kelly Urges Arabs To Drop Campaign Against Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Embargoed for 7 p.m. EDT. Time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official called on
the Arab governments Friday night to abandon their campaign of
trying to expel Israel from the United Nations.
   John H. Kelly, the assistant secretary of state for the Near
East, said that ``change in tactics'' could contribute to efforts to
arrange negotiations between the Arabs and Israel.
   ``Every year around this time the question comes up for a vote,''
Kelly said in a speech prepared for a conference on the Middle East
at the Wye Plantation in Maryland.
   ``It is time for the Arab nations to follow the example of the
PLO and acknowledge Israel's existence as a state. Israel is
entitled to membership in the United Nations under the principle of
universality,'' Kelly said.
   The U.S. official referred to the step taken last year by
Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat, who also
publicly renounced terrorism. That action met U.S. conditions for
the dialogue opened by the United States with the PLO last December.
   ``It is time for the Arab governments to stop the anachronistic
practice of voting against Israeli credentials,'' Kelly said.
   The Arabs have consistently failed to oust Israel from the United
Nations but the move provides an annual opportunity to condemn the
Jewish state before a large audience. Arab delegates also habitually
walk out when Israel's representative speaks to the U.N. General
Assembly.
   Kelly denied U.S. peace efforts were at a dead end.
   ``There is potential for movement,'' he said, adding that a
timetable for face-to-face negotiations should be set by
Palestinians and Israel _ not the Bush administration.
</TEXT>
