<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1746EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ControllerProbe     09-15 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Controller Probe,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Asks Justice Department to Probe FAA Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel charged Friday that FAA officials
lied under oath about payroll records prepared during the 1981
controllers' strike and in some instances doctored time sheets to
cheat the controllers.
   The committee asked the Justice Department to investigate.
   Faced with shoddy documents to justify the firings before the
Merit Systems Protection Board, Federal Aviation Administration
officials in Chicago for three months created attendance records to
bolster their cases, lawmakers concluded.
   The report by the Public Works and Transportation subcommittee on
investigations and oversight capped a three-year probe that included
private hearings and documents subpoenaed from the Chicago Air Route
Traffic Control Center at Aurora, Ill.
   The panel said it was willing to send its evidence to the Justice
Department and sent a letter to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
urging an investigation into possible criminal misconduct.
   John Leyden, a spokesman for the FAA in Washington, declined
comment except to say, ``The FAA has receieved the report and will
review it.''
   The subcommittee said it was not judging the merits of the 450
firings in Chicago, which were among 11,500 nationwide ordered Aug.
5, 1981, by then-President Reagan, two days after members of the
Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization struck.
   Rather, the subcommittee said it was concerned with the actions
of FAA officials while they were defending the firings in front of
the board that considers appeals from dismissed federal employees.
   For example, the FAA officials corrected some attendance records
to bring them up to date, but altered others, in some instances
recording a controller who was on leave at the time of the strike as
being absent without leave, to cheat the controllers, the
subcommittee said.
   The panel's report said the strike produced ``traumatic and
confusing times'' at the Chicago center. Supervisors had to handle
other jobs, ``and this situation severely affected the condition of
the center's attendance records,'' the report said.
   On Aug. 13, 1981, 10 days after the strike began and a month
before the controllers were told formally they had been fired,
Robert L. Miller, evaluations officer at the center, began to
process personnel files in anticipation that appeals would be filed
with the appeals board, the subcommittee said.
   To justify the firings, FAA officials decided to present
attendance records showing that the controllers had failed to report
to work during the strike.
   Between Sept. 14 and Oct. 1, these records were sent to the FAA's
Great Lakes regional office in Des Plaines, Ill., but officials
there found so many clerical errors that employees in Aurora had to
produce a second set of attendance records, the subcommittee said.
   FAA officials subsequently assured the merit board that the
records were the ones that had been used by George Gunter, the chief
of the Chicago center and the official who ordered the firings.
   The subcommittee concluded, however, that the assurance was ``a
certification that we now know to be false.''
   ``These documents, in many cases, either did not exist at the
time of the controller dismissals or were riddled with errors,'' the
subcommittee said. ``A plan was instituted whereby records were
created where none existed and amended where there were errors.''
   The subcommittee said it was not able to determine who had
ordered the second set of records.
   The subcommittee's report also concluded that Richard Shewfelt,
the FAA's regional manager for labor relations at the time, ``knew
of the problems of consistency and accuracy in the records that led
to the second shipment.''
   Shewfelt, who still works for the FAA's Chicago office, did not
return phone messages requesting comment. Miller is retired and
could not be found for comment.
   Gunter, now supervisor of training at the Air Route Traffic
Control Center in Fremont, Calif., said he had not seen the report
and declined to comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0169 </DOCNO>
