<FIRST>r w AM-FairchildSuit 190   09-15 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fairchild Suit, 190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Joins Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Friday that it had
joined a whistleblower's lawsuit charging that Fairchild Industries
Inc. defrauded the Pentagon by selling the Air Force faulty jet
fighter equipment.
   The department said it had taken over the lawsuit filed by Neil
Aliksanian, who was a program manager for Fairchild until leaving
the company in 1987.
   The government's complaint amending the original allegations made
by Aliksanian was unsealed Thursday by a federal judge in Los
Angeles.
   Stuart E. Schiffer, acting head of the Justice Department's civil
division, said in a statement that the government is claiming more
than $1 million in civil penalties for filing false claims.
   The government contends that Fairchild Control System Co., a
division of the Chantilly, Va.-based defense company, sold the Air
Force defective fuel-tank equipment for jet fighters.
   Aliksanian's original lawsuit was filed under the False Claims
Act, a Civil War-era law that allows private citizens to sue on
behalf of the government. His complaint was kept under court seal
until last month.
   The government's amended complaint was filed under seal in June.
