<HEAD>West German Police Arrive to Monitor Namibian Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty policemen from West Germany
arrived Friday to join the U.N. force monitoring the transition to
independence in this South African-ruled territory.
   The West Germans will be dispersed among the 1,000 U.N. police
monitors assigned to watch the territorial police during the period
before November elections, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
   South Africa has ruled the territory, also known as South-West
Africa, since it was captured from Germany after World War I. The
South Africans have agreed to grant Namibia independence under a
U.N. plan.
