<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-15 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Along West Coast; Thunderstorms in Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms reached across the Midwest and parts of
the South on Friday, and forecasters predicted the first rain in
months for Los Angeles on Saturday.
   Showers were reported in West Virginia, Kentucky, southern
Indiana and Illionois, eastern and southern Kentucky, western North
Carolina and from southeast Louisiana across the Florida panhandle.
   Nashville had .67 inches of rain during a six-hour period ending
at 2 p.m. EDT.
   A rain advisory was posted Saturday over the central San Joaquin
Valley in California. Forecasters said there was a good chance for
light rain Saturday over Los Angeles _ which would be its first rain
since May.
   Northern Nevada also had a good chance for rain during the
weekend, with snow possible in the eastern Sierra Nevada by Monday.
   The nation's low temperature Friday was 21 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 101 degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz.
   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern New England and much of New York state, across Georgia and
northern Florida, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys; scattered rain
from the lower two-thirds of the California coast into Nevada;
warmer weather over the mid-Mississippi Valley and central Plains
but cooler over much of the Pacific states.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s and 70s from New
England across Maryland, from the Great Lakes through the Tennessee
Valley over the middle Mississippi Valley, southern Rockies, Pacific
Northwest, along the California coast; near 90 degrees over the
Florida peninsula; in the 90s in the desert Southwest; and in the
80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
