<FIRST>u a AM-Ailing&amp;Unwanted     09-15 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ailing &amp; Unwanted,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Cuts Could Leave Some Severely Retarded Adults Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Helle in 5th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Brauer is severely retarded and a captive of
physical problems that require 24-hour attention. His parents can't
care for him and now the state says it has no money to look after
him once he turns 22 next month.
   So Larry Brauer was set to go to court on Monday in a bid to save
his life.
   ``His life is in jeopardy. There's no question about it because
(state officials) haven't fulfilled what they have committed
themselves to,'' Larry's father, Dr. Mark Brauer, said Friday.
   ``I don't know why this is happening to my son, who has done
nothing to anybody, whose life is hard to imagine,'' said Brauer, a
hematologist at Boston City Hospital. ``I'm not asking for charity.
... I'm a pretty resourceful guy. I'm usually able to solve my own
problems. But I've really hit the wall here.''
   Mark and Helle Brauer, a physical therapist, have joined nine
other couples in suing Gov. Michael Dukakis for impounding the money
that would continue care for their retarded and disabled sons and
daughters.
   The young people receive care at the private Crystal Springs
School in Assonet, at an annual cost of about $80,000 a person. But
funding for such care ends when they all turn 22 this year.
   The lawsuit contends that by impounding the money already
approved by legislators, Dukakis violated the constitutional
separation of powers, and that retarded citizens such as Larry
Brauer have a constitutional right to treatment and safety.
   Every year about 450 mentally retarded Massachusetts residents
turn 22, the age at which they leave the protection and training of
the state education system. The most severely retarded and disabled,
about 70 this year, usually get placed in a home in a residential
community with 24-hour supervision and medical care.
   But this year there is no money to pay for such care.
   The deep budget cuts Dukakis made in July eliminated $3.3 million
needed to give those 70 people the care they need to survive, said
Maureen Sullivan, spokeswoman for the state Department of Mental
Retardation.
   ``Going home to their families is going to be a real disaster,''
Ms. Sullivan said. ``It's a lousy situation.''
   The state is trying to help, Ms. Sullivan said. Parents are being
advised about support services. Some could go to state schools for
the retarded, reversing a move to empty institutions once decried as
warehouses. Pediatric nursing homes that might consider taking
adults are also being contacted, she said.
   ``The choice we have to make is (for) someone who is literally
homeless,'' she said.
   Larry Brauer has been at Crystal Springs since he was 11. He
functions at the level of a 16-month old, is paralyzed on the left
side and suffers from grand mal seizures so intense that they can
stop his breathing and require him to wear a helmet to avoid injury.
   He needs help going to the bathroom, dressing and eating. If his
parents took him home, one would have to quit work and they could
expect to spend some nights just listening to make sure he was still
breathing.
   ``Historically, even going back to the 19th century, this state
has always provided for these types of clients,'' said Roderick
MacLeish, the attorney for the Brauers and the other parents.
   ``The parents can't safely handle these kids. And the schools
can't continue to care for these kids free of charge. We face the
very real prospect of people who are seriously mentally retarded,
living in shelters for the homeless. The state has never abandoned
people like this,'' MacLeish said.
   The matter is far from over.
   Since the lawsuit was filed, some families have been told their
children could receive state benefits until new, federally funded
cottages are built to accommodate them at Crystal Springs, Mark
Brauer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
