<FIRST>u i AM-Ireland-Britain     09-15 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ireland-Britain,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>British, Irish Say Forces' Integrity `Critically Important'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish and British officials agreed at a
7{-hour meeting Friday that integrity was ``critically important''
among Northern Ireland security forces, tainted by charges of murder
and collusion with terrorists.
   Foreign Minister Gerry Collins, in his first meeting with
Britain's new Northern Ireland secretary, Peter Brooke, stressed
Ireland's unhappiness with reports that confidential police
documents fell into the hands of Protestant gunmen.
   The officials met specifically to discuss questions about the
reliability of the security forces., the first time since the
signing of the Anglo-Irish accord in 1985 that security was the only
topic on the agenda.
   The pact gave the Irish Republic a say in the affairs of the
Protestant-dominated British province and set up a structure for
such meetings as Friday's.
   Brooke said later, ``The Irish put to us their concerns and it
was decided all the points raised should be looked at again. In any
discussions there are bound to be differences, but ... I think we
made considerable progress.''
   Collins called it ``a serious meeting.''
   ``The important thing is to establish confidence in the security
forces as a whole among the nationalist community in Northern
Ireland,'' he said.
   The two sides agreed to meet again shortly, a joint statement
said.
   It said both sides ``emphasized their belief that confidence in
the evenhandedness and integrity of the security forces was
critically important.''
   Also on the agenda were the role of the British army's locally
recruited Ulster Defense Regiment and the use of plastic bullets.
   Irish authorities have said that intelligence developed by the
Garda Siochana, Ireland's police force, may not be safe in the hands
of the security forces in Northern Ireland.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the police force in Northern
Ireland, disclosed Thursday that a list and photographs of 12
suspected members of the Irish Republican Army were stolen from a
Belfast police station.
   Confidential information earlier disappeared from the Ballykinlar
army base in County Down.
   An English detective was assigned to investigate the two cases.
   On Monday, two members of the Ulster Defense Regiment were
charged with the murder of a Roman Catholic man.
   Men who had identified themselves as members of the outlawed
Ulster Freedom Fighters had shown a TV reporter documents,
apparently stolen or leaked from security forces, which identified
the murder victim as a suspected IRA member.
</TEXT>
