<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-15 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Troops Welcome Trucks with Garlands, Slaughtered Sheep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANDAHAR, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children clapped, the governor was
showered with cloth garlands and a sheep was slaughtered in the
middle of the road Friday as the military welcomed about 200
vehicles from a supply convoy that began rolling last month.
   The anti-Marxist rebels welcomed the convoy in their own way. Two
rockets slammed down about 250 feet from where the provincial
governor, Gen. Noor al-Haq Ulumi, was talking to reporters as trucks
and tanks rumbled past.
   No injuries were reported.
   Ulumi said almost 1,000 trucks had snaked their way across almost
780 miles of the barren south before arriving in this southeastern
provincial capital this week.
   In Pakistan, sources from the mujahedeen _ or Islamic holy
warriors, the Afghan rebels based in Pakistan _ and diplomatic
sources said the rebels knocked out 80 vehicles and slowed the
convoy's forward progress to a snail's pace. The sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Ulumi said the convoy lost three trucks in a collision and one
tank to a land mine. He said it had not suffered any mujahedeen
attacks after leaving Grishik, 60 miles west of Kandahar.
   Earlier, government officials said rebel forces attacked the
convoy at least three times and rebel rocket attacks forced it to
halt between Grishik and Kandahar.
   Initial government reports also said 1,300 vehicles were in the
convoy.
   The rockets Friday scattered the welcoming crowd that had been
throwing cloth flowers threaded onto metal rings.
   The throat of the lone sacrificial sheep was cut with a dull
knife in front of the lead vehicle, and tires left gory imprints on
the road.
   The trucks rumbling through the outskirts of Kandahar Friday were
the second batch to reach the city. Ulumi said with more expected
each day.
   He said the convoy was carrying ammunition and food and included
500 military trucks, 300 civilian trucks and a brigade of armored
vehicles. He would not say how many.
   There were no civilian trucks and no food in the carefully
orchestrated welcoming ceremony. The military trucks were flanked by
32 tanks.
   Most were stacked with ammunition boxes and caked with dirt. Some
were empty with spanking clean cabs. Ulumi said they were unloaded
earlier at a nearby garrison.
   Many trucks seemed new. Government officials have said the Soviet
Union recently delivered more than 1,000 trucks to Afghanistan.
   Ulumi said the ammunition should last troops in the area a year,
depending on the extent of fighting.
   ``If there is no war, the supplies will last 10 years, if there
is a war, one year,'' he said.
   It is the first such convoy since February, when Soviet troops
withdrew from Afghanistan nine years after intervening to prop up
the Marxist government. The U.S.-backed mujahedeen are still
fighting the Kabul government.
   The mujahedeen have not captured a major city despite repeated
attempts. The convoy was seen as a warning to the mujahedeen that
their acknowledged primacy in rural areas could be weakened.
   Officials in Kabul were always upbeat about the trucks' progress,
but repeated claims that the convoy was on the outskirts of Kandahar
were constantly revised.
   Ulumi would not say when the trucks had pulled out of Torghundi,
on the northern border with the Soviet Union. Government sources in
Kabul have said the departure date was Aug. 18. Kandahar lies 350
miles to the northwest of Torghundi.
   Ulumi claimed progress toward Kandahar was slow because the
trucks were used to supply a new set of border posts near Pakistan.
Speaking through an interpreter, he said the posts should make it
harder for the mujahedeen to use clansdestine routes through the
Registan Desert to get into Afghanistan.
   Supplies muust be brought into Afghanistan during the summer
because winter rain and snow make the roads impassable.
   Guerrillas have tried since October 1987 to capture Kandahar and
heavy fighting has left much of the city in ruins. Ulumi said two
weeks ago that 70 percent of the buildings in the city were
completely destroyed.
   Kandahar is 70 miles from Pakistan and about 270 miles south of
Kabul, the Afghan capital.
   It was Afghanistan's second largest city with about 300,000
people before the civil war began nearly 11 years ago. Govertment
officials said the population fell to about 25,000 when bombardment
was at its heaviest, but later talked of 200,000 now living in
Kandahar.
</TEXT>
