<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-Drugs     09-15 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Drugs,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Tells Aides He Will Never Be Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry insisted to his cabinet on
Friday that he will never be indicted in the federal investigation
of convicted drug dealer Charles Lewis, according three top District
of Columbia officials.
   Barry opened and closed the monthly cabinet session by telling
his aides that they should go ahead with the work of the city
without worrying about whether his legal difficulties will worsen,
the officials said.
   ``It was a call to arms,'' said one official. ``He lashed out at
the media, said the white power structure is out to get him, and he
vowed not to be beaten down by these forces.''
   Barry has said he will seek a fourth, four-year term next year.
   Another top city official who attended the hour-long session said
Barry stressed that he would not be indicted in a probe of his ties
to convicted drug dealer Charles Lewis.
   Barry ``assured us that he was in no legal trouble, that this
would all blow over,'' the second official said. ``He also mentioned
several biblical passages, and said he was counting on God to see
him through this.''
   Two officials said the meeting was dominated by Barry's comments
on his legal difficulties, despite the fact that other issues like
drugs, crime and public education were discussed.
   ``The mayor set the tone,'' a third official said. ``He
concentrated on this in his opening remarks, and then he closed by
trying to let us know that everything was alright and that we should
go ahead with our jobs.''
   All of the officials asked not to be identified.
   ``Cabinet meetings are for the benefit of the mayor and his
aides,'' said Maudine Cooper, Barry's chief of staff. ``They are not
for the public, and it is disloyal and inappropriate for anyone to
talk about those meetings.''
   She refused to comment on Barry's remarks.
   Barry spokeswoman Lurma Rackley said Friday the mayor ``wants to
go on record as saying he never said that. He never used the words
black and white in that context.'' Rackley said she was at the
meeting.
   Rackley said Barry had no comment on other events at the meeting.
   The cabinet meeting came just one day after a legal secretary
from the Virgin Islands, Dixie Lee Hedrington, testified before a
federal grand jury investigating Barry's ties to Lewis, a former
city employee who faces drug charges in the nation's capital and is
awaiting sentencing in the Virgin Islands.
   The Washington Post has reported Hedrington told authorities she
saw cocaine in Barry's Virgin Islands hotel room when the mayor
visited there in March 1988.
</TEXT>
