<FIRST>r w AM-Cheney-POW-MIA     09-15 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-POW-MIA,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Pledges Continuted Effort on Behalf of Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney pledged Friday
that the nation ``hasn't and won't forget'' those military still
listed as missing and unaccounted for.
   ``This government will continue its effort to ensure that we
achieve the fullest possible accounting,'' Cheney said at a Pentagon
ceremony marking National POW-MIA day.
   ``We're here today, because of families that have suffered, and
continue to suffer, not knowing the fate of their loved ones,''
Cheney said, adding, ``Your government hasn't and won't forget.''
   Cheney added, ``that also includes Col. Richard Higgins,'' the
Marine Corp officer who was kidnapped and apparently killed by his
Shiite Moslem captors in Lebanon.
   Higgins was serving as part of a United Nations peacekeeping
force, and U.N. efforts to recover his body have not met with
success.
   Cheney noted that from World War I through Vietnam, more than
92,000 Americans were lost in combat and their bodies were not
recovered.
