<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Arrests 1stLd-Writethru a0716 09-15 0871</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0899</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Canadian Suspects Linked to Colombian Drug-Trafficking Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with officials saying there's link
between two cases, U.S. officials comment, no Bush connection, details.
CORRECTS spelling of suspect Jaramillo's name. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMUNDSTON, New Brunswick (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men arrested with
Venezuelan papers and an arsenal of weapons have been linked to
Colombian suspects in a drug-trafficking case, authorities in this
Canadian province said Friday.
   A U.S. official said two of those arrested are known to be
Colombian.
   The arrests Wednesday launched a flurry of speculation that the
suspects came to this eastern province to interfere with a hearing
Thursday for two Colombians suspected of cocaine trafficking.
   Canadian Mounted police confirmed that connection Friday. Asked
if there was a link between the two cases, Inspector Al Hutchinson
of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Fredericton said, ``That's
correct.''
   ``We've re-evaluated the situation between the two groups,'' he
said without elaborating.
   However, Hutchinson said the connection between the cases has
prompted police to move the men facing drug charges from Fredericton
city jail to a more secure prison within the province. He would not
say which prison.
   Canadian police said they had ruled out suggestions that the
suspects are hitmen sent by drug traffickers in Colombia to kill
officials from Canada or the United States.
   ``There's no threat to any U.S. or Canadian government
official,'' Hutchinson said in a brief statement.
   Canadian authorities also rejected speculation that the suspects
had intended to cross the border to mount an attack at President
Bush's vacation home in Kennebunkport, Me.
   In Washington late Friday, Secret Service spokeswoman Jane
Vezeris said, ``We are monitoring the situation there, but we do not
beleive it has anything to do with threats to individuals in this
country. We believe it is a Canadian matter.''
   The United States and Colombia are in the midst of a crackdown on
Colombian drug traffickers, who provide most of the cocaine sold in
the States. Canadian and American officials say Colombian drug
cartels have been routing more drugs through the Maritime provinces
because the United States has tightened its borders.
   On Friday, police led four of the suspects arrested Wednesday
into a heavily guarded provincial court in Edmundston, where they
were charged with a variety of weapons offenses. The fifth man
linked to the case was charged in Saint John.
   Local police said they are also seeking up to three others as
suspects in the case.
   ``Innocent, innocent. Je suis innocent,'' one of the four
handcuffed suspects told reporters outside the Edmundston courthouse
Friday. ``No speak English,'' said another.
   Authorities have identified the four as Tito Sanchez, Euovio
Manzano, Osvaldo Gonzales and Wilmer Ramon Zanabria. Court documents
did not state their ages or hometowns.
   All four were being kept in custody for bail hearings set for
Tuesday.
   The hearing for the two Colombians accused of drug-trafficking
was held Thursday in the provincial capital of Fredericton, 125
miles southeast of Edmundston.
   When Mounted Police and Edmundston authorities arrested the four,
a search of their vehicles uncovered an Uzi submachine gun, Soviet
and Israeli assault rifles and 3,000 rounds of ammunition. Also
seized were six automatic pistols, a .22-caliber pistol, tear gas, a
deactivated Japanese grenade and an electric zap gun used to knock
people out.
   However, no drugs were found.
   Police said they also found five Venezuelan passports, and that a
fifth man was arrested in another provincial city Thursday.
   The man, identified as 33-year-old William Jose Rodriguez of
Caracas, was charged Friday in Saint John with possessing two
.22-caliber handguns. Authorities said he was expected to be charged
later with an immigration offense.
   Rodriguez was to remain in custody for a bail hearing Monday.
   Bill d'Amours of the Canandian Immigration Department said the
Venezuelan passports were sent to the Mounted Police forensic lab in
Ottawa to check their validity.
   In Washington, Frank Shults of the Drug Enforcement
Administration said Friday that two of the suspects are ``known to
be Colombians.''
   The agency sent several agents to Canada on Friday to discuss the
case with Canadian authorities, Shults said.
   Canadian authorities said it was not known how or when the
suspects entered Canada. However, Edmundston police said two of the
men arrested in their city had passports stamped in Montreal,
indicating they entered Canada there.
   Two of their vehicles had New York licenses, including one stolen
plate, police said. The vehicle carrying most of the weapons had
been rented in Fredericton, and police said Rodriguez was arrested
while trying to extend the rental agreement.
   The four men were also carrying maps of New Brunswick and
neighboring Maine. Police said several locations were highlighted on
the maps but refused to say what they were.
   The suspected cocaine traffickers, Jose Ali Galindo-Escobar and
Fernando Augusto Mendoza-Jaramillo, both 36, were arrested in April
after police made Canada's largest cocaine seizure.
   They found about 1,100 pounds of the drug inside the nose of an
airplane at a makeshift airstrip outside Fredericton.
   At Thursday's hearing, the two were ordered held for trial next
month on charges of importing cocaine. Authorities used dozens of
rifle-toting officers for heavy security at the hearing because of
worries prompted by the arrests.
</TEXT>
