<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Talks 1stLd-Writethru a0711 09-15 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Government, Rebels Agree To Talk Peace, Crowds Cheer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with added pact details, quotes.
CORRECTS church mediation and observers details to conform to final communique.
DELETES mediators' names, since none named in communique. REVISES and EXPANDS
Handal quote. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MO3, SAL4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvadoran government and leftist rebels
agreed Friday to meet monthly to try to negotiate an end to their
10-year-old civil war that has claimed 70,000 lives.
   Crowds marched through the streets of San Salvador cheering the
Mexico City agreements, and right-wing President Alfredo Cristiani
said he was encouraged.
   Leaders of the rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front
said their hope was for peace in 1990.
   The rebels and the government agreed to meet next in San Jose,
the Costa Rican capital, on Oct. 16-17 and at 30-day intervals
thereafter.
   They agreed that two representatives from the Roman Catholic
Church will mediate the talks and that they will also invite the
United Nations and the Organization of American States to send
observers.
   The Cristiani government initially opposed church mediation or
outside observers. It had also proposed meeting the Front _ known by
its Spanish initials FMLN _ every two months instead of at 30-day
intervals.
   The pact, reached after two days of intensive talks, also
stipulates that neither side can unilaterally withdraw from the
negotiations and that each delegation will have authority to reach
binding accords.
   ``The FMLN hopes there will be a Christmas and New Year in peace
in our country and that 1990 will be the year of the war's final
end,'' rebel leader Shafick Handal said at a joint news conference
after the accord was signed.
   ``The blood that has been spilled in the longest and most costly
conflict on the continent, all this blood that has been spilled,
deserves this.''
   Cristiani called the agreement ``important'' but cautioned,
``while welcoming the dialogue process, we don't want to create
false expectations.''
   ``We want to reiterate that our attitude is one of openness and
flexibility within our constitutional framework ... We know the road
ahead is difficult and complex,'' he told an Independence Day rally
in the Salvadoran capital.
   The Mexico City accord was announced on Central American
Independence Day _ the 168th anniversary of the independence of El
Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica and Guatemala from Spain
in 1821.
   ``We will possibly confront obstacles. But we trust in God and in
the good will of the two sides, and we will overcome the
difficulties,'' Cristiani said.
   Handal and fellow guerrilla commander Joaquin Villalobos said the
FMLN proposed the talks because of pressure inside and outside their
country for peace.
   They also said they feared the rightist government would become a
``facist dictatorship'' unless checked by the kind of democracy
peace could bring.
   Most of the war's victims have been civilians. Human rights
groups and international organizations say many were killed by
right-wing death squads linked to the military and Cristiani's party
_ links the party denies.
   The Mexico City talks were the first in two years between
government and rebels; they were also the first meeting between the
rebels and Cristiani's administration.
   The rebels have already laid out their peace proposal. The
government is to present its proposal in October.
   The FMLN offered to transform itself from a rebel army into a
legal political party in exchange for sweeping social and political
reforms.
   The reforms would erode the power of the military and of
Cristiani's party, which now holds controls the National Assembly
and the Supreme Court.
   The rebels demand that the military be purged of human rights
violators and reduced in size; that the date of the 1991 legislative
and municipal elections be advanced; and that a new high court be
appointed.
   In return, the rebels say they will become a legitimate political
party and run candidates in elections _ something they have refused
to do.
   They dropped demands for power-sharing and for merging the rebel
and government armies and couched their plan in language far milder
than any previous proposal.
   The proposal asks the United States to end military aid to El
Salvador and channel the money instead into El Salvador's economic
development.
   To prevent a rebel victory, the United States has given about
$3.5 billion in military and economic aid to El Salvador this decade
_ making it Latin America's biggest single recipient of American
assistance.
</TEXT>
