<HEAD>Former Argentine President to Help Supervise Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Raul Alfonsin of
Argentina arrived Friday at the invitation of the leftist Sandinista
government to help supervise general elections set for February.
   Alfonsin will head an observers' commission along with former
U.S. President Carter, who is expected to arrive Saturday.
   ``I have come to defend democracy,'' Alfonsin told reporters when
asked about his mission.
   Nicaraguan general elections set for Feb. 25 promise to be
closely watched.
   The United Nations and the Organization of American States have
set up observer commissions to watch the elections under regional
accords to bring peace to Central America.
   Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, publisher of the opposition
newspaper La Prensa, is the presidential candidate for the National
Opposition Union, a 14-party coalition.
   President Daniel Ortega most likely will seek re-election, but
the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front has said it won't
announce its official ticket until Sept. 25.
   U.S. Secret Service agents assigned to Carter arrived in Managua
this week and ``have been scouting the security situation,'' said a
high-level diplomatic source at the U.S. Embassy.
