<FIRST>u a AM-Children-Accident 1stLd-Writethru a0677 09-15 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children-Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Children Injured on Way Home from School</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with two more children critically injured;
that one child is reported comatose; two injured adults in stable condition;
details of charges against driver; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car struck a group of children on their way home
from school Friday, injuring nine people, five of them critically,
and leaving schoolbooks and notebook papers scattered in the street,
police said.
   Witnesses said the children were struck as they stood on the
median of a road. They said a car ran a stop sign, striking a
station wagon that slammed into the children.
   Five children were taken to Children's Hospital, where three were
listed in critical condition, including one who was reportedly
comatose. One child was listed in serious condition and one in fair
condition.
   ``I'm hoping I can get to sleep tonight. I've never seen anything
this bad,'' said Adell Jackson, 30, who was on her way to pick up
her son from a nearby school when she witnessed the accident in the
Dorchester section.
   The children were on a median strip when the car struck them, she
said.
   ``That's when the kids went up in the air,'' Ms. Jackson said.
   Two other children were taken to Boston City Hospital, where both
were listed in critical condition, hospital spokesman Louis Daddario
said.
   Officials said two adults, one bystander and one riding in a
vehicle, were also injured and taken to Brigham and Women's
Hospital. Hospital officials refused to release their condition.
Richard Serino, an emergency medical services deputy, said both were
in stable condition when they were taken to the hospital.
   The driver of the car that went through the stop sign was cited
for driving to endanger, driving without registration and failing to
stop, police spokesman Scott Gillis said.
   The children ranged in age from 7 to 11, said Kristi Kienholz, a
spokeswoman at Children's Hospital.
   Books notebook papers were scattered in the median strip shortly
after the accident. Police blocked off the area as neighbors
gathered. They said they have long believed the crossing is
dangerous.
   ``This is a bad intersection,'' Ms. Jackson said.
</TEXT>
