<FIRST>r w AM-HUDName     09-15 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Name,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-HUD-Pierce</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kemp Receiving Improvement Suggestions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack
Kemp some time ago asked top agency officials for suggestions for
improvements, and two he got back called for the department to
change its name and stage a fire sale of foreclosed properties.
   The proposed new name: The Home Department.
   Several other officials in recent days have objected to selling
off homes at distress prices because of its possible depression of
local real estate markets. Others have indicated a name change is
improbable.
   The two suggestions came from C. Austin Fitts, assistant
secretary for housing, in response to Kemp's request `just about
anything that came to mind,'' in the words of one official.
   Ms. Fitts' suggestion called for HUD to reduce the price of its
houses 1 percent per day until they were sold. For example, a
$50,000 house would cost $49,500 the second day, $49,000 the third
day and so on.
   Kemp is expected to make decisions around the end of the month.
</TEXT>
