<FIRST>r w AM-CinemaRacism     09-15 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cinema Racism,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racism in Film Detrimental to Whites and Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From Tarzan to Indiana Jones, racism in the
movies has created false notions and negative images of
African-Americans held by both white and black people, two veteran
black actors said Friday.
   ``The dominant culture puts out so much misinformation in a
relentless fashion that you are programmed against yourself,'' said
Bernie Casey, recalling that as a child he rooted for Tarzan to win
against the Africans.
   ``I did not want to be one of the Africans yet I am an African. I
would reject myself ... In the land of ooga-booga, I wanted no part
of it,'' Casey said.
   Casey, who has appeared in 25 movies and on television, took part
in a seminar with Madge Sinclair Madge Sinclair, late of
television's ``Trapper John.''
   In making their remarks during a seminar at the Congressional
Black Caucus weekend, the two also urged listeners to write in to
producers when they are pleased or displeased; refuse to see films
or rent videos that do not have black people in significant roles;
and form collectives to act on both ideas.
   ``I never see a Woody Allen film,'' Sinclair said about the
filmmaker who is acclaimed for filming slices of New York life yet
whose few black characters frequently are butlers and maids.
   ``I feel better when I don't subscribe to the images that deny my
very existence.''
   The two agreed that: loving black couples are rarely shown;
dashing black men are never the heros; black people are thought to
have lips that are too large thus few if any kissing scenes are ever
filmed.
   Also, Tarzan's successor, Indiana Jones, also was in films that
``speak to the evilness'' of the cultures of people of color and
those dark people's ``lack of ableness,'' Casey said.
   He added that ``what is born out of misinformation is
misperception and what is born of misperception is
misunderstanding.''
   That has lead to, among other things, black people rejecting
their culture by straigtening their hair to be more like white
people, Casey said.
   ``As long as you reject yourself, you will never feel of any
consequence,'' Casey said.
   And added Sinclair, the world only knows about black people what
is exported on film, leading to Japanese prime ministers being able
to make disparaging remarks about the intelligence of blacks and
Latinos.
   When she was growing up in Jamaica, Sinclair said, black people
in films were always worthless, shiftless bums or gangsters.
   Fortunately, she said, she and members of her family traveled to
the United States ``and so we knew better.''
   Recently Sinclair said she was insulted by some black producers
who were thinking of casting her.
   But one of them told her ``he thought I was too polished, too
cultured, could I `get down''' or act in a more stereotypical black
manner, Sinclair said.
   ``That floored me and made me want to leave the business,'' she
said to the overflow crowd in a Congressional hearing room on
Capitol Hill. ``That's what I expected from the other side.''
   But one of the worst incidents occurred when she went to a
producer with a project by and about black people.
   After presenting all of her arguments for something she thought
black people would flock to see, Sinclair said the producer told
her: ``It doesn't matter what we put out there. Anything we put out
there they'll go see.''
   Too true, the two actors said. Casey, using conservative figures,
said that if 20 million blacks saw two movies a month at $3 a
ticket, that would equal $120 million a month and more than $ 1
billion a year.
   ``So if you think you are inconsequential, stop it,'' Casey said.
   A visiting black actor from Great Britain was taken aback by the
discussion.
   ``You've kind of blown me away. We guys thought you were doing so
well,'' Brian Bovell said to much laughter during the question and
answer portion of the program.
   Afterward, he said black Britons were aware of Malcolm X, Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. and also, as seen through the movies, that
life in America was good.
   ``It was presumed to be the same for blacks,'' Bovell said.
``This has been brilliant for me.''
</TEXT>
