<FIRST>u a AM-ExxonValdez 2ndLd-Writethru a0654 09-15 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0654,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleanup Operation Ends _ Officials Disagree Over Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with announcement of state winter
cleanup program; picks up 7th graf, `State officials ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As workers who labored to remove the scars
of the Exxon Valdez disaster left this port town on Friday, the
state announced its own $21 million cleanup plan for the winter.
   Gov. Steve Cowper said the winter program will include cleaning
shorelines, researching and developing cleanup technology that can
be used next spring, and protecting fish hatcheries and untainted,
environmentally sensitive areas.
   Exxon officials have pronounced 1,100 miles of oil-smeared
shoreline ``environmentally stable,'' saying their 25-week effort to
remove gross contamination from shorelines in Prince William Sound
was a job well done.
   Otto Harrison, general manager of Exxon's Valdez operations, said
that while oil remained in some areas, it was not enough to harm
wildlife.
   ``What you've seen is a coastline almost free of oil,'' Harrison
said at a Valdez news conference. ``You're seeing the steady
recovery of Prince William Sound.''
   Officials at VECO Inc., the primary contractor for Exxon in the
cleanup, defended their work at a news conference on Friday. Bert
Hartley, VECO's general manager, said the removal of oil from
beaches was ``Herculean accomplishment.''
   ``That does not mean you cannot find oil on the beaches. You can
find oil if you look for it,'' Hartley said.
   Cowper was conciliatory toward Exxon as he announced the state
cleanup.
   ``I think Exxon has made a good-faith efort to clean up the
beaches,'' the governor said. ``I'm not going to fault Exxon because
they made some mistakes. Frankly, some of the things the state has
done were mistakes.''
   The state should have known more about dealing with a spill, he
said. ``At least we should have known no one else knew how to do
it,'' Cowper said.
   The state work will be funded with an oil tax the Alaska
Legislature passed this year, and reimbursment will be sought from
Exxon, the governor said.
   State officials agreed some shorelines were cleaner because of
Exxon's efforts. But they disputed the company's rosey portrayal of
an environmental rebound from nearly 11 million gallons of spilled
crude.
   Dennis Kelso, the state's environmental commissioner, toured
shorelines on two islands south of Valdez on Thursday and said he
was not pleased with what he saw.
   ``This beach is not environmentally stable,'' he said as he poked
a stick into thickly oiled rocks on Knight Island.
   The Knight Island shoreline was one of the last treated by
cleanup crews. The air still was thick with the pungent smell of a
chemical fertilizer recently sprayed on the rocks.
   The fertilizer is supposed to stimulate microorganisms to break
down the oil faster than they would normally. Kelso, who had visited
the same beach two weeks ago, said the process has shown signs of
success.
   In other spots, however, it appeared the cleanup was rushed to
meet Exxon's self-imposed cleanup deadline, Kelso said.
   The commissioner said the state is asking Exxon to do more
research in the coming months to determine the chemicals' possible
side effects and whether the process does much more than remove
surface oil.
   Exxon officials said that while the summer cleanup is over, the
company will continue to monitor the spill and respond to major
problems. About 300 cleanup workers will remain in Alaska, down from
about 10,000 at the height of the effort.
   The spill on March 24th was the nation's worst _ 10.92 million
gallons of crude gushed out when the ship ran aground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
