<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Baltics     09-15 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Urges Compromise at Meeting with Baltic Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail Gorbachev urged compromise upon
the leaders of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia at a Moscow meeting on
economic reform plans and ethnic tensions in the Baltics, Tass said
Friday.
   Nationalist movements have sprung up in those three Baltic
republics and other regions.
   The official news agency said Gorbachev told Communist leaders of
the three republics on Wednesday that ``what is needed is
consolidation, reciprocity, a search for sensible compromises.''
   The Baltics have been pushing Gorbachev's economic reforms and
won approval from the national Parliament to carry out plans for
economic autonomy beginning Jan. 1.
   Gorbachev wants economic restructuring, but maintains the
Communist Party should play the leading role in those reforms.
   Tass said Gorbachev told the Baltic leaders that the ``main
current difficulty is that the long-term goals ... come against
striking problems, which reflect the current needs of people.''
   It said he told them they had to ``move actively,'' but not
forget the three fundamentals ``from which we have no right to
deviate.''
   He listed these as: solving all problems ``only in the framework
of the federation;'' unity of the party _ ``the main guarantor of
perestroika and the process of national revival,'' and ``equality of
the citizens of all nationalities.''
   Soviet officials say Gorbachev took part in writing a statement
from the Communist Party Central Committee in late August warning
Baltic residents that separatism would not be in their interests.
   On Aug. 23, more than 1 million Baltic residents joined hands to
protest the 50th anniversary of a Nazi-Soviet agreement in which
Josef Stalin incorporated the previously independent Baltic states
into the Soviet Union.
   Harry Tiido, an editor of the official Estonian radio, said in a
telephone interview from Tallinn that the republic's Communist Party
chief, Vaino Vyalyas, President Arnold Ruutel and Premier Indrek
Toome attended the meeting.
   Tiido quoted Estonian leaders as saying Gorbachev expressed a
willingness to ``put pressure through the Politburo on ministries in
Moscow'' that might try to slow down economic reform.
   He said that Vyalyas dodged questions on ethnic tensions in
interviews after the meeting.
   Last month, non-Estonians went on strike to protest a law
imposing residency requirements for voting and running for local
office in the republic.
   Tass said in its account that Gorbachev told the leaders on
Wednesday that perestroika _ his term for economic and social
restructuring _ ``can succeed only if the party ranks are united.''
   ``It would be a grave historic mistake to weaken such a powerful
political organism, as the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.''
   Also on Friday, the Communist Party daily Pravda accused members
of the Ukraine's new Narodni Rukh political movement of seeking to
undermine Kremlin authority and take power itself in the republic.
   The Narodni Rukh ended a three-day founding congress last Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
