<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 5thLd-Writethru a0763 09-15 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0763,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Injure 7 in Colombia, Army Arrests 28 Suspected Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with seven injured in bomb attacks;
pickup graf 5 pvs `In Eastern...' DELETES grafs 20 pvs `The bombings...';
pickup graf 21 pvs `The current...' DELETES final three grafs to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of bombings in three of
Colombia's major drug-trafficking centers Friday damaged banks and
injured seven people, including two policemen, authorities said.
   The army meanwhile said it arrested 28 suspected leftist
guerrillas and accused them of carrying out terrorist acts with drug
traffickers around the cocaine hub of Medellin.
   In the southwestern city of Cali, a bomb blew out windows and
caused extensive damage Friday night to an insurance building, which
also housed a savings and loan bank. Two other blasts damaged a
state bank and another bank.
   Cali Police Col. Roso Julio Franco, in an interview with national
Radio Caracol, said the three bombs went off within a few minutes of
each other in the city of 1 million people. He said five people were
seriously injured.
   ``The wave of terrorism has escalated, but we now have things
under control,'' he said.
   The region is home to one of four Colombia's major drug cartels,
which have been blamed for a series of nationwide bombing attacks in
recent weeks.
   In Medellin, 150 miles northwest of Bogota, police said a bomb
went off Friday night at a highway to the capital as a police car
drove by. Two policemen were injured, they said.
   A two-week curfew was suspended Thursday in Medellin. Mayor Juan
Gomez said the curfew was lifted because the city of 2 million had
returned to ``absolute normalcy.''
   Earlier Friday, four bombs exploded at banks in Bogota.
   Banks have been major targets of bombings since the government
launched a crackdown on the drug trade a month ago.
   No one claimed responsibility for any of Friday's attacks.
   Also Friday, the Defense Ministry ordered the country's
200,000-member army and the national police on alert and reinforced
security at many buildings in anticipation of violence on the eve of
the ``Day of Love and Friendship.'' Colombians exchange gifts on
Saturday's holiday.
   In eastern Canada, Colombians Jose Ali Galindo-Escobar and
Fernando Augusto Mendoza-Jaramillo were ordered held for trial next
month on charges of importing 1,100 pounds of cocaine. They were
arrested and the drugs seized in April.
   Their hearing in the New Brunswick town of Fredericton was held
Thursday under tight security following the arrests Wednesday in
Canada of five armed men.
   Inspector Al Hutchinson of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police in
Fredericton said Friday the two Canadian cases are linked, but he
gave no details.
   U.S. officials said two of arrested men are Colombian, although
all held Venezuelan passports.
   The arrests in Colombia were announced in a communique from the
4th Army Brigade in Medellin, the site of almost daily bombings,
shootings and arson attacks since the government and its cocaine
cartels declared war on each other last month.
   The United States has been helping Colombia in the crackdown, and
Gen. Oscar Botero Restrepo, Colombia's defense minister, said Friday
that Argentina would be sending ``various airplanes.''
   However, he gave no details, and there was no immediate
confirmation from Argentine officials.
   The army said the 28 arrested belonged to the National Liberation
Army, which is one of six leftist guerrilla groups operating in this
South American country.
   The communique did not say when the 28 were arrested or what
specific ``terrorist acts'' they were accused of committing.
   ``We have succeeded in capturing an entire gang of bandits from
the so-called National Liberation Army that together with
narco-traffickers have been carrying out terrorist acts (around
Medellin),'' it said.
   It would be unusual for leftist guerrillas to work with drug
cartels.
   Drug organizations here traditionally have considered guerrillas
their enemies and have funded hit squads aimed at killing leftist
sympathizers.
   Drug traffickers also view the army-guerrilla confrontations in
remote regions as getting in the way of their cocaine processing and
shipping operations.
   Since President Virgilio Barco decreed special emergency powers
Aug. 18 to aid in the anti-narcotics fight, authorities have been
rounding up drug suspects and seizing bank accounts and property
presumed linked to the traffickers.
   The emergency measures temporarily suspend some constitutional
guarantees and allow suspects to be held for eight days without
being formally charged.
   The current crackdown started after drug gangs Aug. 18
assassinated the leading presidential candidate, Sen. Luis Carlos
Galan, a foe of the traffickers.
   Also Friday, a U.S. official in Bogota backed up a declaration
made the day before by Botero Restrepo, who said there were no
American military advisers in the country.
   ``The problem is the word `advisers.' They aren't advisers. We
have trainers and technicians,'' said the U.S. official, who spoke
to foreign reporters on the condition of anonymity.
   Consternation arose in Colombia following reports from Washington
that President Bush had deployed troops to help fight narcotics in
Colombia, Bolivia and Peru.
  
</TEXT>
