<HEAD>Top China Official Says Deng to Appear Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Chinese official in Beijing has said Deng
Xiaoping is in good health and will make an appearance during
celebrations of the Oct. 1 National Day, newspapers reported Friday.
   Deng, 84, has not been seen publicly since June 9, when he
praised martial law troops for suppressing the pro-democracy
movement. His long absence from the public spotlight has added fuel
to widespread rumors that the Chinese leader is in poor health.
   But Yao Yilin, a member of the Chinese Communist Party Politburo
Standing Committee, told a Hong Kong delegation that Deng will
appear in celebrations marking the 40th anniversary of the founding
of the People's Republic, several local newspapers reported.
   Yao's message was relayed by members of the Heung Yee Kuk, a
powerful organization in rural Hong Kong, who returned to this
British colony Thursday from Beijing, where they met several Chinese
leaders.
   The group quoted Yao as saying that Deng, who is chairman of
China's Central Military Commission, continues to swim for a
half-hour daily. He also was quoted as saying he had visited Deng
three days earlier and that he was in good health.
   The delegation also said it was told that martial law in Beijing,
which was imposed May 20, will not be lifted before National Day.
