<FIRST>r a AM-HighRise-Razing     09-15 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High Rise-Razing,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Approves Newark High-Rise Demolition Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Thursday approved the
demolition of eight buildings in two housing projects in a
compromise that was struck after a proposal to knock down nearly
five times as many high-rises drew fire.
   In addition to demolishing buildings containing about 1,900
apartments, the agreement between the Newark Housing Authority and
tenants groups calls for the renovation or construction of more than
3,000 apartments for poor people.
   Nearly $3 million in federal Housing and Urban Development funds
are committed to the renovations and construction.
   The city originally had planned to tear down 3,900 buildings
containing about 5,700 units. Tenants and advocates for the homeless
said the plan would swell the number of homeless people in Newark.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise tentatively approved
the plan on Aug. 17, but delayed final approval until Thursday to
give officials time to distribute copies of the pact to tenants and
federal housing officials.
   ``There was some disagreement, but none of the parties involved
wanted to jeapordize the HUD funding in the agreement,'' said the
judge, whose courtroom was packed with tenants and many on the
authority's long waiting lists.
   Under the agreement, buildings containing 1,506 apartments in the
Columbus Homes project and about 400 at the Kretchmer Homes will be
demolished. Most of the units in those two projects are already
vacant.
   The pact requires the city to break ground for the 1,776 new
units it has promised to build before beginning demolition at
Columbus Homes and to repair and fill 1,632 vacant apartments before
demolition at the other project.
   Many of those attending Thursday's hearing took the opportunity
to complain about the housing authority's efforts to provide
low-income housing.
   About one-third of Newark's 316,000 residents receive public
assistance. The housing authority is the eighth largest in the
nation with 13,000 apartments.
   The original plan to destroy most of the city's high-rise
projects reflected a trend toward low-rise public housing, which is
considered more manageable by many officials.
</TEXT>
