<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:MissSaigon Adv19   09-15 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Miss Saigon, Adv 19,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, Sept 19 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>And Now, Vietnam _ the Musical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People expect great things from Cameron Mackintosh,
the producer of ``Cats,'' ``Les Miserables'' and ``The Phantom of
the Opera.''
   But a musical set in Vietnam? That's something else.
   ``It's another emotional roller coaster,'' the Tony-winning
millionaire said of ``Miss Saigon,'' his most-anticipated
blockbuster to date.
   The $4.65 million-show, opening Sin Vietnam prior
to the 1975 fall of Saigon and then picks up in 1978.
   The musical at the Theater Royal, Dept. 20, is set rury Lane, reworks
the
``Madama Butterfly'' story about the doomed liaison between an
American naval officer and his Japanese bride.
   It stars Welsh actor Jonathan Pryce as a Vietnamese pimp; Simon
Bowman and Claire Moore as the lovesick American GI and his wife;
and 18-year-old Filipino actress Lea Salonga in her Western stage
debut, as Kim, the musical's tragic heroine.
   ``Miss Saigon'' reteams Mackintosh with Alain Boublil and
Claude-Michel Schonberg, the award-winning French authors of ``Les
Miserables,'' which is well on its way to being the most
internationally successful musical ever.
   Richard Maltby Jr., the Tony-winning Broadway director of ``Ain't
Misbehavin''' and ``Song and Dance,'' co-wrote ther over three years and
its
pre-opening ticket sale of $7.75 million is believed to be a London
record.
   Mackintosh said its appeal differs from that of ``Les
Miserables,'' which was based on Victor Hugo's epic 1862 novel and
has been running in London almost four years.
   ```Miss Saigon' doesn't have the revivalist emotion of the end of
`Les Mis,''' he said, referring to the earlier musical's final
number. ``They all start singing `When Tomorrow Comes'... and
there's a terrific surge of powerful emotion about survival.''
   Mackintosh said the new musical, by contrast, presents ``an
intimate tragedy about a girl who gives up her life,'' and that he
and his collaborators did not intend ``Miss Saigon'' as an overt
political broadside.
   ``It's set against the Vietnam War, but you could equally, though
not necessarily as effectively, set the story in Argentina, South
Africa or wherever colonialism rears its head,'' he said.
   ``We all militantly eschewed a political statement,'' said
Maltby. ``We believe any political statement will emerge from the
events on-stage.
   ``It's hard to miss a parallel between the war itself and what
happens to this Vietnamese girl.''
   ``Miss Saigon'' is expected to arrive on Broadway late next year,
but Mackintosh said this may well be his last mega-musical for a
while.
   ``I've had more than my share of luck; I really can't cope with
looking after any more shows,'' said the 43-year-old producer, who
will spend 1991 producing the movie of ``Les Miserables,'' to be
directed by Alan Parker (``Mississippi Burning'').
   His hit musicals have generated a truly international theater
stretching across America, Europe and Asia, but he said in an
interview: ``I'm beginning to lose my enthusiasm for it.
   ``People say, `What's your next biggie going to be?' and I think,
`Who cares?' All that matters is that what we do, we do well.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Sewpt. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
