<DOCNO> AP890915-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv17   09-15 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 17,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>The South Dissected, Hangups and All</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for the regular column by Walter R. Mears, who is
vacationing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It says something about the book put out by
William Ferris and Charles Wilson that the major complaint from
readers is that it is too heavy to read in bed. Most people don't
take an encylcopedia to bed.
   It says something, too, about the eight-pound, three-ounce
Encyclopedia of Southern Culture that not many people except for the
citizens of Fort Worth, Texas, have found much that was left out.
   Fort Worth complains because it didn't get an entry of its own,
making it appear, perhaps, less Southern than Dallas or New Orleans.
   This massive and ambitious $50, 1,600-page compendium of ``the
cultural landscape of the South'' _ exploring everything from Johnny
Cash to Moon Pies _ was published this summer.
   Even before it came out, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram carried a
piece offering a carload of mint juleps if the book would just
include Fort Worth.
   ``It was a very attractive offer,'' says Ferris, son of a soybean
farmer, now director of the Center for the Study of Southern Culture
at the University of Mississippi, but in defining what constitutes
Dixie ``we had to draw the line somewhere and we basically drew it
between Fort Worth and Dallas.''
   As for the rest of the South and its institutions, folkways,
foods, burdens, icons, topics, attitudes, crops and hangups, ``to my
knowledge, there have been no real omissions,'' says Ferris.
   Which says a lot.
   Edited jointly by Ferris, a folklorist, and Charles Wilson, a
historian, and 10 years in the works (it was supposed to have taken
four), the encyclopedia has 800 contributors, including novelists,
theologians, lawyers, psychologists, historians, sociologists.
   They're specialists on everything from the role violence, race
and religion have played on the psyche of the South to the history
of the Goo Goo Cluster (``the South's favorite candy,'' it got its
name, legend says, from the first utterance of the infant son of its
creator, William H. Campbell, in 1912).
   The encyclopedia offers Billy Carter's distinction between a good
old boy and a redneck. The former rides around in a pickup drinking
beer and puts his empties in a sack; the latter rides around in a
pickup drinking beer and tossing his empties out the window.
   Ferris says the criticism he's heard most often from readers
concerned the book's size, but some critics have complained about
imbalance. Reviewer Jonathan Yardley felt there was too much Henry
Aaron, too little Willie Mays, too much Vivian Leigh, not enough
Clark Gable.
   John Egerton, author of ``Southern Food: At Home, On the Road, In
History,'' complained he couldn't find entries on Andrew Johnson,
Earl Long, Happy Chandler, Larry McMurtry or Minnie Pearl and not
enough on Southern politics and rivers.
   Never mind. The book still swarms with the stuff that makes the
South distinctive.
   The flavor is conveyed by just a smattering from the A, B and C
entries in the index:
   _A:
   Air conditioning (``Ask any southerner over 30 years of age to
explain why the South has changed in recent decades, and he may
begin with the civil rights movement or industrialization. But
sooner or later he will come around to the subject of air
conditioning.''). The Andy Griffith Show. Armadillos (come out at
night, live on insects and worms, voted in 1971 by the University of
Texas student senate to replace the longhorn as the school symbol,
but never acted upon).
   _B:
   Barbecue (``three topics upon which Southerners never agree are
religion, politics and barbecue''). The Beverly Hillbillies. The
Bible Belt. The Blues. The Boll Weevil (``During the initial
infestation many communities exclusively dependent on cotton
underwent boll weevil panics or depressions similar to other
economic depressions.'').
   Paul ``Bear'' Bryant. Burma Shave signs (``Missin' _ Kissin'? _
Perhaps Your Thrush _ Can't Get Thru _ The Underbrush _ Try _ Burma
Shave'').
   _C:
   Catfish (``Southerners have never aligned themselves as closely
with any cold-blooded creature as they have with the feline-looking
catfish.''). Chitterlings. Coca-Cola (once called ``the holy water
of the American South'').
   Company towns (``The right to occupancy was dependent upon
employment. If out on strike, or ill, or injured, a worker and his
family could be evicted on short notice.''). Confederate Memorial
Day. Congress of Racial Equality. Country Music Hall of Fame. Davy
Crockett.
   Co-editor Ferris is astonished at the encyclopedia's instant
popularity. A first printing of 15,000 sold out quickly; a second
printing is in the works.
   He thinks it says something about the country that, despite the
homogenizing effects of television, mobility, urbanity and the
Interstate highway system, interest in regionalism is taking on new
strength.
   ``A sense of being a Southerner, a New Yorker or Midwesterner
persists,'' says Ferris. ``I think Americans are realizing that
their regions are at the heart of their own identities as
Americans.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Feinsilber has been a fan of Southerners
since marrying one 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 17</NOTE>
