<FIRST>r f AM-GMLakewood 1stLd-Writethru f0295 09-15 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM Lakewood, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0295,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM to Shut Georgia Plant in March; 2,200 Workers Affected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The plant ...,' to ADD that 1,000 workers already
laid off.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s Lakewood, Ga., assembly
plant will close in mid-March and production of the cars made there
will shift to other plants, the company said Thursday.
   The United Auto Workers union swiftly criticized the decision,
saying it ``sends a message of defeat and a message of failure'' in
GM-UAW relations.
   The plant employs about 2,200 people, 250 of whom are salaried.
About 1,000 of the employees are on indefinite layoff, a GM
statement said. Provisions are being made to ensure they get all the
benefits to which they are entitled, GM said.
   ``We want to give our employees as much time as possible to
prepare for this,'' said A.M. Beirne, head of manufacturing for GM's
Chevrolet-Pontiac-Canada Group.
   The Lakewood plant makes the Chevrolet Caprice and the Buick
Estate Wagon. The Caprice also is made at GM's Arlington, Texas,
plant. Buick spokesman Larry Gustin said the station wagon will be
built beyond mid-March, but he couldn't say where.
   ``General Motors management is not trying nearly hard enough to
fulfill its obligations under the national agreement and to source
offshore production back into domestic plants if necessary to
maintain employment here,'' said UAW Vice President Stephen Yokich,
in charge of the union's GM department.
   ``There's still time for GM to demonstrate that it truly wants a
new relationship with the union and union workers,'' Yokich said in
an apparent reference to negotiations, which will begin next summer.
   The UAW-GM national contract expires exactly a year after GM's
announcement Thursday.
   GM began producing cars at the plant in Atlanta in 1929. GM would
not comment on the production rate, but a study of automotive
capacity by Autofacts Inc. of Paoli, Pa., said the plant had a
capacity of 145,000 cars a year at a line rate of 37.75 an hour on
two shifts.
   Caprice sales through Sept. 10 of this year were 116,288, down
3.6 percent from last year. Sales of the Buick wagon were down 15
percent to 6,536 cars. As of Sept. 10, all of GM's North
American-made cars were selling at a rate 7.1 percent below last
year's.
</TEXT>
