<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said retail sales rose a
moderate 0.7 percent in August because of strong automobile sales
but analysts foresee growing sluggishness in the remainder of the
year.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that sales increased to a
seasonally adjusted $144.3 billion in August following a 0.5 percent
gain in July. Sales had remained flat in June after rising 0.8
percent in May.
   Analysts said the report was consistent with the so-called
``soft-landing'' scenario sought by the Federal Reserve as it moves
to keep inflation under control while permitting continued, but
slower, economic growth.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC says it will sell $1.31
billion in assets and cut its work force 17 percent in a major
restructuring aimed at boosting efficiency and focusing on
higher-risk oil exploration.
   BP, the world's fourth-largest oil company, said Thursday it
would sell exploration assets off Great Britain's North Sea and in
six other countries to Oryx Energy Co. of the United States.
   BP said it agreed to sell 9 percent of its British exploration
assets in the North Sea, including four oil- and gas-producing
fields, five prospective developments and 42 unexplored blocks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Milken's lawyers have asked a federal
judge to order the government to halt ``a constant stream'' of leaks
to the press they claim treatens the indicted bond financier's right
to a fair trial.
   The lawyers claim the government has turned confidential grand
jury proceedings into ``a spectator sport'' by leaking information
about the federal probe repeatedly over the last three years to
pressure witnesses and other possible targets to cooperate.
   Milken has been indicted on fraud and racketeering charges. The
motion was filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, prodded by congressional
leaders to do more for the new Polish government, has announced he
will double _ to $100 million _ next year's U.S. food aid to that
nation.
   Foods to be sent to Poland, all coming from existing surpluses,
include beef, pork, corn, butter, sunflower oil, cotton and rice.
The new program was announced Thursday. The aid, for the fiscal year
that begins Oct. 1, will follow $8.4 million in emergency food aid
sent to Poland this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orin Atkins, the former chairman and chief
executive officer of Ashland Oil Inc., has pleaded guilty to charges
he tried to sell confidential company documents to an Iranian oil
company involved in a dispute with Ashland.
   Atkins, 65, of North Palm Beach, Fla., pleaded guilty Thursday in
U.S. District Court to conspiracy and wire fraud. He faces a maximum
of 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine when sentenced Nov. 16.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government would come out ahead if it
repealed or relaxed a law that reduces the Social Security benefits
of senior citizens who earn more than a limited amount of outside
income, a group of House Republicans says.
   GOP critics of Social Security's earnings test released a private
study Thursday concluding that at least 700,000 retirees would
rejoin the labor market if the law were scrapped. The new workers
would generate more in income and payroll taxes than the government
would pay out in increased Social Security benefits.
</TEXT>
