a cut in the capital gains tax, helping fulfill one of President
Bush's campaign promises over the vehement objections of Democratic
leaders.
   The committee in a closed-door session Thursday approved the cut
19-17 as six conservative Democrats sided with the 13 Republicans on
the panel.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market extended its September slump Thursday in selling
blamed on takeover-debt worries. The Dow Jones industrials average,
down 27.74 points Wednesday, dropped another 14.63 to 2,664.89.
   The dollar rebounded to finish higher in choppy U.S. dealings.
   Treasury bonds and most corporate bonds rose but the junk bond
market continued to weaken.
   Copper for spot delivery surged to a 4{-month high; pork bellies
rose the limit and grain futures rallied on news of a food-aid
package to Poland; energy futures fell and precious metals were
mixed.
