<FIRST>r f PM-FordTrucks     09-15 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford Trucks,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Says New Truck Production Heading to Ky. Truck Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says it will move production of its
Cargo line of medium- and heavy-duty trucks from Brazil to its
Kentucky Truck plant near Louisville.
   The company also said Thursday it plans to spend three times as
much on its North American heavy-truck business over the next five
years than it did in the previous five years.
   Spokesman D.W. Haines said the company would provide no figures
because of competitive reasons.
   Edward Hagenlocker, a vice president and general manager of Ford
Truck Operations, made the announcements at the North American Ford
Heavy Truck Annual Dealer meeting in Vancouver, British Columbia,
according to a news release received in Detroit.
   He said production of the Cargo trucks at the Kentucky truck
plant would start in the last three months of next year. The company
said it would continue its current production at the plant along
with Cargo production, bringing total production to about 70,000
vehicles a year.
   The 2,000-employee work force will not change with the addition
of the Cargo trucks, Haines said.
   Cargo line trucks also are made in Australia and the United
Kingdom, but none of their production is for the U.S. market.
   On Wednesday, Ford announced it would move production of its
Ranger light pickup from the Louisville Plant, which is near the
Kentucky Truck plant, to Edison, N.J., to make way for a new
two-door and four-door Explorer sport-utility vehicle that will
replace the Bronco II.
</TEXT>
