<DOCNO> AP890915-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-JunkBonds Bjt   09-15 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battered Junk Bond Market Awaits Campeau's Next Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battered junk bond market is anxiously
waiting to see whether Campeau Corp. can snatch its prime retail
operations from the precipice of default.
   Campeau's Federated Department Stores Inc. is scheduled to make a
loan payment today reported to be in the $50 million range, but
Campeau needs an outside infusion of cash to prevent a default.
   In the junk bond market, where trading of the high-yield,
high-risk securities took a gut-wrenching hit earlier this week,
``everybody is looking to see how Campeau gets out of this mess,
because it could have a big effect on everything,'' said John Moran,
a trader at Advest Inc.
   Admissions that both Federated and Campeau's Allied Stores Corp.
units could default on their debt payments triggered a broad junk
bond selloff earlier this week that spread to issues regarded as
among the most stable and attractive.
   Critics have long contended that junk bonds, typically used to
finance expensive, highly leveraged takeovers, were ripe for a fall.
The thinking goes that companies would default on interest payments
either because they would be unable to sell divisions at the heady
prices they anticipated or because cash flows would not live up to
expectations.
   Robert Campeau, head of the Toronto-based real estate and retail
concern, was scrambling to line up financing from Olympia &amp; York
Developments Ltd. to pay the debt.
   Any success in getting more financing for Allied and Federated,
which are in dire need of credit so they can stock up on inventory
ahead of the Christmas shopping season, would help not only to prop
up those precarious issues but the junk market in general.
   Traders fear that if the market is widely perceived as too risky
and unstable, investors will dump their holdings.
   ``If too many people start jumping on the band wagon, the
(junk-bond) mutual fund managers are not going to have enough cash
to cover redemptions, and they're going to be forced to blow out of
their positions,'' one observer said.
   So far traders said they had not detected any significant selling
by mutual funds that invest in junk bonds.
   Moran said managers ``are studying the situation'' and are not
likely to act hastily. ``Besides, the whole thing is up in the
air,'' he said, noting that Campeau could succeed in its
restructuring plans.
   While some market experts said this week's selloff was
particularly significant because more stable, attractive issues fell
in tandem with distressed bonds, others contend the downturn was due.
   Robert Levine, president of Kidder Peabody High Yield Asset
Management, characterized the decline as more of a ``technical
correction'' because prices had been on the upswing recently.
Furthermore, there has been no change in the credit quality of most
companies, he said.
   Yields quoted on some Allied and Federated issues have soared
well above 25 percent to compensate for heightened risk.
   But, said Anthony Naylor, a senior vice president at Rodman &amp;
Renshaw Inc., ``When a bond is trading at a 25 percent yield, it
means they're not going to pay.''
   Campeau used billions of dollars from the sale of junk bonds to
finance its $8.8 billion takeover of Federated last year. Not only
did he pay top dollar for the retail company, but a stagnant
consumer market dashed his plans for relying on cash flow to pay
down the debt.
   Last week, Campeau put its flagship Bloomingdale's department
store chain on the auction block in an effort to raise cash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
