<DOCNO> AP890915-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-Breeden Bjt   09-15 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Breeden, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breeden: SEC Staff Needs More Money to Remain Competitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard C. Breeden, President Bush's choice for
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, pledges to crack
down hard on inside traders but says his No. 1 problem is improving
the pay of the agency's staff.
   The nominee told senators at his confirmation hearing Thursday
that he would ``absolutely'' continue the SEC's current efforts ``to
root fraud out of the securities markets.''
   But Breeden also said pay increases for SEC staffers were
necessary to attract new talent and cut the agency's high turnover
rate.
   ``I don't know of any single issue facing the commission today
that is more important than our ability to maintain the caliber and
the quality of the staff,'' Breeden said.
   The starting salary for an SEC staff attorney is $27,130 _ well
below what a top law school graduate can make at a Wall Street law
firm, SEC officials said.
   In a morning-long hearing before the Senate Banking, Housing and
Urban Affairs Committee, Breeden, who once headed a task force on
deregulation of the financial industry, said he believed in free,
competitive markets.
   But, he added, ``Free markets don't work if investors or
participants believe they are dominated by fraud or corruption.''
   The committee will decide if Breeden's nomination should be
recommended to the full Senate.
   ``I think you can do an exceptional job, but it won't be easy,''
said Committee Chairman Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich., adding that he
intended to vote for Breeden's confirmation.
   After the hearing, Riegle told reporters he expected a
confirmation vote would come ``in a few days.''
   Riegle noted Breeden still had to supply detailed answers to
written questions posed by the committee staff.
   Breeden, a White House aide who helped write the legislation to
bail out the nation's savings and loan industry, was tapped by Bush
for the SEC post last month.
   At the time, Riegle and other senators expressed skepticism about
the banking lawyer's experience in the securities industry.
   But the promised public grilling of the nominee never
materialized, apparently due to Breeden's impressive performance in
private meetings with committee members earlier this week.
   Several senators remarked about those private meetings in
praising Breeden's intelligence and candor during the hearing.
   Breeden told Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., that it's ``a
perfectly legitimate role of government to keep the markets clean.''
He said that would restore individual investors' confidence in the
markets and attract foreign investment.
   When Riegle expressed hope that wrongdoers would find Breeden a
``fair but tough cop on the beat,'' Breeden replied, ``Certainly, if
I am fortunate enough to be confirmed, under my leadership that will
be the case.''
   Breeden appeared relaxed but cautious as he answered committee
members' questions, constantly asserting that his views were his own
and he couldn't speak for the SEC.
   He said the $200 billion junk bond market ``is worth the careful
attention of the commission'' although he was ``not suggesting
there's any particular problem in the market today.''
   Breeden also said he didn't think the SEC had been
``overzealous'' in its pursuit of insider trading and said the
charges against the investment banking giant Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. were for more than ``harmless technical problems.''
   He said the SEC and the rival Commodity Futures Trading
Commission should remain separate agencies and called for a better
working relationship, including staff exchanges, with the CFTC,
which has disputed the SEC jurisdiction over some new financial
instruments that have elements of both securities and futures
contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
