<FIRST>r f PM-LuxuryCarWars     09-15 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Luxury Car Wars,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lexus and Infiniti Bear Watching, Cadillac Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cadillac should hang on to its share
of the luxury car market in 1990 despite the entry of two Japanese
luxury car lines this year, the division's general manager says.
   John Grettenberger also said Thursday that the popularity of
Nissan's Infiniti line and Toyota's Lexus cars would be watched
closely by Cadillac officials.
   Lexus cars officially went on sale Sept. 1, but some had been
sold before they arrived in showrooms. Infiniti's two models go on
sale Nov. 8.
   ``We're not taking it lightly at all,'' Grettenberger said during
Cadillac's 1990 introduction. ``I'm not surprised that Cadillac
owners are susceptible.''
   A survey by Thomas O'Grady of Integrated Automotive Resources
Inc. in Wayne, Pa., showed that of 200 people who bought Lexus cars
during the first month of sale, 12.2 percent of them traded in
Cadillacs and 6.1 percent switched from Lincolns.
   Early predictions by Lexus officials forecast that about 10
percent of the cars traded in on their two models would be Cadillacs
or Lincolns. Many more people would trade in European luxury cars,
including Mercedes and BMW, and others would step up to Lexus from
other Toyota-made cars, they said.
   Infiniti's two cars will be in about 50 Infiniti dealers on Nov.
8. Dave Hubbard, Infiniti's national advertising director, said
Thursday the division had not predicted the kinds of cars that would
be traded in.
   However, he added, Infiniti had a long-range goal of capturing
buyers moving into the luxury segment for the first time.
   Grettenberger said it was understandable that a large percentage
of trade-ins would be Cadillacs since Cadillac is the largest player
in the luxury car market, holding about 26.8 percent of it.
   ``There's no question that the newest products from Japan will
represent formidable competition,'' Grettenberger said.
   Cadillac's base prices for 1990 range from $26,960 to $36,980
with the Allante's prices at $50,900 for the new convertible-only
version at $50,900 and $56,533 for the model with a removable
hardtop, the same price as last year.
   Lexus' two cars carry base prices of $21,050 and $35,000, and
Infiniti cars cost $23,500 and $38,000.
   ``They've done a very good job of preparing the market for the
car,'' Grettenberger said of Lexus. ``It will be interesting to see
if they can maintain this level over the next couple of months.''
   Lexus has forecast annual sales of about 75,000 cars, about
one-fourth Cadillac's prediction. Hubbard said Infiniti would make
no sales projections for the first year.
   Grettenberger said he expected Cadillac to continue to command
the lion's share of the luxury car market. holding on to its 26.8
percent share.
   Asked where Lexus and Infiniti would get their buyers,
Grettenberger said they most likely would come from the European
makers.
   ``Luxury car buyers like to buy new things,'' he said.
   For 1990, Cadillac has kept the basic exterior designs of its
entire line. It is introducing the convertible Allante, adding a
traction control system for the two-seater.
   It also is putting more powerful engines in the De Ville,
Fleetwood, Seville and Eldorado models. In addition, Cadillac is
making other changes in all its cars, none of which will affect how
the vehicles look.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
