<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Curtiss-Wright     09-15 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Curtiss-Wright,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Contractor Agrees to Pay $1.4 Million Civil Fine, Official
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's chief supplier of hydraulic
aircraft landing gear has agreed to repay the government about $1.4
million in contract overcharges for the Air Force's largest
transport plane.
   The government claimed that labor charges on a $6.7 million
contract were twice as high as original estimates by the company,
Curtiss-Wright of Ridgefield, N.J., said U.S. Attorney Samuel A.
Alito Jr.
   The contract was for 60 spare landing gear actuators that control
landing gear, flaps and other moveable exterior systems on the Air
Force's Lockheed C-5A Galaxy.
   Alito said the company's failure to provide Air Force auditors
with labor standards and data on the company's internal cost
estimates ``led to a gross inflation of the labor costs.''
   Curtiss-Wright has denied any wrongdoing. Attempts to reach
corporate officials after the settlement was announced Thursday
evening were unsuccessful and the switchboard at the company's
headquarters was closed.
   The government contends Curtiss-Wright's contract was based on a
company estimate of 46,000 labor hours for the contract. Alito said
investigators found the contract was completed in 23,000 hours.
   ``The company's failure to live up to its certification with
respect to the C-5A flight actuators subjected it to civil
liability,'' Alito said in a statement.
   Under the False Claims Act, a Civil War-era statute aimed at
wartime profiteers, the government can demand reimbursement when it
can prove a contractor was not negotiated in good faith. The act was
further bolstered in 1986 by amendments that allow the government to
claim triple damages and apply large fines.
   Alito said the claims were not part of criminal or civil court
proceedings but were the result of a preliminary investigation by
his office and the Defense Criminal Investigative Service, an arm of
the U.S. Defense Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
