<FIRST>r f BC-DaytonHudson     09-15 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dayton Hudson,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>President to Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce G. Allbright plans to retire early next
year as president and a director of Dayton Hudson Corp., the
retailer said Thursday.
   Allbright, 60, has been president of the Minneapolis-based
corporation for two years. He will retire from that position and as
a director on Feb. 1, 1990, at the end of the corporation's fiscal
year.
   Allbright was elected president of the corporation in September
1987 after having been chairman and chief executive officer of its
Target discount store division since 1984. He joined Dayton Hudson
in 1971 as president and chief executive of its B. Dalton Bookseller
unit.
   He left Dayton Hudson in late 1981 to join F.W. Woolworth Co. as
chairman and chief executive officer but returned to the company the
next year.
   Kenneth A. Macke, Dayton Hudson chairman and CEO, praised
Allbright's contributions. ``He was very influential in the speeding
up of Target's growth and its entry into the key West Coast
markets,'' Macke said.
   Macke also announced the election of Stephen E. Watson as
executive vice president of the corporation. Watson has been with
Dayton Hudson since 1973.
   Watson, 44, has been chairman and CEO of Dayton Hudson Department
Store Co. since 1985. He will continue to hold those positions.
   Dayton Hudson has about 135,000 employees in its Target, Mervyn's
and Dayton Hudson Department Store Co. divisions and operates 675
stores in 38 states.
</TEXT>
