<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0818EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AshlandOil     09-15 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ashland Oil,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Chairman Pleads Guilty to Scheme to Sell Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of Ashland Oil Inc. has pleaded
guilty to conspiracy and wire fraud for his role in a scheme to try
to sell confidential company documents.
   Orin Atkins, 65, of North Palm Beach, Fla., entered the plea in
U.S. District Court on Thursday. He faces a maximum of 10 years in
prison and a $500,00 fine when sentenced Nov. 16.
   An attorney whose firm once worked for Ashland was indicted
Thursday for his alleged role in the same scheme.
   U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said Atkins and the lawyer, Charles
D. Barnett, were involved in a secret scheme to defraud Ashland by
attempting to sell confidential papers to the National Iranian Oil
Co., which was involved in a dispute with Ashland.
   The documents dealt with the 1979 sale of $283 million in crude
oil from the Iranian company to Ashland Overseas Trading Ltd., a
Ashland subsidiary in Bermuda. Court papers said Ashland never paid
for the oil.
   Atkins was Ashland's chairman and chief executive from 1974 to
1981. He was a consultant to Ashland, earning $425,000 a year, from
1981 to 1984.
   In 1982, while he was a paid consultant, Atkins received about
260 privileged documents about the oil sale through an unidentified
Ashland employee, Romano said.
   According to the indictment against Barnett, Atkins and Barnett
made repeated attempts from 1982 to 1988 to sell the documents and
Atkins' consulting services to the Iranian company. They had planned
to use a Swiss bank account to receive their payment, it said.
   As compensation, Atkins and Barnett asked for 25 percent of the
Iranian company's recovery from Ashland, the indictment alleged.
   In court Thursday, Atkins said the deal was never finalized
although representatives of the Iranian company were allowed to view
the documents in 1985.
   After seeing the papers, the National Iranian Oil Co. sued
Ashland and Ashland Overseas for payment on the oil. Those suits,
filed in Mississippi and Bermuda, were settled last week when
Ashland agreed to pay $325 million, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Herve Gouraige.
   Neither Ashland or National Iranian Oil Co. were charged with any
wrongdoing. Romano praised the cooperation of Ashland in the
investigation.
   Barnett, 38, of Palm Beach, Fla., was charged with conspiracy and
six counts of wire fraud. If convicted, he faces five years in
prison and a $250,000 fine on each count.
   He was not in custody and was scheduled to be arraigned Sept. 21.
An earlier complaint charging Barnett and former Ashland vice
president Charles Dugan with interstate transportation of stolen
property was dismissed during the investigation that led to the
latest charges.
   Barnett was identifed as a former partner in the law firm of
Barnett &amp; Alagia, based in Louisville, Ky., with offices around the
country. The indictment said the firm represented Ashland in certain
legal matters while Atkins was chairman.
   Gouraige declined to discuss why the earlier complaint against
Barnett and Dugan was dismissed.
</TEXT>
