<FIRST>r f PM-BellAtlantic     09-15 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bell Atlantic,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bell Atlantic Announces Restructuring, Early Retirement for 1,000
Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. has launched a
restructuring program that will trim as many as 1,200 managers from
the workforce despite years of steady profit growth.
   The regional telephone company announced Thursday it would offer
early retirement incentives aimed at cutting 1,000 to 1,200 managers
and said it is also considering several financial moves such as
refinancing some debts and revaluing spare parts inventories.
   The reorganization will lead to the company's first quarterly
drop in profit since it was created in 1984 by the breakup of
American Telephone and Telegraph Co.
   Bell Atlantic will break even or make a small profit in the
fourth quarter, officials said. For the same period last year, the
company made $1.53 per share.
   In the second quarter of this year, the company's net income rose
4.9 percent to $360.8 million, or $1.84 per share.
   ``We think the time to change is when you're doing well,'' said
Dennis Mollura, Bell Atlantic spokesman. ``If you wait until things
go bad, it's too late.''
   ``In a very real sense we are laying the groundwork for the Bell
Atlantic of the future,'' Raymond W. Smith, Bell Atlantic's chairman
and chief executive, said in a news release.
   Managers will be offered cash incentives and pension benefits to
retire early, the company said.
   The company will eliminate one level of management, based in
Washington, overseeing the Chesapeake and Potomac Telephone
companies in Maryland, Virginia, West Virginia and Washington. The
four telephone companies will report directly to Anton J.
Campanella, Bell Atlantic president.
   Duties at the Chesapeake and Potomac headquarters will be
absorbed by other units and the employees will be reassigned, Bell
Atlantic spokesman Kenneth A. Pitt said.
   Several internal operations such as office planning, the motor
pool, real estate management and administrative services will be
centralized.
   ``While change always will be with us, we expect this will be the
last major reorganization for the foreseeable future,'' Campanella
said.
   The company is considering seeking lower interest rates on debts
owed by Chesapeake and Potomac Telephone Companies in Maryland and
West Virginia and by Diamond State Telephone in Delaware.
   Other possible moves include revaluations of spare parts in its
computer maintenance business and reducing the book value of its
assets of smaller subsidiaries.
   The moves would decrease earnings in one quarter but give a
``slight lift'' to earnings in 1990, said Philip A. Campbell, Bell
Atlantic chief financial officer.
   Pitt said the recent three-week strike by members of the
Communications Workers of America and the International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers against Bell Atlantic played no part in the
restructuring decision or its timing.
   Bell Atlantic's seven subsidiaries are Bell of Pennsylvania, New
Jersey Bell, Diamond State Telephone in Delaware and the Chesapeake
and Potomac companies in Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia and the
District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
