<FIRST>r f BC-Mitsubishi-NYSE     09-15 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mitsubishi-NYSE,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi Bank to List on New York Stock Exchange Next Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mitsubishi Bank Ltd. next week will become the first Japanese
bank to be listed on the New York Stock Exchange and also will rank
as the largest foreign company traded on the Big Board, published
reports said Friday.
   Mitsubishi, the world's fourth-largest bank, will be the ninth
Japanese company to be listed on the NYSE, according to the New York
Times.
   American investors will be allowed to trade more than two billion
Mitsubishi shares, which initially will trade in the form of
American depository receipts, the paper said.
   The move marks the first attempt by a Japanese bank to raise
money in the American capital markets, which some Wall Street
observers have predicted would be a growing trend, the paper said.
   The major Japanese banks are under pressure to raise $35 billion
over the next four years in order to comply with new capital
requirements that the world's leading central banks have set for
international banks.
   The Times noted that Japanese banks had not been expected to
resort to the New York Stock Exchange to raise capital because they
would have to meet Securities and Exchange Commission disclosure
requirements as well as alter their accounting practices. But
Mitsubishi has met the requirements.
   In Tokyo, the economic newspaper Nihon Keizai Shimbun said the
listing would be made on Sept. 19.
   Established in 1919, Mitsubishi had assets totalling about $343.2
billion and net income of $1.15 billion for the fiscal year ended
March 31, according to a company report.
   The Tokyo-based bank has 245 domestic offices and 37 overseas
affiliates in 24 countries.
   Mitsubishi and Japanese government officials were not available
for comment Friday, which was a national holiday in Japan.
</TEXT>
