<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today, getting
support from unexpectedly favorable economic news.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.08 to 2,670.97 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 699 up, 406 down and
568 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 78.68 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour,''
involving the last trading in a group of expiring options and
futures on stock indexes.
   There had been concern that professional traders engaged in
multiple strategies involving those contracts would depress the
market with a barrage of sell orders for stocks.
   But at the opening the market absorbed whatever pressure resulted
from the witching hour, with a big assist from the latest data on
the state of the economy.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods dropped 0.4 percent in August for its third
consecutive monthly decline.
   And the Commerce Department said the nation's trade deficit
narrowed to $7.58 billion in July from a downward-revised $8.01
billion in June.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Merck, up ] at 70};
American Express, up \ at 36[; General Motors, up ] at 48~, and
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up [ at 40].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.31 to 191.26. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .16 at 381.10.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 14.63 to
2,664.89, bringing its loss over the past two sessions to 42.37
points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 3 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 387 up, 1,112 down and 459 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 149.25 million shares, down from 175.33
million in the previous session.
