<FIRST>u f PM-Campeau 1stLd-Writethru f0008 09-15 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campeau, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0008,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Word Awaited from Campeau on Financial Rescue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Junk Bonds, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with no announcement from Campeau,
stock remaining halted in Canada. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Campeau has ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading in Campeau Corp. stock remained halted today while the
debt-crippled retail and property holding company worked out
arrangements for a financial rescue.
   Toronto Stock Exchange spokesman Steven Kee said this morning the
exchange had been advised that Campeau expected to make a statement
shortly.
   The company Thursday had told the exchange it expected to have an
announcement before the market opened Friday. Campeau stock has been
halted since Wednesday, pending an announcement from Campeau.
   There was no indication from the company when any news might be
forthcoming. The company's spokeswoman was not taking telephone
calls.
   Campeau has such a desperate need for cash to run its retail
subsidiaries that it was forced to turn to a major stockholder for
funds and was widely expected to cede control to the lender, Olympia
&amp; York Developments Ltd.
   As part of a restructuring to cope with its debts, Campeau also
decided to put its Bloomingdale's department store chain up for sale.
   Campeau's Allied Stores Corp. and Federated Department Stores
Inc. divisions, which operate numerous U.S. chains, have run very
short of working capital.
   Without the $250 million loan from Olympia &amp; York, it appeared
uncertain how Campeau would be able to obtain credit so that its
department stores could stock shelves adequately before the crucial
Christmas season. Plus, Federated needs an infusion of funds because
it faces a loan payment deadline today.
   Disclosure of the severity of Campeau's financial problems on
Wednesday rocked the market for high-interest ``junk bonds'' that
the company used to finance its buyouts of Allied and Federated and
contributed to a selloff in the stock market.
   The junk bond market calmed on Thursday as trading slowed and
participants awaited more word from Campeau.
   Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York, which has a 24.5 stake in Campeau,
was expected to gain a larger interest in Campeau in exchange for
granting the loan. There has been speculation that Chairman Robert
Campeau, who owns nearly 54 percent of the Toronto-based company,
would relinquish controlling interest.
   Campeau and Olympia &amp; York entered an agreement in principle but
various other parties _ Campeau's creditors _ had to agree to the
arrangements before the loan deal could be activated.
   Separately, Campeau issued its second-quarter financial results
Thursday. It reported a loss of $124 million in the three months
ended July 31 on revenue of $2.26 billion, compared to a loss of
$109 million and revenue of $2.21 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
