<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-15 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed in Early Tradings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade in light trading
amid an absence of significant changes in supply-and-demand factors.
   Soybeans were a little stronger, reflecting temporary supply
tightness in Europe caused by weather-related delays in shipping
soybeans and soybean meal from Brazil, Europe's main source of
imported soybeans.
   ``They've had a tremendous amount of rain in some of the South
American ports and that's created a situation where stuff that
should be in Europe by now hasn't gotten there yet,'' said Gerald
Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s floor operations at the
Board of Trade.
   Corn futures were mostly lower in light of forecasts for fair
weather this weekend in the Midwest, which could speed up harvest
activity.
   Wheat futures were a little stronger but trading activity was
light in the absence of new export business.
   In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent to 2\ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.86{ a bushel; corn
futures were 2\ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with September at
$2.37{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent lower with December
at $1.42{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents lower to 1\ cents higher
with September at $5.85 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .12 cent lower with October at 72.40
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .12 cent lower with
October at 82.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .15 cent
higher with October at 40.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.50 cent to .72 cent lower with February at 47.65 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Thursday, paced by
the pork bellies, on reports that President Bush was authorizing an
additional $50 million in food aid to Poland that would include pork
products.
</TEXT>
