<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru f0023 09-15 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges Despite Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with central banks selling dollars
after dollar surges.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against all major
currencies in active European trading Friday after the release of
unexpectedly good U.S. trade data. Gold traded in a tight range.
   The dollar gained sharply after the U.S. government reported that
the nation's trade deficit narrowed to $7.58 billion in July from
$8.01 billion in June. Economists had predicted a trade gap of
around $9 billion.
   Though the data triggered an apparently concerted round of
dollar-selling by central banks, the dollar edged up to three-month
highs against a batch of currencies.
   In London, the British pound fell nearly two cents on Friday to
$1.5375, compared with $1.5582 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with morning rates in
parentheses, compared with Thursday's late rates included: 2.0015
(1.9758) West German marks, up from 1.9705; 1.7305 (1.7050) Swiss
francs, up from 1.7000; 6.7375 (6.6660) French francs, up from
6.6485; 2.2470 (2.2250) Dutch guilders, up from 2.2185; 1,432.50
(1,417.20) Italian lire, up from 1,413.00; and, 1.1895 (1.1840)
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849.
   The yen was not traded Friday in Tokyo, because markets were
closed for Respect for the Aged Day, a national holiday. In London
the dollar traded at 148.95, compared with 146.90 yen earlier Friday
and 145.85 yen in Tokyo Thursday.
   New York currency dealers also said they detected the Federal
Reserve Board selling dollars to stem a surge after the economic
reports were released. The U.S. central bank never comments on
intervention.
   Gold opened in London at $359.75 bid per troy ounce, down from
Thursday's late price of $362.00. At mid-morning the city's major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $359.65.
   Gold traded in Zurich at $359.70 bid per troy ounce, compared to
$361.75 late Thursday.
   Hong Kong's gold market was closed today because of the Chinese
mid-autumn festival.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid $5.07 a troy ounce, down
from $5.12.
</TEXT>
