<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MGM-UA     09-15 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MGM-UA,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>MGM-UA Reaches Quits Talk With Murdoch, Reaches Agreement With Qintex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH COTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA Communications Corp. today
accepted a $1.9 billion buyout offer from Australia's Qintex Group,
a sweetened bid that topped a $1.8 billion offer from Rupert Murdoch.
   Qintex increased its offer to $25 per share from its earlier $20
bid, MGM-UA spokeswoman Mary Hardy said.
   Two companies controlled by Murdoch, News Corp. Ltd. and Fox
Inc., offered $23.16 a share in a surprise bid announced Tuesday.
   Qintex sealed its latest offer with a promise to promptly make a
non-refundable $50 million deposit on MGM-UA, which encompasses the
remainder of the old United Artists and MGM movie studios.
   Under the terms of the agreement, Qintex would acquire all of
MGM-UA's outstanding common stock for $25 per share and all its
preferred stock for $18 per share, she said.
   MGM-UA negotiated with News Corp. and Fox until late Thursday,
but then ended their talks.
   Howard Rubenstein, a Murdoch spokesman, said MGM-UA had
approached him about a buyout.``He thought he had a deal, but then
the transaction fell apart,'' Rubenstein said.
   MGM-UA has spent 18-months trying to find a buyer satisfactory to
MGM-UA's controlling shareholder Kirk Kerkorian, who has repeatedly
sold and then repurchased many of the assets of the studios.
   The Qintex deal provides for $1.33 billion to be paid for
MGM-UA's common stock, $180 million for its preferred stocks, and
$400 million in junk bond debt that Qintex is assuming.
   Murdoch's offer valued MGM-UA at about $1.8 billion, including
the debt.
   A previous Qintex deal would essentially split MGM-UA, with
Qintex paying about $600 million for the United Artists studio and
some other assets. It would have given the famous lion logo, the MGM
TV operations, a library of 34 recent movies, and the MGM-UA
headquarters building in Beverly hills to Kerkorian.
   But under the agreement announced today, there would be no
repurchase of any MGM-UA's assets or any investments in Qintex by
former MGM-UA shareholders.
   Kerkorian owns 82 percent of MGM-UA's common stock and all but a
tiny fraction of the preferred stock.
   However, MGM Grand Inc., a Kerkorian-controlled company that
operates a first-class airline and Nevada casinos, will purchase the
MGM-UA headquarters building in October for $43 million or its
independently appraised value.
   MGM-UA will make about $26 million on that deal, the company said.
   In addition to the 20th Century Fox studio, Murdoch's newspaper,
magazine and television enterprises on four continents are said to
be worth more than $8 billion.
   Murdoch, who needs programming for his Sky Television satellite
channels in Britain, had his eye on MGM-UA's huge United Artists
film libraries, which include the recent movies ``Rain Man,''
``Betrayed'' and ``Baby Boom,'' as well as the ``Rocky,'' ``Pink
Panther,'' and James Bond pictures.
   Qintex, also owns 43 percent of Qintex Entertainment, a Los
Angeles based producer of television movies and miniseries such as
``Lonesome Dove.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
