<FIRST>a f BC-DiscountGolf Adv18   09-15 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Discount Golf, Adv 18,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Sept. 18 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Broken 7-Iron Inspiration For Las Vegas Discount Golf Chain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voss Boreta was a failed casino host between
jobs when a broken 7-iron got him off the golf course and into the
golf equipment business.
   Fifteen years later, he heads one of the country's biggest golf
retailing outfits, one now poised to enter the lucrative Japanese
market with a chain of 30 new stores.
   ``We were just going to have a little store,'' Boreta said of the
humble beginnings of his Las Vegas Discount Golf &amp; Tennis empire.
``It's just kind of grown from there.''
   From the 1,200-square-foot store tucked in the corner of an aging
shopping center, Boreta's discount golf outfit has grown into a
multimillion-dollar operation with 42 franchises nationwide and 13
more ready to open this year.
   The chain, riding a nationwide boom in golf, did $47 million in
business in 1988, $12 million of that at its main Las Vegas store
alone, ranking it near the top golf equipment retailers in the
country.
   Not bad for a one-time avid golfer who doesn't even play the game
anymore.
   ``I haven't played since 1975,'' Boreta said recently in an
interview in his cramped and cluttered office in the back of the
original store. ``With the company growing like it has, I didn't
have the time to devote to playing.''
   Timing has been everything for the 52-year-old Boreta, a former
San Francisco nightclub operator who freely admits he stumbled into
the golf game almost by accident.
   Boreta came to Las Vegas in 1974 to become a casino host at the
Tropicana Hotel. But, after three days, he decided the job didn't
suit him and spent his days playing golf while deciding his future
plans.
   ``One day I broke a 7-iron and there was no place to fix it,''
Boreta recalled. ``I sent it to a friend who ran a golf shop in San
Francisco and told him there was a great opportunity here. He said,
`Why don't you do it?'''
   Boreta took the advice and opened the original Las Vegas Discount
Golf store in a shopping center near the Las Vegas airport. The
store grossed $275,000 the first year and Boreta was off and running.
   It was a tenative step into mail order two years later, however,
that put the company name on the national map and on its way to
being a major player in the golf equipment business.
   ``We put a little ad in Golf Digest (magazine) that people had to
call with their own dime,'' Boreta said. ``When they called, we told
them we'd send them a catalog when we didn't even have one put
together yet. But the next thing you know, here comes a couple of
orders in.''
   Ironically, one of the country's largest golf mail-order outlets
and franchisers, Nevada Bob's, also got its start in Las Vegas.
   At the same time the discount golf shops were beginning to
expand, golf club manufacturers were broadening their club lines to
tap the beginners market.
   ``These manufacturers got smart and started making game
improvement clubs,'' Boreta said. ``That is what really started the
golfing boom. Now, you can take a non-player and after one lesson he
can hit the ball in the air and in the general direction he or she
wants it.''
   Those clubs have been constantly improving and Japanese companies
have taken the lead in marrying boron and graphite shafts that are
stronger, longer and more accurate than their steel predecessors.
   Partly as a result, according to the Florida-based National Golf
Foundation, some 23.4 million people played at least one round of
golf last year, up from 15.1 million in 1980.
   More than 320 new courses have opened since 1987 in the United
States, bringing the total to more than 13,000. In Japan, there are
an estimated 12 million golfers and 1,600 courses.
   ``I've never seen anything like the last few years as far as
people playing the game,'' Boreta said. ``It seems like just in the
last two years it has really taken off.''
   Boreta sees an even bigger opportunity in the lucrative Japanese
market and his chain has signed an agreement with a Japanese company
to open a store in Tokyo next month followed by 29 others for other
locations in the golf-crazy country.''
   ``We get a tremendous amount of Japanese who come here and buy
three or four sets of clubs and take them home to sell to friends,''
Boreta said. ``We figured we'd take the operation to them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Sept. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
