<FIRST>d f BC-Mercantile     09-15 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mercantile,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mercantile Co. Moving Headquarters to Cincinnati</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mercantile Co., parent of 12 groups of
department and specialty stores, has announced plans to move its
headquarters to Cincinnati from New York.
   Mercantile said Thursday it will transfer its executive staff and
accounting, financial and data processing offices to Cincinnati, but
will keep its merchandising operations in New York. The shift will
take place during the next few years and could involve several
hundred employees.
   David Huhn, Mercantile's new chairman and chief executive
officer, said no Cincinnati site has been selected and no timetable
has been set for the move. He was in Cincinnati on Thursday, but
declined to say why the move is being made. The company will remain
incorporated in Delaware.
   Huhn, a Cincinnati native, had kept his family residence in
Cincinnati since moving to New York last year as executive vice
president. He had been president of the company's group of McAlpin's
department stores, which includes nine stores in Cincinnati and
Lexington, Ky., since 1972.
   His promotion to chairman and chief executive officer was
announced Monday.
   Mercantile's other store groups are Bacon's, in Louisville, Ky.;
Root's, Terre Haute, Ind.; Castner Knott Co., Nashville, Tenn.;
Gayfer's, Mobile and Montgomery, Ala.; Jones Store Co., Kansas City,
Mo.; J.B. White, Augusta, Ga.; Lion's, Toledo, Ohio; Joslin's,
Denver, Colo.; De Lendrecie's, Fargo, N.D.: Hennessy's, Billings,
Mont.; Glass Block, Duluth, Minn.
</TEXT>
