<DOCNO> AP890915-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1431EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CableStation     09-15 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable Station,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Operator to Debut Independent Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent television station being
launched by a local cable operator could signal the opening of a new
battleground between cable and free television.
   WGRC-TV, scheduled to debut Thursday in Rochester, will air
syndicated network reruns, sports, movies, and locally produced
children's shows. The station hopes eventually to debut a local
newscast and is negotiating to broadcast some New York Mets and
Yankees games.
   ``It's an expansion of cable's promise, which is to deliver
programming choice to subscribers,'' said Robert Alter, president of
the Cable Television Advertising Bureau in New York City.
   ``It's providing expanded, enriched service that is very
localized.''
   The station will be programmed and operated by local cable
operator Greater Rochester Cablevision, which currently reaches 62
percent of the area's households with televisions. The Rochester
market has one non-cable independent station.
   Alter predicted that if the Rochester station is successful,
independent stations will be launched in other markets. Some cable
operators have already begun airing local news shows, he said.
   Lana King, marketing vice president for the Association of
Independent Television Stations, reacted with dismay to the advent
of the new station and the possibility of others like it.
   ``This threatens our ability to serve the community free of
charge,'' she said. ``It's a fear that we have had for a long time.''
   King said that cable stations, with the added revenue from
subscriber charges as well as advertising, can outbid independent
television stations for syndicated programming.
   Eventually, she said, viewers could end up having to pay to see
the same programs they would have gotten for free.
   ``We're seeing it happening in sports,'' she said. ``That same
phenomenon is now happening in all programming.''
   The Rochester cable station currently carries locally originated
programming like fishing shows.
   GRC President and chief executive officer Frank Chiaino said the
idea for the station originated in Rochester, but that GRC's parent
company, New York City-based Time Warner Inc., will be ``watching
what we do with interest.''
   The station was created to increase advertising revenues and
subscribers and in response to new syndication laws, Chiaino said.
   Time Warner may sell advertising on the station in packages with
its other products, including Sports Illustrated and Time magazines,
according to James P. Murtagh of Seltel Inc., a sales representative
for the station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
