<FIRST>r f BC-DiGiorgioSale     09-15 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Di Giorgio Sale,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Di Giorgio Seeks Offers For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Di Giorgio Corp., a $1 billion a year food
and building materials company that has rejected a $163 million
buyout offer, said Friday it is seeking formal proposals for sale of
all or part of the company.
   Di Giorgio, parent of White Rose foods, said several third
parties had expressed interest on a preliminary basis but did not
say who they are.
   The company last month rejected as inadequate an unsolicited
offer of $32 a share made by an investor group led by Arthur
Goldberg and urged its shareholders not to tender shares to the
Goldberg group. The offer, which had been due to expire on Aug. 30,
was extended to Sept. 20.
   In late afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Di
Giorgio was up $1 a share at $33.75, indicating traders' belief that
a better offer than Goldberg's is likely.
   For the first six months of this year, Di Giorgio earned $4.5
million, or 70 cents a share, on revenue of $565 million. It had
$1.05 billion in revenue for all of 1988.
   The company is engaged in food distribution through its White
Rose Food Division. It processes and sells speciality meats through
its Cerando Division. Di Giorgio also makes and sells a variety of
building materials through its DG Mouldings, BiltBest Windows and
Las Plumas Lumber Divisions.
</TEXT>
