<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-15 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Futures Drop On Lack Of Expected Soviet Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a quiet session marked by a
lack of significant supply-and-demand developments.
   The corn market weakened late in the session when confirmation of
a rumored Soviet corn purchase failed to materialize.
   Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s floor
operations at the exchange, said the speculation was premature.
   ``I think the Russians are going to be significant buyers of U.S.
corn ... but not at this time,'' he said. ``You buy during the
harvest, not before the harvest. You don't get the lowest prices
right now.''
   Corn harvesting has begun but won't get into full swing for
another week, he said. The peak of the soybean harvest is still two
weeks away.
   Forecasts for clear dry weather in the Midwest this weekend also
weighed on the markets. Analysts said those conditions would help
the crops mature and speed up the early harvest activity.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1} cents lower to 3 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.88} a bushel; corn
was 2\ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with September at $2.35 a
bushel; oats were } cent lower to 2{ cents higher with September at
$1.37 a bushel; and soybeans were 3{ cents lower to } cent higher
with September at $5.82 a bushel.
</TEXT>
