<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0547EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-SharonSteel Adv18   09-15 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sharon Steel, Adv 18,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Sept. 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>Workers Unconvinced By Tale of Woe, Laying the Basis For Showdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FARRELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Steel Corp.'s chief operating officer
would have people believe his company is failing when times are good.
   True or not, E. Leonard Kern's view is rejected by employees who
will soon be asked by company negotiators to grant a third
consecutive round of contract concessions.
   ``I don't believe it, not one bit of it,'' said Jim Thompson, 56,
of Sharon, a veteran of nearly 30 years with the company. ``They're
cutthroats.''
   Kern says the company's ability to persuade the United
Steelworkers union could determine whether Sharon Steel rises from
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization or is liquidated under Chapter
7.
   That in turn will influence the economy of this steelmaking area
of western Pennsylvania, into which Sharon Steel pumps about $200
million annually as one of the largest employers with 2,600 workers.
   ``We lost money in the best steel market in a decade and have the
dubious distinction of being the only company to say that. That
gives you an idea of the destitute situation here,'' Kern said in a
recent interview in his spartan office.
   The nation's 16th-largest steelmaker has been trying to
reorganize under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy laws since April 17,
1987, listing $740 million in debts it could not pay.
   Kern's plan for saving the company begins with lowering
employment costs by cutting direct cash outlays and erasing what he
calls wasteful and inefficient work rules. New equipment would come
later.
   ``A contract has to be clearly in sight by Thanksgiving and
ratified by no later than January or February or we will face a
number of things,'' he said.
   By early next year, Kern said, the company could run out of cash
and be forced to delay bill payments, echoing events that forced it
into bankruptcy court two years ago.
   ``We're that close if the market stays soft, and I think it will
get softer,'' said Kern, a 14-year veteran of Sharon Steel
management who left in 1982 and returned in late April as chief
operating officer.
   It was not clear when contract talks would begin.
   Sharon Steel owes $70 million to pension plans for 3,500
retirees, and total labor costs are around $28 per hour, among the
highest even for major producers, said Phil Smalley, vice president
of industrial relations.
   The company's steel and steel-related segments lost $16.3 million
on sales of $263.1 million during the first half of this year,
according to the court-appointed trustee serving as chief executive.
   The company's non-steel operations _ copper and brass fabrication
at Mueller Brass Co., and coal mining at U.S. Fuel Co., and gold
mining at Alaska Gold Co. _ continue to offset much of steel's
losses and helped limit the first-half consolidated net loss to $2.5
million.
   ``How can they not be making money?'' said Sharon Steel veteran
Bud Pears. ``Guys are working overtime out their ears. We're
producing steel like crazy''
   Workers say there are plenty of signs that the company is making
money.
   Sharon Steel expanded its workforce to 2,600 by early this year
to meet demand for its products.
   Average shipments climbed from 70,000 tons per month in 1987 to
89,000 last year and were running at 92,000 tons per month through
the first half of this year.
   The steel industry is enjoying its third year of recovery.
   And Victor Posner, the Miami Beach financier accused of sucking
Sharon Steel dry of cash after acquiring control, still owns the
stock but has been stripped of his authority.
   ``People say, `Who are you kidding?' '' Kern said, acknowledging
the skepticism. ``I say even in the good days, Sharon was one of the
laggards.''
   A landlocked blast furnace, for which iron ore, coke and
limestone must be delivered by rail and truck instead of cheaper
barge transportation, is one of the disadvantages that Kern calls
congenital defects.
   ``Near-Neanderthal tools,'' an unwieldy product mix and work
rules that inflate production costs also work against the company,
he said.
   ``The market is weaker, and prices are softening, and the loss
rate is accelerating,'' Kern said. ``We're losing money, dissipating
assets.''
   Management sees another crunch coming, and warns employees in a
series of red-lettered pamphlets that without large sums of money to
buy new equipment, lower labor costs may be the only hope of
avoiding Chapter 7 liquidation.
   ``Not as far as I'm concerned,'' said Pears. ``I don't care what
they do. I'm just down there working. When it's over, it's over.
I'll go find the next job.''
   Pears and others say they're particularly bitter about an
employee stock ownership plan that the employees say is overdue in
repaying their investments.
   ``I've got $16,000 in it, and I'll never see it,'' said Pears.
``So you tell me how you'd feel towards the place. Bottom line.''
   Even those workers who are convinced Sharon Steel is in trouble
don't sound sympathetic.
   ``As far as concessions are concerned, I do believe they need
them. But as far as I'm concerned they're not going to get them,''
said Bob Ivanovich of Farrell. ``I gave and gave. There's no more to
give.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Sept. 18</NOTE>
