<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BAT Bjt   09-15 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BAT, Bjt,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoylake Gets More Time for Its BAT Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's takeover watchdog, recognizing the
increasingly international nature of the bidding process, on Friday
allowed Hoylake Investments Ltd. more time for its $21 billion bid
for BAT Industries Inc.
   In an unprecedented step, the Panel on Takeovers and Mergers,
which imposes a complex timetable on takeovers in Britain, said it
would allow Hoylake to rebid for BAT after it obtains approval from
U.S. state insurance regulators to change the ownership of BAT's
Farmers Insurance Group Inc. of Los Angeles.
   It said delays by the U.S. regulatory process meant BAT
shareholders were not able to properly consider the offer of 878
pence, or $13.52, a share in securities. The purchase would be the
world's second-largest takeover after Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp;
Co.'s $24.5 billion acquisition of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   BAT, a British conglomerate with interests in tobacco, retailing,
financial services and paper, said it would take the ruling to the
panel's appeal committee. That stops the current British takeover
clock until a final decision is reached.
   BAT's shares soared on the developments. They rose 18 pence, or
28 cents, to 819 pence, or $12.61, a share on London's Stock
Exchange on Friday.
   Hoylake still must win the green light from the U.S. regulators.
In addition, Hoylake probably would have to increase its offer or
include some cash to lure BAT's shareholders, analysts have said.
   BAT attacked the panel's decision, saying it undermined the
watchdog's goal of protecting targets from ``an indefinite and
damaging siege.''
   Hoylake said it welcomed the news and that Anglo-French financier
Sir James Goldsmith, who is spearheading the bidding group, would
depart immediately for the United States ``to establish the best way
to continue to expedite the U.S. regulatory approval.''
   Goldsmith is to meet with Claude Bebear, chairman of the French
insurance giant Axa-Midi Assurances, which wants to buy Farmers
under Hoylake's proposed break-up of BAT. Hoylake says it wants to
sell off all of BAT's non-tobacco assets.
   Other investors in Hoylake include British merchant banker Jacob
Rothschild and Australian entrepreneur Kerry Packer.
   Concern has grown in Britain over interference from U.S.
regulators and courts in takeover fights involving British companies
with U.S. interests.
   South African-controlled Minorco SA's bid for the British mining
group Consolidated Gold Fields PLC failed earlier this year because
the offer expired under British takeover rules while it was being
reviewed in U.S. federal court.
   Under the panel's rules, Hoylake, which launched its offer for
BAT on July 11, had had until Oct. 7 to obtain a majority stake in
BAT. If it had failed, it would have had to wait for a year to bid
again.
   The panel, after holding a full hearing on Wednesday, said Friday
morning that it would allow Hoylake 21 days to complete its bid for
BAT after it wins U.S. approval.
   The panel has altered its timetable in the past under varying
conditions, but it has never before granted an extension because of
U.S. regulatory holdups, said a panel official, who asked not to be
identified, in accordance with British practice.
   Explaining its decision, the panel said the delay caused by the
U.S. proceedings meant BAT shareholders were not getting a real
opportunity to consider the offer on its merits.
   ``One of the principal objects of the code is to enable the
shareholders in the target company to have an opportunity to
consider an offer for their company on its merits on an informed
basis in an orderly and limited time scale,'' the panel said.
   BAT Chairman Patrick Sheehy said BAT didn't want to deprive its
shareholders of the opportunity to consider a bid.
   ``We are simply seeking to remove the uncertainty, and also the
damage which a prolonged siege would inflict on the company,''
Sheehy said.
   BAT said the panel's ``wrong decision'' allows Hoylake to free
itself from regulatory difficulties which are ``entirely of its own
making.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0267 </DOCNO>
