<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Time-Warner     09-15 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Warner,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chris-Craft Appealing Ruling In Time-Warner Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chris-Craft Industries Inc. said Friday it was
appealing a Delaware judge's ruling that the company, a major
shareholder in Warner Communications Inc., has no power to veto the
merger between Warner and Time Warner Inc.
   The ruling last week by Chancery Court Judge William Allen said
the terms of a class of Warner preferred stock held by a Chris-Craft
subsidiary, BHC Inc., did not entitle Chris-Craft to vote on the
merger of the two media giants.
   A Chris-Craft attorney, Charles S. Crompton Jr., said the company
was asking the Delaware Supreme Court to overturn the ruling on the
ground Allen had inaccurately interpreted the terms of the stock.
   A three-judge panel of the state's highest court was to hear
arguments in the case on Oct. 18 in Dover.
   Allen ruled in response to a request for a declaration of
Chris-Craft's rights by Warner and Time Warner, who want the issue
resolved so they can consummate their merger.
   Time Inc. completed a $14 billion tender offer for Warner in
July, and then changed its name to Time Warner Inc. The companies
hope to finalize their merger later this year.
   A decision by Allen, later upheld by the state Supreme Court,
threw out a challenge to the merger by Paramount Communications
Inc., which had sought to acquire Time Inc. for $12 billion.
   In his latest decision, Allen said that under the terms of the
stock Chris-Craft does not ``possess a veto over every merger in
which its interests would be adversely affected.''
   Chris-Craft contended it had a right to vote on the merger
because its preferred Warner shares can be converted into preferred
Time Warner shares.
   Warner and Chris-Craft Chairman Herbert Siegel have been feuding
since Chris-Craft helped Warner fend off an unwanted takeover bid
from publisher Rupert Murdoch in 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1708EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-15 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Panicky Domestic Dealings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply Friday in panicky
domestic dealings characterized by wild rumors and price swings,
erasing gains posted in earlier foreign trading.
   Gold prices were mixed. On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold
bullion for current delivery jumped to $363.90 a troy ounce, up
$3.40 from Thursday. Republic National Bank quoted a late bid for
gold of $362.50 an ounce, up from $359.35.
   The dollar rallied sharply in foreign trading, climbing above the
benchmark 2.00 level against the West German mark following a
better-than-expected report on the U.S. trade deficit.
   The Commerce Department said the deficit narrowed to a seasonally
adjusted $7.58 billion in August from a revised $8.01 billion in
July, shocking a market that had expected a $9 billion shortfall.
   But traders at home said the euphoria was short-lived. By
mid-afternoon, the market was hit with a string of outrageous rumors
ranging from the assassination of President Bush to the failure of
Wells Fargo &amp; Co.
   ``With the slew of rumors, the dollar came screaming off,'' said
Kevin Lawrie, a vice president at the Bank of Boston's New York
office. ``It was scary.''
   Within an hour, the dollar plunged 6 pfennigs against the West
German mark.
   ``That's a pretty dramatic move,'' said Earl Johnson, a vice
president at Harris Trust and Savings Bank in Chicago. ``We were
sitting at 2.00 marks _ it was a wild and crazy day.''
   One by one the rumors were denied, which helped pick the dollar
up from its lows. But Lawrie said many investors had been ``scared
enough today to step out of their positions and take a breather.''
   The central banks joined forces to sell dollars throughout the
day, and ultimately traders welcomed the move for smoothing out the
dollar's decline.
   The session's extreme volatility has forced technicians to revise
their trading ranges. ``It will be a while before we test 2.00 marks
again,'' Johnson said.
   Fundamentally, dealers noted that the trade report showed a
decline in both imports and exports, perhaps pointing to a weakening
economy and lower interest rates, which do not bode well for the
dollar.
   The yen was not traded Friday in Tokyo, where markets were closed
for a holiday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 148.65 yen,
compared with Thursday's closing price in Tokyo of 145.85 yen. In
New York, the dollar closed at 146.35 yen, down from 146.85 yen on
Thursday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5390 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5582 late Thursday. In New
York, it cost $1.5660 to buy one pound, more expensive than
Thursday's $1.5540.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.9660 West German marks, down from 1.9750;
1.6945 Swiss francs, down from 1.7040; 6.6295 French francs, down
from 6.6615; 1,410.50 Italian lire, down from 1,418.50, and 1.1848
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1850.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 2.0005 West German marks, up from 1.9705; 1.7260
Swiss francs, up from 1.7000; 6.7430 French francs, up from 6.6485;
2.2490 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2185; 1,433.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,413.00; and 1.1880 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $356.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $362.00. In Zurich, gold fell to
$356.00 an ounce from $361.75 late Thursday. Hong Kong's gold market
was closed Friday for the Chinese mid-autumn festival.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $5.084 an ounce from $5.055 Thursday. In
London, the metal was trading at a late bid of $5.03 a troy ounce,
compared with Thursday's $5.12.
</TEXT>
