<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-15 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Rise on Late Buying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices resumed their upward climb
Friday after one trader entered the gasoline market in late
afternoon and sparked activity in crude and heating oil futures.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 24 cents to $19.96 a 42-gallon barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline picked up 0.94 cent to
close at 57.61 cents a gallon and home heating oil for October
delivery rose 0.91 cent to settle at 55.95 cents a gallon.
   On Thursday, energy futures, which have rallied in recent weeks,
paused for a round of profit-taking, and for much of Friday's
session, the market was quiet.
   However, in late afternoon, one trader began buying the October
contract for gasoline, and ``ran it up to a level where they got
everyone else's interest,'' said Greg Dreis, an analyst with Merrill
Lynch Energy Futures.
   ``Crude and heating oil had to come up with it,'' Dreis said.
   There were no news developments to influence trading, he said.
</TEXT>
