<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-15 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rumors Wrench Gold Market, Which Ends Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices made strong gains Friday on New York's
Commodity Exchange after being wrenched back from three-year lows by
unfounded rumors that President Bush had been shot and that a major
U.S. bank was near collapse.
   ``From what we can see it was purely rumor-driven,'' said John
Jonat, a metals trader with Deak International Inc.
   On other markets, energy futures advanced; grains and soybeans
were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $3.40 higher across the board with the
contract for delivery in October at $365.20 a troy ounce. Silver
futures were 2.7 cents to 2.9 cents higher with September at $5.084
a troy ounce.
   Analysts said the moves in the metal markets were mainly
reactions to the dollar, which strengthened early in the day
following positive reports on inflation and the trade deficit, then
collapsed in the afternoon amid the wild rumors.
   ``We had a complete reversal,'' said Craig Sloane, a metals
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``The
dollar went through what was described as a free fall.''
   The market gave more credence to the talk of an impending bank
collapse than to the rumors about Bush, analysts said, because the
financial markets already were jittery about the credit troubles of
retailing giant Campeau Corp.
   For the gold market, which has been weakening gradually for
months, the turnaround could mark a turning point, Sloane said.
   ``New lows were made and then you came up with a higher close on
the day. That could be considered a key reversal,'' signalling the
start of a major bull move, he said.
   Energy futures also rallied late in the session on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, more than offsetting the significant
technically inspired losses that had accrued earlier in the week.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 19 cents to 26 cents
higher with October at $19.96 a barrel; heating oil was .74 cent to
.91 cent higher with October at 55.95 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .74 cent to .90 cent higher with October at 57.50 cents
a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade in a quiet session marked by a lack of significant
supply-and-demand developments.
   The corn market weakened late in the session when confirmation of
a rumored Soviet corn purchase failed to materialize.
   Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s floor
operations at the exchange, said the speculation was premature.
   ``I think the Russians are going to be significant buyers of U.S.
corn ... but not at this time,'' he said. ``You buy during the
harvest, not before the harvest. You don't get the lowest prices
right now.''
   Corn harvesting has begun but won't get into full swing for
another week, he said. The peak of the soybean harvest is still two
weeks away.
   Wheat futures settled 2 cents lower to 3 cents higher with
September at $3.88} a bushel; corn was 2\ cents lower to 1\ cents
higher with September at $2.35 a bushel; oats were { cent lower to
2{ cents higher with September at $1.37 a bushel; soybeans were 2
cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $5.83{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in a day of profit-taking following Thursday's fierce
rally, which was prompted by proposals to include pork products in a
food-aid package to Poland.
   Live cattle futures settled .07 cent lower to .45 cent higher
with October at 72.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent
lower to .05 cent higher with September at 83.37 cents a pound; hogs
were .32 cent to .55 cent higher with October at 40.97 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher
with February at 48.25 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
