<FIRST>r f AM-MinorityBroadcasters     09-15 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minority Broadcasters,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minority Broadcast Rules Need Congressional Protection, Senate Panel
Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Communications Commission rules that
have increased minority and female ownership of radio and TV
stations need congressional protection from recent attacks in the
courts and from the FCC itself, a Senate panel was told Friday.
   Minority and women broadcasters said they had made great strides
in gaining licenses during the 1970s when the rules were established
to ease their entry, but that progress slowed under the Reagan
administration during the early 1980s.
   The Republican-led FCC ``began a concerted attack upon minority
ownership polices. ... Eight years after the Reagan administration
took office there are only 160 radio stations and 15 television
stations'' owned by blacks, which represents 2 percent of all
stations, said James L. Winston, executive director of the National
Association of Black Owned Broadcasters.
   Congress in 1988 ordered the FCC to stop reconsidering the
minority and female preference rules, but the rules suffered a major
blow earlier this year when a court declared part of them
unconstitutional.
   Witnesses urged the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation
communications subcommittee to write the FCC rules into law to
protect them from constitutional attack.
   Subcommittee chairman Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, said his
staff was preparing such legislation.
   ``In the Reagan years, the FCC got on the wrong track,'' Sen.
Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., the full Commerce committee chairman,
said in written testimony. ``While it used fancy words and phrases
to claim these policies were unconstitutional, we knew all along it
simply did not support the spirit of these policies.''
   Hollings said a Senate appropriations subcommittee this week
included a provision in an FCC appropriations bill that would
maintain the rules.
   The FCC rules, first adopted in 1973, give preference to
minorities and women in license renewal proceedings. In 1978, the
FCC added an important provision that gives a tax break to station
owners who sell to minorities.
   ``If the tax certificate policy is ever eliminated, minority
purchasers might as well disconnect their telephones, because they
will never get another call to purchase a station,'' Winston said.
   Another provision added in 1978 was the distress sale policy that
allows broadcasters facing license revocation to sell quickly to
minority groups for 75 percent of the fair value of the station and
end further FCC action against them.
   But the U.S. appeals court in Washington this year struck down
the policy, saying the FCC had not demonstrated there was a link
between minority ownership and a proliferation of minority
programming and that the agency had not demonstrated there is a
history of racial discrimination in broadcasting requiring the
preference policies.
   Less than a month later, however, another three-judge panel of
the court upheld the constitutionality of the female and minority
preference provisions.
   The lone witness testifying against codifying the rules was Alan
Shurberg, the Hartford, Conn., broadcaster who won the appeals court
test.
   Shurberg, who opposed a minority broadcaster who had won station
WHCT-TV in a distress sale, cited the court's view that without firm
evidence that would-be minority owners are subject to discrimination
when they try to buy stations, Congress should not intervene.
   He said minorities don't necessarily program for the benefit of
minorities once they've achieved their licenses, particularly if the
station is located in a market made up of primarily non-minority
listeners.
   ``Diversity is driven by the marketplace,'' Shurberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
