<FIRST>u f AM-Ralston-Beech-Nut     09-15 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ralston-Beech-Nut,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ralston to Buy Beech-Nut Baby Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co., the world's leading maker of
dog and cat food, is going into the baby food business.
   Ralston officials said Friday they had reached a tentative
agreement with Nestle Enterprises, Inc., to buy its Beech-Nut baby
food business, which has annual sales of about $150 million.
   Beech-Nut is the second largest maker of baby food in the United
States, far behind Gerber in the $1 billion baby food industry. The
deal does not include Beech-Nut gum, which is produced by another
company.
   ``Because there are a great many similarities between how some of
our products and Beech-Nut products are sold and marketed, we
believe this deal offers us some tremendous opportunities,'' said
Ralston spokesman Pat Farrell.
   Terms of the deal, which should be completed in 30 to 60 days,
were not disclosed, Farrell said.
   Beech-Nut, headquartered in Fort Washington, Pa., makes jarred
baby food, fruit juices and cereals in three plants around the
country, two in upstate New York and one in San Jose, Calif.
   The company has about 1,100 employees.
   Ralston, with annual sales of $5.8 billion, is best known for its
cat and dog chow, but the company also makes breakfast cereal, and
owns Continental Bakery, which makes Hostess snack cakes and Wonder
bread and is the largest wholesale baker in the country.
   The company also owns Everready Battery Co.
</TEXT>
