<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1755EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     09-15 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Up After Uneven Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices gyrated Friday before finishing
higher in a session dominated by mixed economic news and rumors.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond was up in early trading,
down slightly at midday, and back up by the close. It finished 15-32
point higher, or nearly $4.70 per $1,000 face amount. Its yield,
which falls when prices rise, fell to 8.07 percent from 8.12 percent
late Thursday.
   Analysts said bonds got their first boost from the Labor
Department's Producer Price Index, which showed wholesale prices
falling in August for the third consecutive month, down 0.4 percent.
But bonds dropped later when traders noted that excluding the
volatile food and energy sector, inflation actually rose 0.5 percent.
   Inflation is the enemy of bonds, which pay fixed interest.
   The bond market reacted uncertainly to long-awaited reports on
trade and factory output. The U.S. trade deficit narrowed in July to
$7.58 billion, the smallest gap since December 1984. Output at the
nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.3 percent in August.
   Several rumors of bad news also affected the market. Financial
markets are susceptible to rumors because many people trade on them
without taking time to see if they are true.
   By the end of the day traders decided that on balance the news
was good.
   ``What the market got was kind of an information overload,'' said
Robert Chandross, economist for Lloyds Bank PLC in New York.
``Overall the economic numbers confirmed we're not in a recession
and that growth is continuing at a respectable rate in the third
quarter.''
   Trading remained thin in the junk bond market, where lower-grade
issues have been hit by the cash crunch at the Federated Department
Stores Inc. and Allied Stores Corp. units of Canadian retailing
giant Campeau Corp.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments were up about 1-32 point, intermediate
maturities were up 3-32 to 3-16 point and long-term issues were up
close to { point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 1.89 to 1,183.49.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of
five years or longer, gained 1.06 to 331.79.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3-32 point to 92 11-16. The average
yield to maturity rose to 7.36 percent from 7.35 percent late
Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.76 percent as the
discount fell 5 basis points to 7.52 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 7.94 percent as the discount fell 2 basis points to
7.54 percent. Yields on one-year bills were unchanged at 7.98
percent as the discount remained at 7.45 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 9 1-16 percent, up from 8~ percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
