<HEAD>Mexican Company Extends Tender Offer Until Sept. 21</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vitro S.A. extended its $280 million takeover
bid for Anchor Glass Container Corp. a second time, but the
Tampa-based glass maker said Friday it still recommends stockholders
reject the $20-per-share offer.
   Anchor spokesman Tom Davies said the nation's No. 2 glass maker
is still conducting talks the others interested in acquiring the
company.
   Vitro extended its offer until 5 p.m. EDT Sept. 21. The previous
deadline was 5 p.m. Thursday.
   Vitro, based in Monterey, Mexico, made the takeover offer Aug. 9.
It was one of the first unsolicited bids by a Mexican company for a
major U.S. manufacturer.
   Vitro announced Friday it has tendered about 66 percent of the
13.9 million shares outstanding of Anchor.
   Anchor's stock was trading below $10 a share the week before the
Vitro offer. Anchor closed Friday at $18.50 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
