<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SatelliteAuction     09-15 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satellite Auction,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meat on the Hoof Offered By International Satellite Link</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyers in Australia, New Zealand, Mexico
and Canada can bid on Hereford cattle being sold here Sunday in what
is believed to be the first international satellite auction of
registered beef cattle, organizers said Friday.
   The first international satellite sale of registered beef cattle
will be beamed throughout the world and the United States to
television viewers who call in their bids to a telephone bank at the
auction here.
   ``We feel like this is going to be the way to go in the future,''
said Willard Wolf, the Northwest representative of the American
Hereford Association who proposed the satellite auction after
attending a similar ``sky bridge'' between U.S. and Australian wheat
farmers last January.
   Cattle ranchers in Australia, New Zealand, Canada, Mexico and the
United States can buy from 26 consignments of registered Hereford
bulls, heifers, semen and embryos by telephone and save the costs of
traveling to the auction, Wolf said.
   ``The price of an airline ticket would buy enough semen to
inseminate 20 cows,'' said Wolf, a Spokane rancher and co-chairman
of the event. ``This way, a breeder in Australia can make a $25
telephone call and save the cost of a ticket.''
   ``You no longer have to be in the heat of cattle country to have
a significant cattle sale,'' said Carey Hegreberg, program
coordinator and Spokane Area Chamber of Commerce representative.
   Sixty head of cattle from 11 states will be auctioned, as well as
frozen embryos and semen, said Wolf. Animals are expected to fetch
$2,500 to $20,000 apiece.
   Videotapes of animals not at the auction, or of bulls and cows
from which semen or embryos were taken, also will be shown, Wolf
said.
   The Foreign Agriculture Service of the U.S. Department of
Agriculture and a veterinary corporation gave the pilot project
grants of more than $12,000, Hegreberg said.
   A USDA analysis of the event will largely determine whether
similar grant money is available in the future, Hegreberg said,
noting skepticism among some agriculture interests.
   The satellite auction may help to cut through some regulations,
restrictions and politics surrounding livestock imports and exports,
Wolf said. Logistics of transporting the sale animals and other
items will be worked out between the sales manager and buyers, he
said.
   ``We're very excited about it and we hope it will become an
annual event,'' said Wolf. If the pilot program is a success, plans
for next year call for satellite sales in Japan, where there is
strong interest in both dairy and beef herds, Hegreberg said.
   Future satellite auctions would not be limited to cattle, and
other agricultural commodities could be offered for sale, said
Hegreberg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DallasNewspapers     09-15 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dallas Newspapers,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Injunction; Frees Universal to Pull Features</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge on Friday refused to prevent
Universal Press Syndicate from pulling 26 comics and other features
from the Dallas Times Herald until the newspaper's lawsuit against
its main competitor is resolved.
   Judge David West said the Times Herald did not prove it would be
irreparably harmed if it lost the features as a result of a deal
between Universal Press and A.H. Belo Corp., parent company of The
Dallas Morning News.
   ``They didn't prove to the judge's satisfaction that irreparable
harm would take place and at the time of trial the Herald would
likely prevail,'' West said.
   The order took effect immediately, but West said he would not
hold the Times-Herald in contempt if some Universal Press features
continue to appear in the newspaper for a few days. The judge said
he realized some of the features were printed ahead of time and
couldn't immediately be withdrawn.
   A Universal Press official testified that The Morning News has
agreed to run all 26 of the comics and columns in question, and Belo
spokeswoman Jodie Hughes said some of them will appear beginning
Monday.
   ``We're very pleased with the decision, and now we can move on,''
Ms. Hughes said. She declined further comment.
   Times Herald Editor Roy E. Bode said the newspaper will continue
to pursue its antitrust case.
   ``We will fully and vigorously peruse all available legal
remedies in an attempt to recover these features and all damages to
the Dallas Times Herald,'' Bode said in a prepared statement.
   ``We will continue our suit and continue to fight for fair
competition in Dallas with all our energies,'' he said.
   The judge issued his decision after attorneys asked him to
indicate how he was leaning. He said that although he was ruling
from the bench, he had given much thought to the decision.
   ``No one thinks a one-newspaper town is advantageous. I'm taking
this very seriously,'' he said.
   He asked attorneys to agree on a trial date later this year for
the antitrust suit and set a Nov. 6 hearing to decide whether the
case should be transferred back to Dallas.
   ``I think the evidence overwhelmingly showed that this was a
fantastic business opportunity for The Morning News,'' the paper's
attorney, Bill Sims, said after the ruling.
   The Times Herald suit accuses Belo of unfairly increasing its
influence in the Dallas media market.
   Belo last month formed a joint venture with Kansas City-based
Universal Press to develop some of the syndicate's features for
television. As part of the agreement, Belo _ which also owns Dallas'
top-rated TV station, WFAA _ acquired exclusive rights to Universal
Press material.
   Universal pulled its features from the Times Herald, but the
newspaper regained the right to print them under a temporary
restraining order issued by West on Sept. 5.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
