<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1839EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru f0228 09-15 0822</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0228,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>Good News: Prices Down, Production Up, Trade Gap Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 17th graf pvs, The various ... to CORRECT that index number
is before adjustment for seasonal variations, not inflation. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices declined for the third
straight month in August as a big new drop in energy costs helped
keep inflation in check, the government said Friday in releasing a
string of generally upbeat economic reports.
   The Labor Department said its Producer Price Index, which
measures costs one step short of the retail level, plunged 0.4
percent last month, matching the decline in July. The index had been
down 0.1 percent in June.
   It was the first time that wholesale prices had fallen for three
consecutive months since a four-month drop from January through
April, 1986.
   Adding to the good economic news, the government said that
production at the nation's factories rose in August at its fastest
clip in four months while the U.S. trade deficit in July fell to its
lowest level in nearly five years.
   President Bush said the various government reports showed that
the longest peacetime economic expansion in U.S. history was moving
forward, continuing ``to produce jobs for the American people.''
   Private analysts were generally enthusiastic as well, saying the
reports represented a victory for the Federal Reserve Board, which
has been trying at the same time to keep the recovery alive and
restrain inflationary pressures.
   ``From the Fed's viewpoint, all the news looks very good,'' said
David Wyss, chief financial economist at DRI-McGraw Hill. ``The only
danger is that Fed officials might sprain an elbow patting
themselves on the back.''
   While the trade report sent the dollar surging on foreign
currency markets, the stock market appeared unimpressed by the
favorable economic news, with the Dow Jones industrial average
rising 9.69 for the day.
   Prices on the bond market fell as traders focused not on the
overall 0.4 percent decline in wholesale-price inflation but in a
0.5 percent rise in inflation excluding the volatile energy and food
categories. This inflation figure is considered a better indication
of the economy's underlying inflation rate.
   While some private economists said the non-food, non-energy
inflation increase was worrisome, other analysts maintained that the
figure has had temporary monthly surges in the past without
signalling that the overall inflation rate was getting out of hand.
   ``Inflation is falling, not running away or accelerating as many
people have feared,'' said Lawrence A. Hunter, an economist at the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``Our forecasts indicate that inflation
will continue to decline.''
   The three-month string of declines in wholesale prices was
particularly welcome because it came after a surge in prices earlier
this year triggered by higher world oil costs and the lingering
effects on food supplies from last summer's drought.
   Wholesale prices were racing ahead at an annual rate of 9.4
percent from January through May. But, with prices falling since
June, the annualized inflation rate for the first eight months of
the year is a much more subdued 4.4 percent. For all of 1988,
wholesale prices rose 4 percent.
   In August, gasoline prices plunged 12.1 percent, their third
consecutive monthly decline, while natural gas prices dropped 5
percent and home heating oil costs fell 2.1 percent.
   Analysts said the good news on energy prices should soon be
coming to an end, however, given recent increases in crude oil
prices.
   Food costs posted a 0.3 percent rise in August, led by a 4.4
percent jump in beef prices and a 3.9 percent rise in the cost of
eggs. Prices of fruits, vegetables, chickens and turkeys all fell
during the month.
   The various changes left the Producer Price Index, before
adjusting for normal seasonal variations, at 113.3, meaning a
hypothetical marketbasket of goods costing $100 in 1982 would have
cost $113.30 in August.
   The Consumer Price Index, which measures retail-price inflation,
has also been moderating in recent months, with many economists
forecasting that the August report, due Tuesday, will show a slight
increase of around 0.2 percent.
   In the other economic reports Friday, the government said:
   _The merchandise trade deficit in July shrank by 5.3 percent from
the June figure to $7.58 billion, the smallest imbalance since
December 1984. The improvement reflected a 2.5 percent drop in
imports, which offset a 1.8 percent decline in U.S. export sales.
   _Industrial production rose 0.3 percent in August, the best
advance since a 0.7 percent rise in April. The gain was credited to
a rebound in mining after the end of a strike and a rise in
production at auto plants.
   _Business inventories in July climbed 0.6 percent while total
business sales were falling 0.9 percent. While rising inventories
and falling sales would normally be worrisome, economists noted that
August data was pointing to a rebound in sales, which should insure
that inventory levels stay at manageable levels.
</TEXT>
