<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 0006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-LincolnLawsuit     09-15 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lincoln Lawsuit,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Reportedly Preparing $1.1 Billion Fraud Suit Against Thrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are about to file a lawsuit
against Lincoln Savings and Loan Association seeking $1.1 billion in
damages from the failed thrift for alleged widespread fraud, experts
said Thursday.
   Several newspapers have reported that the Resolution Trust Corp.
would sue Lincoln, its parent American Continental Corp. of Phoenix
and officers of both companies.
   Stephen Pizzo, co-author of ``Inside Job,'' a book about fraud
among S&amp;Ls, said sources had told him the 150-page complaint was
readied six weeks ago but stalled when Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. lawyers took it to their counterparts in the Justice
Department for approval.
   FDIC spokesman David Barr in Washington denied knowledge of any
pending action against against the Irvine, Calif.-based thrift or
American Continental.
   The Resolution Trust Corp. was established under the sweeping
thrift bailout which President Bush signed into law Aug. 9.
   The Los Angeles Times and the Orange County (Calif.) Register
reported Thursday that the suit might invoke the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations statute, which allows triple
damages in civil cases.
   American Continental Chairman Charles H. Keating Jr. could not be
reached for comment Thursday. In the past the company has denied any
wrongdoing.
   The suit will allege misconduct in transactions involving a
tax-sharing plan, the high-yield corporate securities known as junk
bonds, a hotel in Detroit, a Dallas company and three Arizona
communities, Pizzo and others said.
   Federal regulators seized Lincoln on April 14. It now is under
control of the RTC, and analysts said the Lincoln crisis will be the
new agency's costliest bailout.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking
Committee, has said $1.5 billion had been lost ``in the Lincoln
fiasco'' and that discovery of further losses was inevitable.
   The government took over Lincoln the day after American
Continental filed for protection under federal bankruptcy law.
   Keating and his advisers also face a dozen class-action suits
filed by about 23,000 bondholders. American Continental has
responded by suing the Federal Home Loan Bank Board and FDIC to
remove Lincoln from federal conservatorship.
   In another development, a rating newsletter in Coral Gables,
Fla., listed Lincoln as the worst-performing thrift in the nation,
with $787.9 million in losses for the April-June quarter.
   Bauer Financial Reports Inc. said Lincoln accounted for 16
percent of the losses incurred by the 939 S&amp;Ls that ran in the red.
</TEXT>
