<TEXT>
   Federal regulators acting on behalf of a seized
California thrift filed a fraud and racketeering suit against the
founder of the thrift's parent company and numerous other
individuals, seeking $1.1 billion in damages.
   The suit was filed Friday against Lincoln Savings and Loan under
the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations statute. Charges
included negligence, breach of fiduciary duty and breach of contract.
   Lincoln Savings and Loan is a wholly owned subsidiary of American
Continental Corp. of Phoenix.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit narrowed to $7.58
billion in July, its lowest level in nearly five years, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that the July deficit dropped
5.3 percent from a revised June imbalance of $8.01 billion. The July
gap was the slimmest since a $6.79 billion imbalance in December
1984.
   In a separate report, the government said business inventories
climbed 0.6 percent in July, the biggest gain in three months, while
total business sales fell by 0.9 percent. Also, the Federal Reserve
Board said August production rose 0.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. said it would modify
its DC-10 jetliners to ensure safe landings even if all three
hydraulic systems fail.
   The modifications, developed in response to a DC-10 crash that
killed 112 people in Sioux City, Iowa, last July and announced
Friday, were greeted warmly by James B. Busey, the head of the
Federal Aviation Administration.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's takeover watchdog, recognizing the
increasingly international nature of the bidding process, has
allowed Hoylake Investments Ltd. more time for its $21 billion bid
for BAT Industries Inc.
   The Panel on Takeovers and Mergers said Friday it would allow
Hoylake to rebid for BAT after it obtains approval from U.S. state
insurance regulators to change the ownership of BAT's Farmers
Insurance Group Inc. of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the trial of D.L. ``Danny''
Faulkner and six others declared a mistrial after jurors said they
were hopelessly deadlocked in the largest savings and loan fraud
case.
   After deliberating for more than 16 days on the 88-count
indictment, jurors on Friday said they could not come to an
agreement.
   Faulkner and another defendant are accused of heading a
conspiracy to steal $135 million from Empire Savings and Loan
Association of Mesquite and four other S&amp;Ls in Texas and Arkansas in
1982 and 1983.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co., the world's leading maker of
dog and cat food, is going into the baby food business.
   Ralston officials said Friday they had reached a tentative
agreement with Nestle Enterprises Inc., to buy its Beech-Nut baby
food business, which has annual sales of about $150 million. Terms
were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
