<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern     09-15 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Gives Eastern Extension on Disclosure Statement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge on Friday gave
strikebound Eastern Airlines an additional 60 days to file a
disclosure statement for its bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   At a hearing, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland granted
Eastern's request that Friday's deadline for filing the statement be
extended to Nov. 13. The airline's unions opposed the request.
   If the deadline hadn't been extended, other parties would have
been free to file competing reorganization plans.
   Eastern has been under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since
March 9, five days after the start of a strike by pilots, Machinists
and flight attendants. The Miami-based airline filed its proposed
reorganization plan July 21.
   The disclosure statement will contain details on Eastern's
financial position, including 5-year projections, the company has
said. The statement will describe how Eastern intends to emerge from
bankruptcy.
   Eastern recently revealed to creditors that it will have about
$370 million less in cash by year end than first projected, having
abandoned a plan to sell its Latin American routes. The airline has
been renegotiating with its creditors the repayment terms to reflect
the anticipated shortfall.
   Eastern parent Texas Air Corp. appears set to underwrite some of
Eastern's obligations. In another hearing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court
this past week, Lifland approved a plan for payment of $98.3 million
Eastern owes to employee pension plans. Texas Air is lending Eastern
$45 million toward the payment, Eastern is paying $27 million with
the proceeds of asset sales, and the rest has been deferred until
July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
