<DOCNO> AP890915-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 1949EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Campeau 1stLd-Writethru   09-15 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campeau, 1st Ld-Writethru,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campeau, Olympia &amp; York Reach Conditional Agreement on Loan for Campeau</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The loan ... to include reference to loan
payments; INSERTS one graf after the 10th graf to include convertible nature
of loan, SUBS 11th graf with editing change to conform; picks up 12th graf,
Without the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. said Friday it had reached
conditional agreement with one of its major stockholders, Olympia &amp;
York Developments Ltd., on a $250 million loan to help the
struggling retail and real estate company meet interest payments due
on its bonds.
   However, Campeau was technically in default on one series of
bonds issued by its Allied Stores Corp. division. The company said
it was unable to make an interest payment on the bonds Friday.
   The Toronto-based Campeau said in a statement it had entered an
automatic 30-day grace period during which it could still make the
payment. Campeau said it had met a separate interest payment due on
another series of Allied notes.
   The loan from Olympia &amp; York would be used to provide cash for
Allied and Campeau's other retail unit, Federated Department Stores
Inc., to operate while Campeau refinances and restructures and to
meet their interest payments.
   The company said the loan from Olympia &amp; York was subject to
Campeau's bankers agreeing to several conditions, including
Campeau's securing from Citibank an extension until April 1990 of an
$800 million loan.
   Campeau said it was continuing negotiations with Citibank and the
other banks.
   The company announced last week that it was being forced to
restructure and put its prize Bloomingdale's department store chain
up for sale to cope with its massive debt, much of which was
incurred in the separate acquisitions of Allied and Federated.
   Campeau has approximately $11.5 billion in outstanding debt. Of
that amount, $3 billion is in short-term obligations, Carol Sanger,
a Campeau spokeswoman said from Cincinnati.
   Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York, which has a 24.5 percent stake in
Campeau, was expected to gain a larger interest in Campeau in
exchange for granting the loan. There has been speculation that
Chairman Robert Campeau, who owns nearly 54 percent of the
Toronto-based company, would relinquish his controlling interest.
   Ms. Sanger declined to confirm that Olympia &amp; York would increase
its interest in Campeau, but said the terms of the agreement between
the two companies would be announced when all details of the
restructuring were finalized.
   The Campeau statement described the loan as convertible, which
suggested the loan could be converted into stock in Campeau.
   The statement also indicated Olympia &amp; York would be taking an
active role in the management of the firm. Campeau said a management
group which was overseeing the restructuring would report to a
committe of directors, ``including representatives of minority
shareholders.''
   Without the loan from Olympia &amp; York, it appeared uncertain how
Campeau would be able to obtain credit so that its department stores
could stock shelves adequately before the crucial Christmas season.
   Campeau stock again did not trade Friday while the company
negotiated with Olympia &amp; York and its creditors. Trading in
Campeau's shares had been halted since Wednesday.
   Disclosure of the severity of Campeau's financial problems on
Wednesday rocked the market for high-interest ``junk bonds'' that
the company used to finance its buyouts of Allied and Federated and
contributed to a selloff in the stock market.
   The market waited Thursday and Friday for further word from
Campeau, but the lack of news kept the market on edge. Trading was
thin and dominated by rumors.
   On Thursday, Campeau reported a loss of $124 million in the three
months ended July 31 on revenue of $2.26 billion, compared to a loss
of $109 million and revenue of $2.21 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
