<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2002EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PSNHBankruptcy     09-15 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filing Deadline For Plans To Take Over PSNH Passes; 4 Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The struggle over control of New
Hampshire's largest electric utility settled on four companies
Friday as the deadline passed for filing bankruptcy reorganization
plans.
   Public Service Company of New Hampshire, which filed for
bankruptcy protection in January 1988, announced its plan to retain
control Tuesday and formally filed the proposal with the bankruptcy
court early Friday afternoon.
   Several hours later, United Illuminating of Connecticut became
the fourth to add its name to the list.
   Northeast Utilities, Connecticut's largest electric utility, and
New England Electric System of Westborough, Mass., filed their plans
earlier.
   The United Illuminating plan proposed a merger with Public
Service, the only plan to do so. It also called for electricity rate
increases of 5.5 percent a year for seven years for Public Service
customers, matching the rates proposed by Public Service and
Northeast Utilities if Seabrook operates.
   The New England Electric plan called for increases of 4.8 percent
during that period.
   New Hampshire Gov. Judd Gregg endorsed the Northeast plan when it
was introduced in July, but then switched allegiance this week to
New England Electric because of the lower rates.
   But Charles Bayless, Public Service financial vice president,
called his utility the favorite to retain control because its plan
already has the approval of shareholders and creditors. Public
Service also needs only state regulators approval for its plan, he
said.
   The other utilities still would have to reach agreement with
shareholders and creditors, and get approval from the Securities and
Exchange Commission and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission,
something Bayless said could prolong the bankruptcy case for two
more years.
   The fact that Public Service's payoff to creditors and
shareholders would be in securities while some of the other
proposals offered cash or a combination did not deter Bayless.
   ``To our creditors, getting paper in April is a heckuva lot
better than getting cash a year or two later,'' he said.
   The next step in the bankruptcy case will be hearings on the four
plans, which federal bankruptcy Judge James Yacos hopes to conclude
by mid-November. Then creditors and shareholders would vote on their
choice, and Yacos would make the final decision.
   Public Service, with almost 400,000 customers, filed for
bankruptcy under the burden of its 36 percent share of the $6.2
billion Seabrook nuclear plant. Negotiations have dragged on since
then for a reorganization plan that would satisfy creditors,
shareholders and the state.
   Public Service has the largest share of Seabrook, which has been
completed for three years, but has been unable to get a commercial
operating license. United Illuminating's 17.5 percent is the
second-largest share of Seabrook.
   New England Electric System and Northeast own smaller shares.
   United Illuminating valued its plan at $2.2 billion, matching the
value of the plan proposed by Public Service, regardless of whether
Seabrook operates commercially. New England Electric placed a $2
billion value on its plan if Seabrook runs, $1.9 if it does not.
Northeast valued its plan at $1.9 billion regardless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890915-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-89 2307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares     09-15 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Raise Some Discount Fares</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an apparent effort to soften the impact of
travel bargains offered to fall vacationers, several major airlines
have raised a type of discount fare popular with business travelers.
   This past week the airlines hiked ``Supercoach'' one-way fares,
favored by business fliers because they have more lenient
advance-purchase requirements than cheaper discount fares and don't
require a Saturday-night stay.
   The ``Supercoach'' fares, usually 15 percent to 40 percent below
standard economy fares, were raised by around $20 for a one-way
ticket.
   For example, United Airlines' lowest ``Supercoach'' fare from New
York to Minneapolis has been increased from $221 one way to $241. A
three-day advance-purchase fare on American Airlines from Dallas to
Boston was boosted from $269 to $289.
   The action appears aimed at recovering part of the revenue lost
from the big industrywide fare cuts for the fall season announced in
mid-August. At that time, the carriers extended summer travel
bargains and cut round-trip fares by as much as $160 to lure
passengers in the historically weak autumn season. Most fares to
Europe were reduced by $100 into next spring.
   But the latest increase's effect is akin to putting a finger in
the dike, some analysts believe.
   ``The carriers are desperately trying to salvage a very serious
problem that has occurred,'' said Julius Maldutis, who follows the
airline industry for Salomon Brothers Inc. ``They have had a massive
erosion in yield. ... Any fare actions that are taken now are
basically to stem the damage.''
   An airline's yield, which reflects the average price of a ticket
paid by a passenger for each mile flown, has become the name of the
game in the competitive climate of the nation's airline industry.
   The increase was started by Midway Airlines, an aggressive
mid-sized carrier based in Chicago that is paying $210 million to
buy 16 DC-9 aircraft, as well as gates and other airport facilities
in Philadelphia, Washington and New York from strikebound Eastern
Airlines. Midway upped its ``Supercoach'' fares Wednesday by $10 one
way.
   The bigger carriers, including United, American, Trans World
Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Continental Airlines and USAir Group
Inc., quickly matched the move. But they raised the fares by $20.
Some airlines raised ``Supercoach'' fares only in a few cities they
serve to match competitors, while others made widespread boosts.
   USAir spokesman David Shipley, for example, said that carrier was
increasing the fares in markets ``all over the country''. But Delta
is making the change only ``in a very, very few selected markets,''
said spokesman Jim Lundy.
   Eastern is ``considering some selective increases,'' said
spokesman Robin Matell in Miami.
   Continental, like Eastern a subsidiary of Texas Air Corp., had
proposed six weeks ago eliminating many ``Supercoach'' fares, but
the move wasn't matched by competitors and it dropped the idea.
   ``It was an effort on our part to simplify the one-way fare
structure,'' said Ned Walker, a Continental spokesman in Houston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
